<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTHERLAND LEADS WILD BUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Has there ever been a PGA Tour event with a
final-day leaderboard as wild as this one?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it could only happen in movieland, and even here this
script might be a tough sell:
</P>
<P>
   The leader is David Sutherland, who has never won a tour event,
is sponsored by a jellybean company and will step to the tee today
celebrating his 34th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing him _ at (begin ital)really(end ital) close range _ is
more than a third of the field, six of them a stroke back, 12 more
another stroke back and another 11 within three shots of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   That following pack of 29 includes a half-dozen of the world's
most celebrated players _ four of them winners of major
championships, the most notable being Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik, Fred Couples and David Duval are mixed among
the name-brand challengers chasing the candy man.
</P>
<P>
   If it were a movie, they might call it Willie Wonka's Wonderful
Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be something, it's going to be exciting,''
said Sutherland, who expects and looks forward to a large and loud
crowd with so many in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time somebody makes a long par putt, you're going to
think he made eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland earned his spot at the top of the pack by shooting
3-under-par 68 Saturday to get to 204 for the tournament, a stroke
better than Parnevik (67), Kirk Triplett (68), Brandel Chamblee
(69), Tommy Armour III (69) and midway co-leader Bob Tway (72).
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Mediate, who shot 64 for the best round of the day, also
is at 205 after making the best move of the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Nissan Open champion Couples (68) and two-time U.S.
Open champion Lee Janzen (69) are among a dozen players at 206,
including first-round leader J.P_. Hayes (72).
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval, the world's No.1 and 3-ranked players, both
shot 69 Saturday to get to 207 and will likely be among the
most-watched challengers today _ when Woods bids for his seventh
win in his last eight PGA Tour starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' said Sutherland, who has never
finished higher than second. ``Obviously I'm in good shape so far,
but I have not won six of my last seven tournaments. Golly, I
haven't won one tournament so far. So it's basically going to be an
exciting day for me. But I'll be honest. I'm trying to win this.''
</P>
<P>
   Why such a pack at the top?
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee offered a guess shared by many players:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the softness of the greens have a lot to do with it,''
he said. ``I think they had this course set up just the way they
wanted and then it rains. And when it rains like that the quality
of shot you need to stay on the greens goes down, so the course
doesn't separate people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows fast fairways and fast greens will separate
people, so that's my explanation. But it could be blind luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the pack, there's not much question
about who most of them are watching out for today:
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to expect something from Tiger,'' said Sutherland,
who finished 14th last week at the Buick Invitational, where Woods
got to 5-under par and erased a seven-stroke deficit despite
struggling with shots all day. ``It would be ridiculous to expect
he wouldn't play well. You've got to expect 67 or 66 if not
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who played in the same group with Woods on Saturday,
watched him struggle with a four-putt early in the round and then
regroup to record five birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's playing he can shoot pretty much zero around
here,'' Parnevik said. ``So I don't think anyone who's in the lead
is going to think it's a comfortable lead _ especially when you've
got 25-30 guys with a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who has struck the ball well all week but had problems _
as have many _ on damp greens that have been difficult for their
bumpiness, took his putting woes in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all right to hang in there to give myself a chance,'' he
said. His game plan for the anticipated bad weather?
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case,'' he said, ``I need to be patient, make a
lot of pars, hit a lot of solid shots and take my opportunities
when I have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for Woods are different than opportunities for
most touring pros. In each of his past two tournaments, he has
erased seven-stroke deficits in the final round _ the first time in
just seven holes, the next in eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what he can do,'' Chamblee said. ``You expect
spectacular stuff and every time he does it you say, `No way he can
do it again,' and the very next week he does it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee would like to make the most of that challenging
prospect: ``I'd like to be the one that he's trying to do it to.
I'd like to be the one he's trying to hole out a 6-iron to catch.
My hat's off to him if he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Double trouble: Woods posted a 6 on the par-4 No.13 for the
second consecutive round, and in similar fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Woods drove down the left side of the fairway and had a 10-foot
putt for birdie, but sent the ball three feet past the hole. He
missed that putt for par, then missed a two-footer for bogey. Woods
punctuated the hole by impaling the blade end of his putter into
the round behind the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' said Woods, who parred the hole in
the first round. ``I hit a perfect drive and a perfect little
9-iron in there, and made a good putt but just missed it on the
left. I hit another putt and again it broke to the right, not to
the left, which was the opposite of the way it was coming up. Then
the next one I just hit a bad putt, pulled it. Then I tapped in for
a nice little four-putt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
