<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Gooden-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Older and wiser, Gooden eyes fresh start
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ At 35, Dwight Gooden feels like a rookie all over
again, not a pitcher entering the twilight of a storied and
sometimes troubled career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fresh start for me,'' Gooden said Saturday as the
Astros held their first spring training workout.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, signed to a minor-league contract last month, spent his
first official day as an Astro shaking hands and introducing
himself to teammates (just call him ``Doc'').
</P>
<P>
   After a 3{-hour workout, Gooden pronounced himself as being ``in
the best shape in 10 years'' and anxious to rebound from last
year's struggles with the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his 16th major-league season _ with his third team in
four years _ the righthander holds no illusions of regaining the
magic that made him one of baseball's dominant pitchers in the late
1980s. But he believes he has a few years left in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think I can be a starter. Still, you have to go out
and show it,'' said Gooden, whose 188 career victories rank him
fourth among active pitchers behind Roger Clemens (247), Greg
Maddux (221) and Orel Hershiser (203). ``My main thing is to go out
and show them I'm healthy and can still get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   With inexperience and injuries clouding the bottom half of the
rotation, the Astros hope Gooden can fill the No. 4 or 5 spot. A
role in the bullpen also is being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Dwight Gooden we once knew. But he still
demands a lot of respect for what he has done in his career,''
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``When he walks into a
clubhouse, everybody turns around. There's something special in the
air.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden took the fast track to begin his career _ Rookie of the
Year at age 19, a Cy Young Award winner at 20, a member of the
World Series champion New York Mets at 21. He had his best season
in 1985, going 24-4 with a 1.53 ERA in becoming the youngest
pitcher to win a Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   After helping the Mets win the World Series in 1986, Gooden had
his promising career sidetracked by drug problems. He missed two
months of the following season while undergoing rehabilitation for
a cocaine problem.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, Gooden was banned from the final six weeks of
the 1994 season and all of 1995 after testing positive for cocaine,
eventually ending his 11-year stay with the Mets. While serving the
suspension he considered suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' Gooden said. ``The good times override the
bad times. Unfortunately I had some tough times off the field. I
think by doing that you try and bring the positives out of those
situations as best as you can and help others with the situations
that I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden returned to baseball in 1996, signing with the New York
Yankees, and pitched a no-hitter against Seattle. He spent the past
two seasons in Cleveland bothered by injuries, including a shoulder
strain that limited him to 22 starts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It got to a point last season that Gooden wondered if he was
approaching the end of his career quicker than expected. He was
left off the Indians' playoff roster and became a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of mixed reactions and you start wondering.
Deep down you keep telling yourself you still have it,'' he said.
``Last year for myself was a down year, probably the worst I had in
my career both on the field as well as mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden rededicated himself this offseason, enrolling at the
Bollettieri Academy in Bradenton, Fla. Each weekday, he worked
through a conditioning program with a personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulder feels the best it's felt in a long time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also spent time with his five children _ Dwight Jr. (14),
Ashley (9), Ariel (8), Devon (5) and Darren (3) _ and wife, Monica,
at their St. Petersburg, Fla., home. Dwight Jr. watched his dad
work out Saturday from the bleachers at Osceola County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season starts is when I get my rest,'' Gooden joked.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden could get more work than expected this season with the
uncertain physical status of Scott Elarton and the departure of
Mike Hampton, two of the Astros' top four starters when 1999 ended.
</P>
<P>
   However long the Astros have his services, some younger pitchers
plan to soak in the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting today I was getting tips from him how to prepare
yourself after a bad outing,'' Jose Lima said. ``It will be great
for me to hang out with him because he can teach me a lot of
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden listed the opportunity to play for a playoff contender, a
return to the National League and the opening of Enron Field as
reasons for signing with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely a plus at this stage in my career,'' he
said. ``I thought it was a great fit for myself. Hopefully, I'd
like to finish my career here. I think I have at least three more
years.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
