<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FALL TO BULLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- Just when it appeared the Clippers had met an
occasion they could rise to, the NBA's sleeping midget hit the
snooze button and rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   Even the presence of new assistant coach Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
seemed to be no cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a lot of practice,'' the NBA's all-time leading scorer
said after an initial review of his new pupils. ``We're already out
of the playoffs, so we're pointing for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar figured this thing out in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, with all sorts of nasty numbers in their un-hip pockets,
the Clippers coughed up an 11-point, third-quarter lead Saturday
night and continued their impressive moonwalk through the NBA
standings by losing to the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The final count was 74-72 before a noisy sellout crowd of 22,241
at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   This event was littered with more ugly numbers than your
bathroom scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two teams at the bottom of the league, both teams fighting it
out,'' said Clippers interim coach Jim Todd, who could have been
describing a chicken showdown between Ford Pintos. ``Both teams
played great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That would qualify as spin.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls tied a league season low for field-goal percentage
(28.6) and won. The Clippers shot a robust 38.5 percent. They also
extended their overall losing skid to 10, pushed their streak of
road defeat to 16, lost for the eighth time in the eight games Todd
has been their head coach and were beaten for the 25th time in 27
games.
</P>
<P>
   In the crucial Rookie-of-the-Year derby, Clipper Lamar Odom had
19 points (8 of 14 from the field) and 8 rebounds, while Bulls
forward Elton Brand, last year's top pick, had 18 rebounds and 13
points (6 of 23 from the field).
</P>
<P>
   For the Clips, it may be a lose-win situation, after all.
</P>
<P>
   By losing to the Bulls (12-38), the Clippers (11-42) took a
giant leap toward earning enough Ping-Pong lottery combinations to
secure the first pick in the 2000 draft. The Bulls, who heaved Toni
Kukoc overboard last week, have sabotaged their run for draft
supremacy by winning two in a row.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked dicey.
</P>
<P>
   When point guard Troy Hudson (22 points, 8 assists, 6 rebounds)
cherry-picked a layup at 7:35 of the third quarter, the Clips held
a 53-42 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They were caught at 63, when Chicago sub Chris Carr (19 points)
nailed two free throws at 4:36 of the fourth quarter. Abetting the
Clipper collapse was a hideous-looking fall by power forward
Maurice Taylor, who hopped to the locker room with 10:12 left to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was blown,'' Taylor said, referring to his left
knee, not the game. The fall made the injury look worse than it
was. ``It's more of a hyperextension than a sprain. I thought I was
done.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates weren't exactly finished until the final buzzer,
when Hudson shot a 21-footer from 22 feet. The air ball was fired
after the Clippers called time out and set up a play with 1.8
seconds remaining. This was the closing gasp in a last-minute chain
of events that included Eric Piatkowski mishandling an in-bounds
pass and the Bulls going stone cold at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in range,'' Hudson said of the final shot that could
have given his team a 75-74 victory. ``If I thought I had time for
a rhythm dribble, I think I could have got it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
