<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Elliott doggedly works way back after transplant
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ After Sean Elliott underwent a kidney transplant
last summer, his teammate, Avery Johnson, told him to live happily
ever after.
</P>
<P>
   He told Elliott to retire gracefully and happily. Enjoy life.
There no longer was anything out there he needed to prove. The NBA
championship finally was his, but more, so was personal redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who once was considered a nice player in the most cruel
of ways, had risen above it all. After falling victim to the NBA's
most feared four-letter word _ soft _ he swatted away the too-nice
label with the softest of shots in an unforgettable gritty moment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Memorial Day Miracle, a single flash of brilliance
and heart that forever exorcised Elliott's demons and etched his
name among the game's great heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The miraculous shot came in the waning seconds of Game 2 of the
Western Conference finals, as the Portland Trail Blazers threatened
to steal home-court advantage and yet again break Spurs hearts.
Elliott found himself in the middle of a frenetic moment, trapped
deep in the corner of the floor at the Alamodome as time was
ticking away.
</P>
<P>
   He took an inbounds pass from Mario Elie and turned toward the
basket only to find Blazers big man Rasheed Wallace rushing toward
him. He planted his feet, the heels of Elliott's shoes hanging over
the out-of-bounds line like something out of a LeRoy Neiman
painting.
</P>
<P>
   He lofted that soft shot of his and drained a 3-pointer that won
the game and ignited the Spurs' run to the NBA championship. It was
called a shot that sealed Elliott's fate as a warrior, but soon we
would find out that shot wasn't it at all.
</P>
<P>
   This is it. This is the warrior.
</P>
<P>
   This is Elliott's happily ever after: It's six months after the
kidney transplant and three hours before tip-off at the Alamodome.
Elliott is sprinting up the bleachers, grimacing and grunting all
the way, then bending over at the waist trying to grab one solid
breath of air.
</P>
<P>
   He runs the bleachers over and over again, before descending to
the floor to jump rope until his arms begin to tremble.
</P>
<P>
   He is virtually alone _ only a few stadium workers, a few
curious onlookers and the Spurs trainer watch him sprint and shoot,
jump and dunk.
</P>
<P>
   He sprints the length of the court for time, back and forth,
back and forth. He runs 20 sprints, then 10 more.
</P>
<P>
   He picks up a basketball and tosses it to the trainer, sprinting
sideline to sideline, taking passes and shooting 17-foot jumpers.
When he misses his last three shots in a row, Elliott screams and
kicks the ball in frustration, sending it some 30 rows into the
Alamodome stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, come on!'' Elliott yells at himself. ``Hit those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He stops and cranes his head back, putting the tips of two
fingers on his throat to monitor his pulse. He shoots free throws,
then runs some more, slashing through the lane for dunks. Finally,
his legs go almost numb and all he can do is pitch layups.
</P>
<P>
   No one said happily ever after was going to be easy. But this is
Elliott's happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   To play basketball again. To prove something to himself, instead
of someone else.
</P>
<P>
   To show transplant patients the world over that you can't
measure heart by counting the number of functioning kidneys inside
a person's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a challenge that I want to accept,'' Elliott, 32,
said. ``I don't want it to defeat me. I'm not going to let it
defeat me. I have to prove I can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   He is.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming practically frail six months ago, losing 20
pounds in a matter of weeks after the end of the Spurs' glorious
season, Elliott began taking small steps back to the game he loves
in November.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, he began practicing again with the Spurs, just five
months after all the energy that defined his game for a decade was
zapped.
</P>
<P>
   He would eat one bowl of fruit all day, then lie in bed for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite place was lying down,'' he said. ``I couldn't do
anything. I had no energy, no desire to get out of bed or do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He underwent the transplant Aug. 24 because of something called
focal segmental glomerular sclerosis. He thanked God for his
brother, Noel, who donated the kidney, often picking up the phone
and asking his brother, ``Are you sure you want to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're my brother,'' Noel would respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't scared about the surgery because the doctors and
nurses were so good,'' Elliott said. ``But it was something that I
knew was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks during the Spurs' championship run a year ago,
Elliott, his family and Spurs teammate Steve Kerr were the only
ones who knew just how serious and fatiguing the condition was and
that it was worsening by the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how I felt and it wasn't real good, but I wanted to
play with it as long as I could,'' Elliott said. ``I knew I needed
a transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 2 against Portland, the protein levels in Elliott's
urine were dangerously high, as was his blood pressure. Doctors
told Elliott not to play because his kidneys were not functioning
properly and he was placing himself in serious danger.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he hit maybe the biggest shot in the history of the
franchise, and in Game 5 of the title-clinching series against the
Knicks, there was Elliott once again with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 5 Elliott heard criticism for ``disappearing''
defensively against Knicks scorer Allan Houston, but he refused to
mention his condition. Elliott spent most days lying in bed during
the series, hardly eating, and retaining water in his legs, face
and neck because of his condition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the Knicks took their last shot in Game 5, it was
Elliott that hustled to the baseline in front of the Knicks'
Latrell Sprewell, forcing Sprewell under the basket and into a bad
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell missed and the Spurs were NBA champions. Elliott hopped
into David Robinson's arms after the buzzer and in the jubilant
locker room afterward, he was seen hugging the championship trophy
as tears filled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Elliott rode a barge along the San Antonio River
in the victory parade. What the NBA world didn't know was that
after the parade, Elliott went to the hospital for kidney dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, after the transplant, Johnson told Elliott he never
wanted to see him in a uniform again.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Spurs visit Compaq Center tonight to face the
Rockets, even if Elliott will not be in uniform, it's only a matter
of time.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Elliott's attempt to become the first
transplant patient to play professional sports is complete, except
for the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, frankly, have worried about Elliott attempting such a
comeback almost from the day he was discharged from the hospital
late in August. But Elliott has stayed determined.
</P>
<P>
   When he got home from the hospital after the transplant, he
promised doctors he would stay in bed. But he went to the foot of
the staircase in his house and tested himself, walking up and down
a single stair until he became dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   It seems everyone around him has told Elliott no, don't try this
_ the league, agents, lawyers, the players association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've signed 200 waivers,'' Elliott said. ``I
understand. I'm the one pressing the issue, not them. But I'll keep
signing the waivers until they let me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, Elliott circled Feb. 18 on the calendar as the day
he wanted to return to the floor _ Friday's game in San Antonio
against the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have played 10 minutes,'' he said, ``but I guess I
haven't signed enough waivers yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs coach Gregg Popovich has called himself a ``mother hen''
when it comes to Elliott's attempted return. But no longer is it a
matter of if, but when. And Spurs players that have scrimmaged with
Elliott say his skills are better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   He gobbles small mounds of pills every morning and works out
twice a day, lifting weights, running, shooting, dunking. He plays
livelier than before and his brittle knees are holding up nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing in awe looking at Sean,'' Robinson said. ``Here's
a man you know, the paycheck is going to be there. It's not like
he's doing it for the money. He's hanging in there, coming back
from a life-threatening surgery, and he just wants to be on the
floor. Every time I see a guy like that and see that kind of
passion, it just gives me energy. I realize how fortunate we are to
do what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's win over the Rockets, Elliott was slumped
against the scorer's table after running a series of drills and
sprints, when a man in his mid-40s called his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean, I have to tell you something,'' the man said. ``I gave
my sister my kidney two years ago. You're special, Sean. God bless
you, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' Elliott told the man, asking, ``How's your sister
doing? Tell her I'm with her.''
</P>
<P>
   This is his happily ever after. Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been to a city yet where someone hasn't come up to
me like that,'' Elliott said. ``They ask me, `What can I expect?
How's my surgery going to be? Were you scared?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's motivated me even more to do this. I want people to look
at me and say, `Look, it's going to be all right. Look how he's
doing.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the Spurs' locker room after a recent workout, Elliott took
off his jersey to show the eight-inch scar on the lower right side
of his abdomen, rubbing his hand across the scar and laughing,
``Nice, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   He has nothing to prove. He has a championship ring. He's proved
himself to everyone, but this is for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show what's possible for organ recipients,'' Elliott
said. ``Anything's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
