A2666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN--FRANBLINEBURY-HN     02-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--FRAN </SLUG>
 BLINEBURY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lima keeps time in his own world
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The little slugger stands barely as tall as
the top of a catcher's shin guards but is unafraid to call out when
the walking giggle machine saunters by on his way to the next
workout station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' shouts the kid with the round face and the brown
hair. ``Could I please get a baseball?''
</P>
<P>
   And Jose Lima stops dead in his tracks, turns to look at where
the tiny voice came from, then squats down at eye level and gives a
conspiratorial wink before rolling a ball into those hungry little
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Another gleeful convert whose clock has been reset to Lima Time.
</P>
<P>
   It is a state of mind somewhere between Margaritaville and a
parakeet who's lost in a marijuana field. And following a season in
which you didn't think Lima could get much higher on life, here he
comes on the first day of spring training like a mountain climber
who just found a set of stairs at the top of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best day ever,'' Lima says.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's the newest one.''
</P>
<P>
   We've all been searching for several years to find a chink in
this armor of perpetual giddiness, so far unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
   There he is, pulling up to the front of the Astros' training
complex in a carload of buddies, music playing, a modern-day
minstrel who provides his own soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   There he is on one of the diamonds, working on a drill that
involves fielding ground balls and covering first base, and he's
keeping a running, one-sided dialogue with coach Matt Galante, who
is swinging the bat.
</P>
<P>
   There he is inside the clubhouse, talking to everyone, singing
to no one, letting fly with jokes and one-liners in two languages
and laughing out loud even when nobody else understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is wonderful,'' Lima says. ``Every day I get to put on a
baseball uniform and they call it a job. Are you kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Sarasota, Ken Griffey Jr. will hold what is being
billed as his only news conference of the spring. The Cincinnati
Reds have sent out detailed instructions on where Griffey and the
media will sit and how the session will run, probably looking more
like a presidential briefing. So many dour, rich young men in
sports these days.
</P>
<P>
   To talk with Lima, all you have to do is be in the same area
code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how the sun is shining and there are old people and
young people and everybody is here to see baseball,'' he says. ``I
couldn't wait to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say Lima didn't enjoy a winter that had him
coming off a 21-win season and signing a three-year contract worth
$18.75 million. He spent time at home in the Dominican Republic,
where the $1.3 million, 7,000-square foot house he had built for
his mother was completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told my mother that someday I was going to buy her a
mansion,'' Lima says. ``Man, to see the look on her face the day
she moved in, you don't put any price tag on that. Now, no matter
what might happen to me, I can say I did the thing I wanted to do
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He also spent time at home in Houston, playing golf, eating at
his favorite restaurant, Hooter's, and enjoying his celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to be out there in the crowds, talking to the people
who support the Astros, who make it possible for me to have this
life,'' he says. ``I talked to kids groups, told them to stay in
school, to say no to drugs, to be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get tired of it. When I talk to some of the fans who
tell me that they have been coming to the Astros games for 20 or 30
years and say that they really appreciate what I bring, that
they've never had anybody like me here, man, that gives me goose
bumps. Look, right here on my arms.''
</P>
<P>
   He won 16 games in 1998 and some called it a fluke. So he went
out and won 21 in 1999 and earned the big contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now he reads a comment in Baseball Weekly that says Lima can't
keep it up and he shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to prove people wrong,'' Lima says. ``Been doing it for
so much of my life. Man, there were all those years when I came to
camp and had to fight just to win a job, to keep my career going.
So this is nothing at all to me. They say I can't win 20 again?
Well, we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be just a thrower. Now I'm a pitcher and I know what
I can do. Just watch.''
</P>
<P>
   So you watch and listen and marvel and wonder if there are ever
any bad days in Lima Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he says. ``That's when I get on the phone to my wife
or my mother or my agent. The world will never see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially not now, when the sun is so bright, the sky is so
blue, the grass is so green, the game is so fresh and it's the best
day ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until tomorrow,'' Jose Lima says.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
