<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-USC-LADN     02-20 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC LOSES, THEN BRAWLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ USC's NCAA hopes are evaporating thanks to a
listless performance against Arizona State, but the Trojans put up
a much better fight after the game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the Trojans' 93-81 loss to the Sun Devils
before 11,534, a brawl involving both teams broke out that lasted
about two minutes and included Arizona State students charging the
court before order was restored.
</P>
<P>
   The main participants were USC guard Jeff Trepagnier and Arizona
State forward Awvee Storey, although USC guard Malachi Thurston and
Arizona State forward Tanner Shell were also seen throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 100 people on the court by the time the
teams finally dispersed and went to the locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what caused the melee depended on whom you spoke with.
USC said Storey hit Trepagnier as the teams were walking off the
court. Arizona State said Trepagnier hit Storey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids saw Storey hit Jeff. The guy took shots all night,''
USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``The kid said something to Jeff and
jumped at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier was less clear about what happened: ``He came up and
there was a squabble.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Storey threw a punch, Trepagnier said: ``I don't know.
I can't remember. I was just trying to protect myself. He got in my
face.''
</P>
<P>
   But the USC players were aware Trepagnier threw a punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear Jeff threw a pretty good one at him,'' guard Nate Hair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Storey said he never threw a punch at Trepagnier: ``I got
cheap-shotted. I didn't see it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is if the Pacific-10 Conference, sure to
investigate the incident, will decide to suspend any of the
participants.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the two schools involved will agree on what
happened, based on the remarks of the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a situation like that in all my years of
coaching,'' Arizona State coach Rob Evans said. ``It just kind of
shows what kind of team they are. They tried every way to get us
unfocused but we wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bibby: ``I know the whole game my guys were getting hit
hard. Jeff got hit real hard. There was nothing called in the game.
Somebody has to see two elbows thrown at him during the game.
Storey threw one and (Eddie) House threw another. But that's what
their strategy was, to grab and hold us.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier had a swollen lip after the game, which he said was
the result of a House elbow. Storey also had a swollen lip.
</P>
<P>
   The game was definitely physical. There were 58 fouls called (32
on ASU, 26 on USC), and two Trojan starters (Trepagnier and Kostas
Charissis) fouled out. Storey also fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds for discontent had been planted well before the game.
Bibby was upset over the physical nature of last month's contest at
the Sports Arena, when Sam Clancy broke his foot and Jarvis Turner
broke his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such a catastrophe in my life,'' Bibby said.
``We know they're fouling every time down the court and the
officials let it get out of hand. It's terrible. This is what you
have when they do that altercations.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State became perturbed Friday afternoon when its
practice at the Student Recreation Center was delayed more than 45
minutes because USC's practice ran longer than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was stuff written on basketballs, and we had shootaround
an hour late,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are classless,'' added House, who scored a game-high 28
points. ``I lost all respect for them the way they handled
themselves at the end of the game. The way they were talking during
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Right after the altercation, Bibby, USC athletic director Mike
Garrett, Evans and Arizona State athletic director Kevin White
discussed the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was reasonable. It was really professional,'' Garrett
said. ``The game was over and we decided, `Let's come to an
appropriate response.' It was resolved with handshakes.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the game, the Trojans (13-11, 6-6) once again seemed to
fade, building a 23-12 lead that shrank to 39-38 at halftime.
Arizona State (16-9, 8-5) then had a 12-0 run in the opening
minutes of the second half to take a 52-43 lead. USC cut the lead
to three points (57-54), but a 12-4 ASU spurt pretty much put the
game away.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans shot 37.7 percent from the field, and their starting
guards Trepagnier and Brandon Granville were 9 for 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they outplayed us,'' Bibby said. ``They wanted it
more than we did. They played harder.''
</P>
<P>
   What it means is simple: The Trojans must win five of their
final six games if they hope to earn an NCAA bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an even bigger sense of urgency now,'' Bluthenthal
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
