<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2669 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     02-20 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHERE'S TIGER?' IS BIG QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As a ragtag army of tournament leaders trudges
into the final round of the Nissan Open, the question is what will
strike Riviera first today, that Pacific storm or Hurricane Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   A chance of sprinkles this morning is in the forecast, a chance
of rain this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Tiger warning is in effect for Greater Pacific
Palisades.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have the impression the rest of the players on the PGA
Tour keep talking about Tiger Woods only because The Media keep
asking about him. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   With six wins and a second-place finish in his past seven
tournaments, Tiger hangs over his opponents, a cloud packing
thunder and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the leaders Saturday as they knock the mud off their
spikes, tip their caps back on their heads and try to forecast the
next 18 holes (or however many holes the weather permits).
</P>
<P>
   David Sutherland, the bespectacled Sacramentan who leads by a
stroke at 9 under par, having followed a 67 Thursday and a 69
Friday with a 68 Saturday, talks about his chances of completing
his first PGA Tour victory today. He says he'll try not to glance
at a leader board until the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to expect something (great) from Tiger,''
Sutherland volunteers. ``A 65, 66, maybe better.'' He laughs --
uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett, the steady but winless Washington state native
who is one of six men tied for second, a stroke behind Sutherland,
is asked if the conditions might favor any particular type of
golfer today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean like Tiger Woods?'' Triplett says.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I don't mean Tiger, but if you insist ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all conditions suit him,'' Triplett says.
</P>
<P>
   Brandel Chamblee, among those tied for second, is asked what
sort of score might win today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't rain but it's windy, 8 or 9 under par can win
this tournament,'' Chamblee says. ``Where's Tiger? Six (under)?
(Then) 12 under ( can win it).''
</P>
<P>
   And so on. When none of the leaders seems inclined to take
control, everybody looks toward Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Daily News' Karen Crouse was interviewing Hal
Sutton's college coach, Floyd Horgen, who was on the phone from
Montana. She told him Sutton was five strokes behind leader J.P.
Hayes after the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did Tiger shoot?'' came the reply from Montana.
</P>
<P>
   After three rounds, 19 players are within two strokes of the
lead. Next on the list, tied for 20th with nine others, including
David Duval, is you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is three strokes off the lead despite a four-putting the
13th hol e Saturday. He wouldn't loom as such a threat if anybody
else had taken full advantage of what have seemed like perfect
conditions the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of golfers are shooting low scores, but none is making
like Ted Tryba, who was 13 under par when he began the final round
of the 1999 Nissan with the lead (only to finish tied with Woods
for second behind winner Ernie Els).
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels to me like 12 or 13 under should be leading,''
Triplett says of the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the good-but-not-great scores is the
swirling wind Saturday. Golfers would prefer a predictable gale to
swirling wind.
</P>
<P>
   Another is the overnight changes in the course. The par-3 sixth
hole, the one with the mid-green bunker, had its tee moved back 40
yards Saturday, and the par-4 12th got 35 yards longer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's that old Riviera scapegoat, the coastal grass known
as Poa annua, pronounced Po' Anna by the golfers. It grows on the
greens and makes them bumpy each afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the ball) looks like a basketball dribbling down there
once in a while,'' Triplett says. ``You become a little more
tentative (putting).' '
</P>
<P>
   The winner could turn out to be the player who's comfortable
enough wit h the final-round pressure to get aggressive with his
putts. And get lucky and hit the holes.
</P>
<P>
   Whom might that be?
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't physically come grab me and throw me down on the
fairway,'' Chamblee says of Tiger Woods. ``I'd like to be the one
he's trying to (beat), trying to hole a 6-iron to tie. My hat's off
to him if he does it. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
