<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES--LA     02-20 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE CASE WILL DRAG ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. -- Gene Orza, associate general counsel of the
players association, said Saturday the case of Dodgers third
baseman Adrian Beltre is at least a month from being resolved.
</P>
<P>
   While all parties involved eagerly await the announcement of
even a hearing date for the grievance, Orza said the process is
only in its infancy . Meanwhile, Dodgers managing general partner
Bob Daly said the club would sign Beltre to a multi-year contract
if ``it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is seeking free agency because the Dodgers signed him
before he turned 16.
</P>
<P>
   Orza said the player association was yet to file the stipulation
for the appeal. After that's done, the next step is to file briefs
for the case , he said. At that point, arbitrator Shyam Das sets a
hearing date, the players association and Major League Baseball
present their sides, and then Das makes a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be (started) until the John Rocker issue is
concluded, and that could be some time still,'' Orza said. ``The
time frame (for Beltre) has been moved back. I don't think you
should expect anything until the end of March.''
</P>
<P>
   That could put a heavy burden on the Dodgers. Word is spreading
through baseball that the Dodgers are confident the ruling will be
in their favor, but they are prepared to end the ordeal by signing
Beltre to a multi-year deal, if the price is right. Sources said it
would likely be a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be a reasonable situation,'' Daly said. ``I'm
prepared for this thing to go to a hearing. But I hope it gets
resolved. My wish is for this not to be an issue anymore. We would
do something (contract-wise) , but it has to be reasonable for the
Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Beltre, in the Dominican Republic readying for
Tuesday's reporting date, remained firm on his stance that he wants
to remain with the club. But because it's a legal case still
pending, he's been advised not to talk about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers treat me right,'' said Beltre, 20, who hit .275
with 15 homers and 67 RBI in `99. ``They play baseball the way I
like to play baseball. I don't think (the pending case) will affect
me. I don't think about it. All I have to do is get ready for
spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   With Das not expected to rule for more than a month, it leaves
Beltre's agent, Scott Boras, and the Dodgers with plenty of time to
still negotiate a deal. But the late date of the situation has the
Dodgers wondering what's taking so long. The case was first
presented in November, commissioner Bud Selig ruled in December and
the grievance was field in early January.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Dodgers are optimistic Beltre will remain with the
club, there is concern that if he's lost, they'll have only a week
to develop a platoon between Kevin Orie and Jose Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna optimistic: Fresh off a season in which Antonio Osuna
pitched in two more games than he had surgeries on his elbow (5 to
3), the right-hander beamed with optimism that he could be back by
openi ng day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Dodgers don't think so. They have a June 1 target
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's going to be ready by opening day and I said the
all-star break,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He's way
ahead of what I thought he would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Osuna's yet to throw off a mound. And with an influx of
right-handers in Gregg Olson, Terry Adams, Alan Mills, Mike Fetters
and Dan Naulty in camp, the Dodgers aren't in a hurry to add Osuna
to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Johnson likes to group certain players together
for workouts, and this year he made sure to place right-handers
Darren Dreifort, Chan Ho Park, Mike Judd and Jeff Williams with
veteran Orel Hershiser. . ..Describing rookie right-hander Eric
Gagne, Johnson said ``he's meaner than a water moccasin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
