<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE TO SABRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO -- Before he requested a trade, Vladimir Tsyplakov asked
for respect.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Kings decided last month that he never would be
more than a great stick handler who refused to shoot, Tsyplakov was
shipped to the Buffalo Sabres for low draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   That is where his old club picked up the story Saturday night
and quickly ended a chapter of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Tsyplakov scored the winning goal and assisted on two others as
the Sabres halted Kings five-game winning streak 4-1 in front of a
sell out crowd of 18,690 at Marine Midland Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was his first goal since coming over on Jan. 23. But
Tsyplakov made a big difference in stopping the Kings' momentum
that peaked the night before with an impressive victory over the
Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of flying to Edmonton with three victories to open their
longest trip of the year, they were sluggish in the second night of
back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in here is happy for him although we wished
he hadn't done it tonight,'' Kings goaltender Jamie Storr said.
``He always worked very hard in practice and he had great stick
handling skill. Maybe this is the place where he can show that.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't going to happen with the Kings. Tsyplakov
filled in on the first line at earlier this season when Luc
Robitaille, Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel were injured.
</P>
<P>
   His play was sometimes brilliant like Nov. 2 in Pittsburgh when
he deked three Pittsburgh defenders then slipped a pass in front to
Donald Audette, who scored. Most of the time it was frustrating for
teammates and coaches. Tsyplakov is from Russia where many players
are raised to pass first, score second.
</P>
<P>
   When the injured players returned, Tsyplakov mostly sat in the
stands, watching his career go nowhere. His agent went to Kings GM
Dave Taylor seeking a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I didn't enjoy myself there, but there were so
many scratches,'' said Tsyplakov, a King for almost five years. ``I
never felt like I got a chance. A game like tonight means
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, Tsyplakov has not become an everyday player. But
with the Sabres one spot from making the playoffs after reaching
the Eastern Conference finals last year, he has been a boost to the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought another weapon to a team that Saturday scored
more than two goals for just the second time in 14 games. Captain
Michael Peca scored twice and Miroslav Satan added an empty netter
with 30 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange because he came to a team that has had trouble
taking advantage of their chances,'' Peca said after the Sabres
scored more than two goals for just the second time in 14 games.
``We've been afraid at times to pull the trigger. But we've worked
on it in practice and made sure Sippy takes shots when he has them.
He does the same for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ziggy Palffy scored his 23rd goal with just 2:58 gone in
the first period, Tsyplakov helped tie it with some hustle behind
the Kings net. Storr was attempting to clear the puck and made a
poor pass. Tsyplakov got it and passed to Peca in front.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second period, Tsyplakov did it himself,
taking a pass from Peca and beating Storr for the eventual game
winner. It was his seventh of the season, but the first since Jan.
3 in a Kings loss at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Tsyplakov acknowledged his second assist -- on a goal by Peca
with 7:32 gone in the third period -- could have been called for a
holding penalty on Mattias Norstrom. Tysplakov held Norstrom's
stick as Peca circled behind him and beat Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray went to referee Dan Maroueli with a tape
to clarify the play. But Norstrom said it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad at the time, but what can you do,'' he said. ``In a
way I was glad for Sippy. It has been a long time coming for him. I
know this must have been great for him beating his old team. I know
he feels good inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
