r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     02-20 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE WINS ON EMOTIONAL NIGHT AT LMU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the night Loyola Marymount remembered its past,
Pepperdine focused on what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the future won out. The Waves, playing against
history and emotion, remained alone in first place in the West
Coast Conference with a 77-65 win over the host Lions on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine needs wins in its final two regular-season games to
claim the WCC crown outright.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy, considering the poignant significance of the
night and emotionally charged atmosphere at Gerston Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   In a touching halftime ceremony, LMU retired the jerseys of the
late Hank Gathers and Bo Kimble, the two forces behind the Lions'
talented teams in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Gathers collapsed and died at Gerston Pavilion in 1990 during
the Lions' WCC tournament semifinal against Portland. LMU, led by
Gathers' boyhood buddy Bo Kimble, shocked the country over the next
two weeks, advancing all the way to the Elite Eight of the NCAA
Tournament before falling to Nevada Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The current Lions, playing inspired before a raucous home crowd,
fed off the atmosphere and stayed close throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions' (2-23, 0-12) only two wins this year are against
against non- Division I-A opponents, yet they easily played their
best game of the season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough against a Pepperdine (21-6, 11-1) team
trying to secure a conference crown and stay in position for an
NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from the get-go it was going to be a war,'' said
Pepperdine forward Tommie Prince. ``They had the ceremony and
Loyola is always hyped to play us so we knew it was going to be
tough in that the game would probably come down to the last
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lalazarian led the Waves with a career-high 23 points to
go along with 10 rebounds. Brandon Armstrong added 17 points and
Craig Lewis had 10. Nick Sheppard had 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Lalazarian is a key reserve who provides scoring off the bench.
His play did not surprise Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the type of character we have, and it shows that we
have guys to come off the bench and get the job done if the
starters aren't doing their job,'' Prince said. ``It's a different
guy getting it done for us every night, so it's tough for teams to
prepare for us because they don't know who that player is going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine shot just 42.6 from the floor (7 of 15 on
3-pointers), but held LMU to only 33.8 percent shooting with a
stifling effort defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert McClendon led the Lions with 22 points. Pablo Machado had
18 points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine closes the regular season on the road at San Diego on
Thursday and St. Mary's Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego upset Gonzaga last Thursday to push the Waves in first
place by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves started pulling away midway through the second half,
using 13-5 run to move ahead, 61-46 after Armstrong's two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Lalazarian kept Pepperdine's lead intact, hitting a running
layup in traffic and a 15-footer to make it 67-53 with four minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves played the final three minutes without Tezale Archie,
who was called for a flagrant foul and thrown out of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
