<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST0220-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Follow through, you
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ Shaquille O'Neal made 15 of 20 free throws against the
Timberwolves, 11 of 12 against the Bulls and 6 of 9 against the
Hornets, including two with 22 seconds left to ice the Lakers'
victory.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, 32 of 41 in his past three games, runs back to the bench
with his right hand still in follow-through position _ having just
figured out he was supposed to be following through, all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the way it left my hand out there,'' O'Neal said. ``I
ain't missing no more. I'm at a point in my life where it's time to
concentrate now. So, I've been concentrating these last couple
games. I've developed more concentration, more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And the pose? ``That's a message. To whoever. That hack-a-Shaq
stuff will never ever work again. Period. Print it.''
</P>
<P>
   SAME OLD, SAME OLD
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over at Los Angeles' other franchise, the Clippers,
we hear Derek Anderson saying, ``My mom said that I've changed,
that I hardly smile anymore. I guess she's right because, out here,
it is hard to show it. We should never be getting beat by 20 points
or have big leads and lose like we do. It's tough to know we're
going to play only for a certain time (each game).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up for the challenge,'' Anderson said. ``I thought I
could come in and help change the situation. I really didn't know
anything about them. I didn't know one thing. I had never even
heard of (owner Donald Sterling).... It hit me during the first
couple exhibition games, when I noticed the crowds. I played in
front of sellout crowds at every level before I got here....
</P>
<P>
   ``I could understand if I was the only one who could play at
this level and we lost that many games, but that's not the case,''
he said. ``With us, there are just too many excuses. We should be
getting it done, regardless. This season has been like a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you spell q-u-i-t? ``If you look at our body language,''
Maurice Taylor said, ``it looks like we do.''
</P>
<P>
   WAITING FOR WALLACE
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen wonders if Portland teammate Rasheed Wallace will
ever completely tap his vast reserves of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not ever scratch it,'' Pippen said. ``He just has so
much talent, it's kind of funny sometimes when you watch him. When
we're in practice, if he would just put a little bit more effort
into trying to perfect a few things, it would change his whole game
and make him a much better player. He's still a great player as he
is. He has so many tools, he can do so many things. None of his
talents are just so overwhelming that he doesn't have to work at
them. If he worked at them, he could be one of the greatest players
in the game. But I'm not sure 'Sheed wants that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
