u r BC-CAR-CHANGES0220-C0X     02-20 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CHANGES0220-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drivers shift gears with new cars, teams
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ When a football team isn't winning, the
first move is to change coaches. In racing, it's the driver that
sits in the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   As the Winston Cup cars line up for the Daytona 500, even
die-hard fans might need a cheat sheet to keep up with who's
driving what car.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most visible changes is with the No. 28 Ford made
famous by the late Davey Allison and Ernie Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin drove the car for the past two seasons, but was
unable to live up to his billing. Irwin is being replaced by Ricky
Rudd, who disbanded his own No. 10 Ford team to drive a Robert
Yates-owned car. It comes from the same stable that prepared the
car Dale Jarrett drove to the 1999 Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who struggled as a team owner and driver, is expected to
be a contender for victories and possibly a championship.
</P>
<P>
   His car number, 10, will be on the Tyler Jet Motorsports Pontiac
driven by Johnny Benson, who left a Jack Roush team and will
replace David Green. Green is returning to a full-time ride in
NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series, where he won the series
championship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin will move to the No. 42 car owned by Felix Sabates and
driven last year by Joe Nemechek. Irwin said he is motivated by a
desire to show his critics _ and his former car owner _ that he can
compete in Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show Robert (Yates) that I can get the job done,''
Irwin said. ``I don't think he said, `Kenny couldn't get it done.'
He just couldn't get the whole deal together for me to get it done
in the 28 car.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what has happened to him, Irwin said he doesn't think
Yates _ or other Winston Cup owners _ are too quick to make
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not performing, at some point somebody says, `Hey,
we've got to make the change,''' he said. ``The owners have to make
the team successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek got his walking papers in midseason last year, then
won at New Hampshire during his lame-duck stage. This year, he will
drive the No. 33 car prepared by Andy Petree.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they say, my stock went up at New Hampshire,'' Nemechek
said. ``That day, we outran them fair and square.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemechek said he thought he was making progress in the Sabates
car before he was released. Now he's starting over with Petree.
``Hopefully, it'll be a better circumstance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader left the Petree car to drive the No. 36 car that
became available when Irvan retired. With the MB2 Motorsports
team's close ties to Hendrick Motorsports, the latest Chevrolet
racing technology should be at Schrader's disposal. But so far, the
MB2 team is winless, and Schrader last won in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we've got everything it takes to win, and that's
what we expect to do,'' Schrader said.
</P>
<P>
   And why has it been nearly 10 years since he won? ``If I could
answer that I would have fixed it already,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Nadeau, who filled in for Irvan in the No. 36 from August
until the end of the 1999 season, has moved to Hendrick Motorsports
and will drive the No. 25 car.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau, unlike other drivers, said he feels no pressure to
produce results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only pressure is what I put on myself,'' Nadeau said.
``We're going to have awesome equipment this year, and you're going
to see a big change out of myself this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach, who drove No. 25 last year, will replace Ted
Musgrave in the No. 75 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated Musgrave parked the car during the race at
Homestead, Fla., and promptly resigned. He is not on the Winston
Cup roster for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mast, who drove the No. 98 for Cale Yarborough last year,
has signed on to drive Larry Hedrick's No. 41 this year.
Yarborough's team is for sale and might not run a full schedule
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying most of the changes is the pressure from sponsors to
perform on the race track. Companies shelling out $8 million a year
or more per driver expect results. And that pressure affects all
but the most successful.
</P>
<P>
   Even rookie Dale Earnhardt Jr., who drives a car owned by his
father and who has won two Busch series titles in a row, feels the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's under contract, and everybody's under expectations
to win,'' he said. ``They're changing drivers, changing teams every
year. Everybody feels it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors don't deny that they put pressure on drivers to win.
</P>
<P>
   W.A. DeVore is senior vice president of Citgo Petroleum Corp.,
which sponsors Elliott Sadler and the Wood Brothers' No. 21 Ford.
He said he expects Sadler to notch some top-10 finishes this year
and eventually take the car to Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing takes a tremendous investment, and the return we get
off that investment is media coverage,'' DeVore said. ``And we get
media coverage when you're up there in the top 10 and especially
when you win a race, so there's tremendous pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the competition is stiffer now, so there's even more
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
