<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-PARITY0220-COX     02-20 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PARITY0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pontiac, Ford, Chevy angle for edge
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The sniping about Pontiac's alleged
aerodynamic advantage over Chevrolet and Ford got personal at the
end of last season. At least Bobby Labonte took it that way.
</P>
<P>
   After he qualified 37th for the last race at Atlanta Motor
Speedway and then went on to win it, Labonte was accused of
sandbagging. ``I heard it all weekend in the garage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inference was that he purposely qualified poorly and
intentionally lay back in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of comical now,'' Labonte said, ``but at the time,
it wasn't that comical. It went to the wrong side of my nerves. We
changed motors, steering boxes, springs, everything. I guess,
(with) all the talk that the Pontiacs had an advantage, they
thought we were just sandbagging. That wasn't the case. I guess
some people didn't know we (usually) run good in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't sandbagging. We run as hard as we can every lap. I
guess, whenever you're busting your butt and trying to go fast and
you're about to wreck and you do hit it right and win the race,
somebody says you're sandbagging. If we were sandbagging, we should
have been sandbagging the whole race, I think. We didn't go there
to sandbag.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac drivers probably will have one more weekend to endure
such jibes. At today's Daytona 500, they will have essentially the
same car that won four of the last five races in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet is debuting a new racing Monte Carlo this season, and
Ford is taking the wraps off a new racing Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers of those makes complained last season that the Pontiacs
had more down force, thus increasing its advantage on flatter
tracks. Winston Cup director of competition Gary Nelson said at the
season finale at AMS that NASCAR might order alterations. More
recently, he said NASCAR will delay making changes until it sees
how the car compares with the new Chevys and Fords at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's possibilities of making changes, but we're looking at
how these new cars fit in relative to the Pontiac, which is a known
quantity,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Joe Gibbs' Pontiac-driving team is holding its
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's happened, and thank God,'' Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at last year, the best Chevrolet won seven
races, the best Ford won six, the best Pontiac won five,'' he said.
``When you look at the point standings, No. 1 was a Ford, No. 2 was
our Pontiac, No. 4 was our Pontiac, and then the Chevys and Fords
come in all mixed in there. So, there's three Pontiacs in the top
10. Is this thing pretty even right now? You'd have to say, yes, it
is. I think NASCAR knows that it's even.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ford and Chevy drivers were crying about Pontiacs last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we got in trouble is when they put all our cars in the
wind tunnel the first part of the year,'' Gibbs said. ``Our car
showed it couldn't hold up to the Chevy and the Ford with the rear
down force. What they did was give us a little more on the rear
spoiler. Well, that started everybody screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiacs raced with a spoiler that was about a quarter-inch
higher than Chevy's and Ford's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we won a race, it was because of the car, not because
we were good,'' Gibbs said. ``Whenever they won a race, it was
because they were good. That's part of life in Winston Cup. I think
what we're scared about right now is they're getting ready to come
out with two new cars to race against us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pontiacs have had that body with those rules all last
year,'' said Robbie Loomis, Jeff Gordon's crew chief. ``They've got
a lot of stuff worked out. The Chevrolet teams are going to have to
work extra hard to figure out where we need to place the bodies and
how to build the fenders to get what we need out of it. I think
we've got a real competitive race car.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Makar, crew chief on Labonte's No. 18 Pontiac, has heard
reports that the 2000 Taurus is a better car for Daytona than last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want an advantage,'' Makar said. ``If we can be
on even terms with both of those manufacturers, I feel like we can
race with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
