u r BC-GOODWILL-NOTES0220-CO     02-20 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-NOTES0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOODWILL GAMES NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    By KAREN ROSEN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Brian Boitano was Goodwill Games a-go-go
Saturday as Brian Orser's hopes at beating his old rival were
gone-gone.
</P>
<P>
   Boitano, who won the famous ``Battle of the Brians'' at the 1988
Olympics, worked with the same choreographer who did the Gap
``khaki-a-go-go'' commercial and used the same music. He had three
triple jumps to Orser's two to edge the Canadian. One of the seven
judges gave each a 10 on the pro scale for presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The other three competitors relied on gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Alexei Urmanov, who did a Phantom of the Opera routine,
tripped over the cape which he had dropped on the ice earlier.
Philippe Candeloro of France also wore a cape -- as well as a skirt
-- for his Braveheart routine. He got a standing ovation for a
program that included a simulation of a battle, surrender and
execution. He also showed the audience his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Petrenko did his routine with a partner, a female dummy
that was attached to him. The audience loved him, and he got two
10s for presentation, but his technical scores were low.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK CONTROVERSY
</P>
<P>
   One day after five male athletes withdrew from the luge
competition citing safety factors on the new $24 million track,
Goodwill Games founder Ted Turner wasn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really aware of it,'' he said. ``I've been at the
events, and I don't know what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   But hometown hero Jim Shea, who is leading the skeleton
competition on the same track, was disappointed that three-time
Olympic champion Georg Hackl and the others gave the track the cold
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough track,'' Shea said, pointing out that none of
the sliders had many practice runs. ``We go over there (to Europe)
to compete and we have a lot of trouble. The Americans never
complain and we never back out. For them to back out is pretty
unsportsmanlike.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realized they couldn't win and they pulled out, in my
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GAMES GO ON
</P>
<P>
   While the site for the 2003 Winter Goodwill Games is still up in
the air, Calgary has committed to host the 2005 Games. Calgary, the
1988 Olympic site, chose 2005 so the event will coincide with
Alberta's 100th anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians plan to add hockey and probably long-track
speedskating to the schedule. One of the 2003 candidates is
Sarajevo, the war-ravaged 1984 Olympic host city.
</P>
<P>
   The next summer Goodwill Games will be held in Brisbane,
Australia, in August-September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ted speaks, sort of:
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he might entertain non-Goodwill Games questions
after a press conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Rocker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!...What's your other question?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like how am I doing with my wife?'' he asked, referring to his
separation from Jane Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of your business! How are you doing with your
boyfriend?'' Then Turner laughed and went to his next photo
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
