<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2706 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-OLY-THIRD-GENERATION0     02-20 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIRD-GENERATION0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shea family tradition rides skeleton sled
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ A couple of years ago, Jack Shea showed his
son a photo that he'd come across amid his scrapbooks and
memorabilia. It showed Jack as a young man and scrawled in pencil
were the words, ``I want to be like him, Jim Shea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't spell hardly anything right but my name,'' Jim Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, he became an Olympian. Now his own son, Jimmy,
is on the brink of continuing the family tradition. If he makes the
2002 Olympic team, the popular Lake Placid family would become the
first in the United States to send three generations to the Winter
Games. And they'll have done it in three different sports: On
skates, skis and sleds.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shea was a double gold medalist in speedskating in 1932 and
still wears his United States team coat. With then-New York Gov.
Franklin Roosevelt in the audience, he won the first event of the
Lake Placid Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, 89, a former local politician, won the 500- and
1,500-meters at the Olympic oval, an outdoor rink which is just
down the street from Jim's liquor store and the Artist's Cafe,
where Jimmy was once a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Shea, 62, competed in cross country skiing and nordic
combined (which also includes ski jumping) at the 1964 Games in
Innsbruck, Austria. He calls himself ``a noncontender'' who was
proud to help carry in the Olympic flag. His wife Judy nearly made
the 1960 Olympic team in alpine skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just the bridge,'' he said. ``I'm just the go-between
between the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy, 31, is the 1999 world skeleton champion and had the two
fastest runs Saturday at the Winter Goodwill Games, leading by more
than a second over Snorre Pedersen of Norway and American Chris
Soule. He'll race again today in front of family, friends and other
well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Skeleton was in the 1928 and 1948 Olympics at St. Moritz,
Switzerland, then was dropped from the Games. Jimmy Shea, who has
his grandfather's gift of gab, lobbied for it to be included in
Salt Lake City in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's ever ridden a sled or toboggan can appreciate
skeleton. Athletes drive down the bobsled/luge run headfirst on a
sled reaching speeds up to 80 mph and forces of about 5 G's. Their
chin guards scrape the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to scare myself,'' said Shea. ``You're trying to
control what's almost out of control. It's never the same twice;
you're always trying to get better and faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shea watched Saturday via the video screen from the bottom
of the run. ``I would like to have been up at the start,'' he said,
``but at 89 years, the hills are steeper than they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the elder Shea said he's always tried to impress upon
his grandson ``what a great honor it is to represent his country in
international competition,'' Jimmy wasn't weaned on the family
sports history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably 11 years old when I realized I'd seen my
grandfather on TV twice a year and that he was a bigshot doing
something,'' said Jimmy. ``My father was really humble about it. He
never really talked about it. I didn't realize he was in the
Olympics until I was little older. I saw him on TV and said, 'Dad,
what did you do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Shea said that becoming a three-generation Olympic family is
``a dream that we've had. My only concern is that there's not too
much pressure on (Jimmy).''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest Shea's first love was hockey. He attended every
hockey game at the 1980 Olympics, including the ``Miracle on Ice''
U.S. win over the Soviet Union. His father thought he'd play
semipro. Then Jimmy tried bobsled. But with top sleds costing
$40,000, he switched to luge, then flipped over to skeleton. The
smaller sleds cost only about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, he was world champion.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shea, who finally hung up his skates about five years ago
because of a bad back, didn't see his son compete in the Olympics.
As the supervisor of the town of North Elba, N.Y., he said, ``I
felt I had to stay home. My wife was real mad at me for doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hopes to be in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm around in 2002, I'll be the most excited, most happy
man in the world,'' he said. ``I just know that Jimmy in 2002 will
be in contention for a gold medal, and what an honor it would be to
see my grandson stand on the podium, and have the flag raised and
`Star-Spangled Banner' play.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like 70 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
