<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT REFUSES TO IMMEDIATELY RELEASE CHICKEN
INSPECTION RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Mopvin in (w) Washington and (a) national
categories.
 &HT;    For release Monday, Feb. 21 
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While claiming that food from two Gold Kist chicken
processing plants in Alabama is wholesome as well as safe to eat,
the U. S. Department of Agriculture is refusing to immediately
release public inspection records at the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Several federal inspectors at plants in Boaz and Guntersville,
Ala., said diseased poultry has been used in part to make chicken
nuggets which the federal government then buys for school lunch
programs in 31 states. While eating the product will not make you
sick and although the chicken is cooked at high temperatures to
kill bacteria, inspectors argue the food is not wholesome. They
also claim that they are hamstrung by new federal food safety rules
that give Gold Kist the power to police itself.
</P>
<P>
   Top Agriculture Department officials say inspection records show
there are no problems at the plant. But when asked for these
records last week, the agency said the records would have to
reviewed under the federal Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) before
they could be released, a process that in the past has taken
months.
</P>
<P>
   Although skeptical of inspector's claims, Carol Tucker Foremen,
a former Assistant Secretary of Food and Consumer Services at the
Agriculture Department, said the agency's unwillingness to quickly
make its inspection records public is ``dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were going to release it on a FOIA,'' she said, `` Give
it to them the minute they ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a Cox Newspapers report earlier this month of the
inspectors' allegations, school districts in at least four states
stopped serving the chicken nuggets from Gold Kist while they
pondered what to do. In Ohio, for example, food service directors
in 12 school districts around Dayton have refused to use Gold Kist
chicken nuggets even though USDA officials have repeatedly assured
state and local officials there is no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Local school officials say they are concerned by the graphic
account of three inspectors at the Guntersville facility of
carcasses with tumors, sores and pus slipping by in the course of
an experimental food inspection program begun by the federal
government last October at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   To allay these concerns, the Ohio Department of Agriculture last
week tested the Gold Kist chicken nuggets to make sure they were
safe to eat. But these tests raised even more questions when the
state announced Friday that it found Listeria, a potentially deadly
pathogen, in one lot of the product stored at a Dayton warehouse.
The state is now doing further testing to track down the source of
the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new federal food safety program, company employees at
the Alabama plant instead of federal inspectors examine and, if
necessary, condemn carcasses. However, at least twice during each
shift federal inspectors scrutinize ten carcasses after they have
been processed. Inspectors said they routinely found a large
percentage of diseased birds during these checks.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Billy, head of the Agriculture Department's Food Safety
Inspection Service (FSIS), dismissed his own inspector's complaints
in a press release last week. He said his agency sets high
standards and ``through inspection, verifies that plants are
meeting these standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy's assurances are contradicted by a day's worth of
inspection records obtained by Cox Newspapers. They show the
Guntersville plant failing four inspections on Jan. 15. However,
because the records are only from one day, there is no way of
knowing whether this represents a serious problem or simply a
momentary lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Gaston, a department spokesperson, said that although
inspection records are public, anyone who wanted to see them would
have to file a formal request under the Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have requested public documents say they have had to
wait months for documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed (a Freedom of Information Act Request) on December 4,
1998,'' said Glen Dosono, a paralegal at the Seattle law firm of
Marler Clark. ``And we have had several follow up letters. They've
given us hardly anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The law firm represents 11 students from Finley, Wash., who
claimed they were sickened when they ate ground beef allegedly
contaminated with E. coli 0157:H7 at their elementary school. The
beef was donated to the school by the Department of Agriculture
under its commodities program. The firm is requesting a variety of
records including inspections at the Nebraska plant where the meat
was processed.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Hicks, who heads the FOIA program at the agency, says she
has seven employees who field the approximately 800 requests made
each year for information. She said that she does not have any
statistics on the average time it takes to fulfill a request.
</P>
<P>
   However, in its most recent report on FOIA the Agriculture
Department said that in 1998 the deparment took over four months to
respond to half of the simple requests and nine and a half months
for what it said were complex questions.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the non-profit, public interest groups in Washington
that monitor government agencies like the Department of Agriculture
say the agency is slow to provide information. Caroline
Smith-DeWaal at the Center for Science in the Public Interest said
she typically has to wait six months after a request is filed.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Nestor, a lawyer at the Government Accountability
Project, said she once got a document in three weeks but that
normally it will take four months. ``If it's a real specific
request like records of filth in a plant, I expect to wait over six
months,'' Nestor said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston said the records could only be released through a Freedom
of Information Act request because they ``may contain proprietary
information.'' Cox Newspapers gave its copy of the inspection
records to Gaston so she could point out what was considered
proprietary. Gaston declined, saying she was not an expert in
identifying proprietary information.
</P>
<P>
   The form, which is filled out by inspectors, asks for the time,
date, shift and production line on which the inspection was
performed. Possible problems that inspectors might find are divided
into five categories on the form. These range from a category No. 1
for carcasses with poultry diseases, to category No. 5 for
``dressing defects'' The inspector enters the number of birds
inspected in each category in one box and the number that were
deficient in a second box. There is no other information on the
form.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
