<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ARIZONA-GOP_PRIMARY-A     02-20 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-GOP_PRIMARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW HAMPSHIRE OF THE WEST': ARIZONA GOT EDGE IN REGION'S GOP
PRIMARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: PRIMARY IS TUES., FEB 22. ALSO MOVING IN ``K''
CATEGORY) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona's early Republican primary has thrust the
Grand Canyon State into the national limelight, but it almost
didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the primary's fate dangled by a single thread in the
Legislature. The deciding vote was held by Sen. Jim Buster, a Yuma
Republican who was playing brinksmanship to save an environmental
bill from a veto.
</P>
<P>
   But the primary had friends, and Buster soon found out how
powerful they were. Near the end of the session, he was summoned
from a meeting and told that Sen. John McCain was calling _ from
North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was THAT important,'' Buster recalled. ``But
apparently he thought it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years before McCain himself would seek the nation's highest
office, he and then-Gov. Fife Symington wanted an early primary.
Both men supported Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas and wanted to give him
an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the best-laid plans of senators and governors often
go astray, and the primary was no exception. Gramm's presidential
bid fell apart before he reached Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain quickly switched his support to the eventual nominee,
Sen. Bob Dole, but millionaire publisher Steve Forbes won the
primary. In the end, most of Arizona's delegates went to Dole after
Forbes dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the primary still accomplished its goal, said former
state Sen. Stan Barnes, who sponsored the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be the New Hampshire of the West,'' Barnes said,
``the first Western state to come off and make a difference. And
you know what? We are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is a big factor in the selection of the next president
of the United States, and as an Arizonan, I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the Arizona primary, which is Tuesday, has
lost some luster, because South Carolina comes just three days
before, and Michigan is on the same day. On the positive side, the
state hosted two GOP debates this cycle, which never would have
happened without a primary.
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP field narrowing to three candidates _ McCain, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and conservative pundit Alan Keyes _ the
dynamics have changed. Bush can simply write off a McCain win to
Arizona being that it's McCain's home state and keep gearing up for
Super Tuesday (March 7).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mike Hellon, Republican national committeeman for
Arizona, said other states have tried to steal Arizona's thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the whole impetus behind the aborted effort to have a
Western regional primary among the Rocky Mountain states,'' Hellon
said. ``They're all very jealous of the attention that Arizona is
getting and they want to jump in on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for the primary goes to Barnes, now a
lobbyist for energy and mining interests.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes shepherded the primary bill through the Legislature,
watching it die not once but twice. Democrats, forbidden by party
rules to participate in an early primary, attacked the bill with a
vengeance, and a few moderate Republicans joined them.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the primary was too expensive _ it ultimately
cost the state $2 million _ to be limited to one party.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of rhetoric, the primary bill would have gone
down a third time without some serious lobbying _ such as McCain's
phone call from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Under serious pressure, Buster decided to dicker with Symington,
who vetoed Buster's environmental bill anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an internal memo obtained by ``The Arizona Republic,''
a Symington aide poked fun at Buster, now a lobbyist for the state
Department of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buster should get the tough-guy award for his suicidal
negotiating style,'' Symington aide Chuck Coughlin wrote. ``You
need to be aware in the future that his style is to take you to the
edge and then jump off, hoping to catch a branch on the way down.''
Buster's leap notwithstanding, Barnes said there was little doubt
that McCain and Symington made the difference, although others had
agitated for a primary for years. An Arizona primary law was passed
in 1992, but it was vague on the date and had other technical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   With McCain and Symington behind an early primary, Barnes said,
``you had the political will to finally get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not to say that it was done for Phil Gramm,'' he
added. ``That has never been true. However, the folks who wanted
Gramm to succeed also wanted an early Arizona primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is a wonderful environment for coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wasn't through tinkering with the primary. Last year, his
operatives lurked in the background as a bill popped up late in the
legislative session, seeking to move the primary back into March,
after Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   To McCain's opponents, the strategy was obvious: save McCain
from expending critical resources to defend his home state from a
George W. Bush incursion. A number of state Republicans rejected
the move, saying it would forfeit the spotlight that Arizona had
gained.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Marc Spitzer, R-north-central Phoenix, supported moving the
primary to the same day as city elections _ March 14 _ to
consolidate the process and save money. But it was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the primary replaced an old-fashioned caucus system, in
which delegates were elected by party activists. That process
marginalized Arizona, because the state convention was held in May,
long after the heart of primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old way was more insular,'' Hellon said. ``You had to be
more of an insider to participate. I think on balance we're
probably better off the more we open up the system.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old system, more than 1,000 delegates went to the state
convention, where they voted for about three dozen delegates, who
would attend the national GOP convention. The delegates campaigned
based on which presidential candidate they supported.
</P>
<P>
   The internecine warring made for some tense standoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, House Minority Leader John Rhodes, an Arizonan who
supported Gerald Ford, was slated to be chairman of the national
convention. But he had no support from state Republicans, who were
lined up behind Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Rhodes almost received the ultimate snub for a
powerful congressman _ not being elected a delegate from his own
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to (elect him),'' Hellon said. ``But the
national Reagan campaign said he's going to control the gavel at
the convention, so we can't have him (ticked) off. You have to
elect him a delegate.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the state party made headlines by electing as a
delegate former Gov. Evan Mecham, who had been impeached and
removed from office just a month before. The move came over the
objections of Sen. Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Hellon said there were advantages to the old system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are making the decisions, they typically know
more about the candidates,'' Hellon said, ``and from a political
standpoint, they make more informed decisions and are not as easily
influenced by short-term passions or media.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, all of Arizona's delegates are committed to the candidate
who wins Tuesday's (CQ: FEB. 22) primary. The delegates are back in
play if the winning candidate drops out before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the attention, there's a more pragmatic reason for
state Republicans to want a presidential primary. It makes money
for the party _ about $100,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the candidates come in and all the news people come in, so
now we have a good reason for them wanting to come in,'' said Dodie
Londen, former chairman of the state GOP. ``Every party needs money
in order to operate for the rest of the year.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Bill.Muller(at)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8178. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1554EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
