<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      02-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLOUT FROM FOX'S MULTIMILLIONAIRE WEDDING 
ONLINE HIRING EVALUATOR (OR EGO DEFLATOR)
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fox broadcasting network created an unexpected television
phenomenon last week by marrying off a man who said he was a
multimillionaire to one of 50 female contestants vying to be his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Fox executives basked in the publicity from the
ratings-rich ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'', they were
faced with questions _ and not just about the propriety of having a
woman agree to marry a man she had seen for about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   They had to explain how the groom _ a comedian named Rick
Rockwell with a penchant for stunts (he once told jokes for 30
straight hours in an attempt to make the Guinness record book) _
could be taken seriously as a wealthy man in need of a wife.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell's resume is deep in show-business moments _ including
stand-up appearances in Las Vegas and a stint on a television
sketch-show as a love-starved beach nerd.
</P>
<P>
   His background underscores a basic flaw in the format not only
of the Fox special but also of the coming crop of reality-based
shows in which real people are supposed to be taking genuine
life-changing actions on camera: How do you keep the
``I'll-do-anything-for-a-break'' fringe element of show business
from infecting the pool of ``real people'' eager to have the most
intimate moments of their lives exposed on national television?
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives are rebroadcasting the show Tuesday night and are
planning to turn the ``Multimillionaire'' format into a
sweeps-month franchise. They say they do not believe they have put
the future of the program at risk by trotting out an initial
contestant who once said, ``I'll do just about anything that's
legal to make people laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   They also continued to vouch for both Rockwell's financial
portfolio _ he is said to have made money by investing with his
father in real estate properties along San Diego's beaches _ and
the sincerity of his proposal and marriage to Darva Conger, an
emergency room nurse.
</P>
<P>
   But they did acknowledge that for the next edition, which is
likely to be broadcast in May, they will choose someone with
absolutely no connection to show business.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that connection is essentially what got Rockwell the gig.
The network, which is owned by the News Corp., had a back-up
multimillionaire ready to go, in case Rockwell had cold feet. And
the back-up had a lot more money, Fox executives said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Darnell, the Fox executive who conceived the special,
said the producers had feared that a man long on wealth but short
on performing skills might be totally undone by the pressure of
having to propose, then exchange vows in front of a stage audience
and on camera.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the question of appearances. The show already had
an unseemly, gold-digging quality _ 50 women deciding to marry a
man sight unseen, just for his assets _ and Darnell acknowledged
that many of the other multimillionaires who had been willing to
take part were not much to look at.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is true,'' he said. ``Millionaires are not all
good-looking men.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox never expected the question about Rockwell's show business
background to become such an issue because they never expected the
special to be such a hit. The show exceeded the best estimate of
Fox's audience research department by about 30 percent, and even
more impressively captured a full third of the women viewers
younger than 35.
</P>
<P>
   The network also had no certainty it would ever try the format
again; now it can hardly wait to do the next show.
Multimillionaires and their prospective brides are piling up, Fox
executives said, with many hundreds of the former and many
thousands of the latter already signed up as possible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, as the saying goes these days, can they keep it
real?
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   Online Hiring Evaluator (or Ego Deflator)
</P>
<P>
   How many people have the self-confidence to subject themselves
to a public appraisal of their market value? Judging by the early
reaction to a new feature of a popular Web site, plenty.
</P>
<P>
   On Vault.com, a 3-year-old site that provides career
information, dozens of job seekers have leapt at the chance to find
out what others think they should earn. The appraisals come from
compensation consultants and a gang of anonymous kibitzers, all of
whom seem eager to place price tags on the services of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Vault.com plans to introduce ``Am I worthy?'' _ a
service that lets people submit their resumes and pictures and get
free feedback on their aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   A test version appeared on the site last week. Some applicants
were more revealing than others, and so were some of the
appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   A young, blond woman calling herself Aerin G. and claiming two
degrees from Stanford University said that she was considering a
switch from a hedge fund to marketing at nonprofit organizations.
Lauren Bell, an account manager at Grady Levkov &AMP; Co. in Manhattan,
estimated the annual salary she could expect at $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Others thought that was a little high, but mostly they wondered
why anybody would abandon a hedge fund for anything other than an
Internet-based start-up company. ``What can a job at PBS do for you
that a job at a hedge fund won't?'' asked someone calling himself
``Aerin admirer.'' He went on to add, ``My career advice would be
to skip on the nonprofit gig and be a model, in which case I'd
raise the valuation to about $500,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of the applicants, whether they are doctors or
investment bankers, want to jump to Internet companies. But Mark
P., who said he has a medical degree and experience as a health
care consultant, may not have been pleased to learn that one
personnel director thinks he is worth only $70,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Oldman, a co-founder of Vault.com, declined to comment on
the new service before its formal debut Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Patrick McGeehan
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
