u f BC-GERMANY-BIZ-MEDIA-NYT     02-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BIZ-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL TIMES WADES INTO GERMANY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also moving in `i' category.) 
(nk) 
 BY EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Germany is the world's fourth-biggest
economy and home to globe-spanning corporations like the automaker
DaimlerChrysler and the media conglomerate Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   But as a market for business journalism, Germany could until
recently be described with only one word: boring.
</P>
<P>
   Most Germans were too conservative to buy stocks and were not
much interested in corporate news. Business reporting was
excruciating dull, yet also prone to highly trumpeted ``scoops''
that turned out to be flat wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of inertia is circulation. In a country with a
population of 80 million, Germany's biggest business newspaper,
Handelsblatt, sells only 170,000 papers a day.
</P>
<P>
   But all that is changing. Thanks in part to a boom in German
high-technology stocks and a revolution in attitudes toward
investing, Germany has become a battleground for new business
publications.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Pearson Group, producer of Britain's Financial
Times, will start a German version of its salmon-colored business
daily with the Hamburg magazine publisher Gruner &AMP; Jahr, which is
owned by Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   It is a big bet. Far from simply translating the British paper
into German, Financial Times Deutschland has its own staff of 130
reporters and editors. Using a state-of-the-art publishing system
in Hamburg, the paper will be printed at four plants around
Germany. It will also have the latest closing time of any newspaper
in Germany, 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times is hardly alone. Confronted by a direct
assault on its turf, the publishers of Handelsblatt put their own
paper through a radical redesign last fall and added several new
sections.
</P>
<P>
   Handelsblatt's parent company, the Holzbrinck Group, also formed
a broad alliance with Dow Jones &AMP; Co. and The Wall Street Journal
Europe. And, just to cover all the bases, it started a new weekly
magazine in January called Teleboerse.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is suddenly awash in business publications. General
interest newspapers, like Die Welt and the Frankfurter Allgemeine,
have bolstered their business sections.
</P>
<P>
   Boerse Online, a weekly investing magazine owned by Gruner &AMP;
Jahr, has seen its circulation quadruple the last three years to
207,000. At least a half-dozen other new business publications have
been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this surge lies a sea change in German attitudes toward
business. As recently as three years ago, less than 7 percent of
all Germans owned stocks. The German stock exchange was a
slow-moving market limited to the shares of big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Frankfurt stock exchange's New Market, where small
companies are listed, has become one of the hottest exchanges in
Europe. With nearly 200 companies listed, most of them new
technology companies, the New Market has attracted hordes of
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a surge in corporate takeovers, particularly
Vodafone AirTouch's hostile takeover of Mannesmann, and corporate
news has become mass-market news.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle between The Financial Times and Handelsblatt
promises to be the fiercest.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to daily business news in Germany, Handelsblatt
seemed to have an undisputed franchise among its target audience of
top-level corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable but extremely dull, Handelsblatt provided exhaustive
daily news about companies and the stock markets. But it offered
little in the way of investigative reporting, probing features or
anything close to humor.
</P>
<P>
   Handelsblatt had already been evolving for several years. The
Financial Times, in English, has more than 20,000 readers in
Germany. The Wall Street Journal Europe, also in English, is not
far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson began talks about a new paper nearly three years ago
with Gruner &AMP; Jahr, and executives say they became convinced that
they could transplant their model without cannibalizing its
existing readership.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier Fleurot, president of Financial Times Newspapers, argued
that the potential readership among corporate decision makers in
Germany is about 1.9 million. Its actual goals are far more modest:
It is guaranteeing advertisers an initial paid circulation of
50,000 and hopes to reach 120,000 within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Handelsblatt have hardly been idle. Thanks to a
makeover last fall, the paper now has color graphics, a much bolder
design and new sections on information technology and personal
finance.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz-Werner Nienstedt, chief executive of Handelsblatt,
disputed Pearson's argument that there is a larger market. ``The
market is well covered by Handelsblatt,'' he said. ``Readers and
the advertisers will have to judge whether there is a market and
whether this new paper is the one to fill it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1615EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
