<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-20 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GIVING HEALTH CARE MORE ATTENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia, S.C. _ Sometimes it takes a tough political campaign
to ``define'' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates seeking more rights for patients in our increasingly
expensive and frustrating health-care system have not always
considered Texas Gov. George W. Bush a hero _ or a leader for their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, to be sure, has signed several laws designed to improve
the lot of consumers dealing with health-care providers and
insurance networks. But on other notable occasions, he has greeted
consumer-backed bills with about as much warmth as insurance
executives offer plaintiffs' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, his first year in office, Bush vetoed a Patient
Protection Act that would have given consumers more rights in
dealing with their health maintenance organizations. He said it
would be too costly. And, in 1997, his heart didn't seem to be in
it when he let another major consumer priority _ a bill allowing
patients to sue their HMOs for malpractice _ become law without his
signature.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, in the midst of his tougher-than-expected
presidential race, Bush started claiming championship credentials
for consumer-friendly health care, which is important to a lot of
people, including voters in states far from home.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the South Carolina Republican primary, when he
wasn't attacking opponent John McCain, Bush was running television
commercials touting his own accomplishments in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the litany was familiar _ setting high educational
standards, fighting lawsuit abuse, reforming welfare, toughening
juvenile justice laws and cutting taxes. But there also was a new
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Washington politicians deadlocked, I delivered a
patients' bill of rights,'' Bush said in one ad. Back home in
Texas, one consumer advocate was surprised _ and amused _ to learn
of Bush's new campaign claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that using the word, `delivered,' is stretching
the truth a little,'' said Lisa McGiffert, a senior policy analyst
for Consumers Union's Southwest regional office in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign office released a list of more than a dozen
patient protections that have been enacted in Texas while Bush has
been governor. They include measures that require HMOs under
certain circumstances to give women direct access to their
obstetrician-gynecologists; require managed care plans to cover
minimum hospital stays of 48 hours following childbirth; require
HMOs to pay for emergency services provided by nonnetwork
caregivers; and various other requirements designed to make managed
care plans more receptive to consumers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called HMO malpractice bill, which Bush let become law
without his signature in 1997, allows a patient to appeal to an
independent review panel and, in some cases, take an HMO to court
if the network denies payment of treatment recommended by a doctor.
It was the first state law of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan believes the list speaks for
itself. ``It's one of the major accomplishments under his (Bush's)
record as a reformer with results,'' he said, reciting a new Bush
campaign tag line.
</P>
<P>
   McGiffert acknowledged that Bush has allowed ``some really good
consumer protection laws to get into place,'' and she gave the
governor credit for ordering the state insurance commissioner to
develop consumer-protection rules, many of which later were made
law.
</P>
<P>
   But McGiffert said that Bush never has taken the lead on patient
rights to the extent, say, that he did on civil justice reform, an
area in which the governor staked out goals for limiting lawsuits
and lobbied lawmakers to ensure that those goals _ or at least
satisfactory compromises _ were met.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's civil justice priorities also often ran counter to
consumer advocates' health-care efforts. The governor almost vetoed
the HMO malpractice bill because he feared that it could drive up
health-care costs and increase the number of lawsuits. Before he
let the bill become law, McGiffert said, he insisted that lawmakers
include some anti-lawsuit language that ``creates more hurdles for
people to jump through.``
</P>
<P>
   But the question of leadership aside, patients' rights advocates
have been grateful for what they have accomplished under Bush's
watch in Texas. Now, maybe health care _ which already has been a
major topic of debate between the Democratic presidential
candidates _ will begin receiving more attention in the Republican
race for the White House as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
