<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-FLAT-TV0221-COX     02-20 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAT-TV0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FlatTV: the latest in home entertainment products
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVERCREEK, Ohio _ Hundreds of ants were marching around behind
the bar of Kirby Gaboury's Beavercreek home.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an infestation; it was a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Gaboury, owner of the Audio Etc. home entertainment business,
was showing the movie ``Ants'' to demonstrate the operation of his
new 50-inch, high-definition video monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Though the screen of the monitor is as wide as some projection
televisions, the unit is only about 4 inches thick and hangs on the
wall behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Gaboury's screen is an example of a plasma monitor, a device
that delivers a wide-screen television image without the bulky box
of a picture tube television or the separate projector of
projection systems.
</P>
<P>
   But though Gaboury's system delivers an incredible picture,
plasma monitors are probably a long way from becoming common
because of their price. Gaboury's monitor retails for about
$20,000, and the least expensive plasma monitors available run
about $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most people have seen commercials for Philips FlatTV, a type of
plasma monitor that is shown being hung on walls or ceilings in the
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But Gaboury said potential customers usually are shocked when
they ask about the Philips sets and find the units in the
commercials sold for about $15,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Philips has introduced a second-generation FlatTV that is due in
stores by March that will sell for about $10,000, but still that
will be outside the reach of all but the most affluent gadget
freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Most retail stores don't even carry plasma monitors but they are
available online or through high-end home entertainment dealers.
</P>
<P>
   If you're curious about plasma monitors, you may run across
demonstration models at home shows or electronics shows as well as
in a few stores.
</P>
<P>
   NO PICTURE TUBE
</P>
<P>
   The normal television set is often about as deep as the screen
is wide because a normal picture tube, called a cathode ray tube,
uses an electronic gun that has to be a certain distance from the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The gun at the back of the picture tube shoots a pattern of rays
at the screen and the rays excite red, blue and green phosphors
that create the images displayed on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a gun, plasma televisions use an electrified gas to
activate the phosphors through a process using ultraviolet light.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers are confused by the terms ``flat TV'' and flat
screen television. FlatTV is what Philips calls its plasma
monitors. Flat screen televisions are traditional deep-box
televisions with flat rather than rounded screens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its flatness, the first thing you'll probably
notice about a plasma monitor is the width of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   While the traditional television screen is only slightly wider
than it is tall, plasma monitors are shaped more like a movie
screen. The normal screen ratio is about 5:4, meaning it has about
five inches of width for every four inches of height. Plasma
monitors are 16:9, meaning the screen is nearly twice as wide as it
is tall.
</P>
<P>
   The wide aspect screen makes plasma monitors an excellent way to
watch DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   When motion pictures are formatted for television, they must be
cropped to fit the narrower television screen. Action that takes
place at the sides of the screen is often lost in the reformatting
process.
</P>
<P>
   Movies in letterbox format capture the full movie image by
displaying the movie at full width and showing black bars at the
tops and bottoms of the television screen. Though letterbox format
reproduces the movie the way the director intended, but most
television watchers don't like it. They feel they're being cheated
because they don't get to use their whole screen.
</P>
<P>
   Many DVD movies offer the option of being displayed in 16:9
format. They'll fill the full plasma monitor screen giving you a
home theater experience much closer to the original movie theater
experience.
</P>
<P>
   When high-definition television broadcasts become widely
available, they too will come in 16:9 format. Having a plasma
monitor is one way to be prepared when broadcaster switch to HDTV
format in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH DEFINITION OR NOT?
</P>
<P>
   It's important to realize that not all plasma monitors are high
definition.
</P>
<P>
   Within the foreseeable future all broadcasts could be in high
definition, a format that gives brighter, sharper picture quality
than convention televisions. When that happens, older televisions
will be able to receive high-definition signals by adding a
converter box, but they won't be able to take full advantage of the
improved picture quality.
</P>
<P>
   Television pictures are made up of horizontal lines drawn across
the screen, and the more lines the entertainment system provides
the clearer the picture tends to be. High-definition signals
include more lines of resolution than normal television signals,
and high-definition televisions can display more lines of
resolution than normal televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gaboury's set, a Pioneer PDP505HD, is high definition and is
able to display high-definition pictures to their best advantage.
</P>
<P>
   His set has a feature called ``progressive scan'' that, in
effect, blends the scan lines on the screen so they are less
visible.
</P>
<P>
   If you get close to the picture on a normal big screen
television, you'll be able to see tiny black horizontal strips
dividing individual lines of resolution. Vertical white objects on
a dark background may have a slightly jagged edge of distortion at
each line.
</P>
<P>
   Progressive scan lessens that effect, Gaboury said, giving a
more natural picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your DVD gives you a lot more lines of resolution than
broadcast television does,'' Gaboury said. ``A high-definition
television gives you much better performance with a DVD right now
than you get on a normal television. You don't have to wait for
high-definition broadcasts to take advantage of a high-definition
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philips new model FlatTV, Model 42PF9952, is not high
definition, according to Lori LeRoy, a spokeswoman for Philips
Consumer Electronics. She said it will display high-definition
programming without a converter box, but it won't offer true
high-definition performance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their costs, plasma monitors are not complete
televisions; they are monitors only. That means they are designed
to show pictures but they don't have a built-in tuner to select
stations to watch, and they don't have sound.
</P>
<P>
   Plasma monitors are designed to be integrated into a home
theater system that already has a sound system and video sources.
Video sources can include cable or satellite television services,
DVD players, VCRs or computers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Philips FlatTV can be purchased with an optional
``e-box,'' a tuner that takes the place of the tuner found in an
ordinary television. The e-box costs about $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gaboury drives his plasma monitor primarily with a DVD player,
but it's also connected to a VCR. Because the VCR has an internal
tuner and it's connected to a cable television service, Gaboury can
watch cable programming on his monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Because plasma monitors are designed to work with a variety of
video sources, they usually have a variety of connector types.
Gaboury's set, for example, is set up for standard RCA inputs
commonly used in cable television in addition to advance input
types Super VHS, component and RGB.
</P>
<P>
   Gaboury said some early plasma monitors had problems, especially
with overheating that shortened the lives of the units. But he said
the second- and third-generation models being sold today are more
dependable.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of his customers say they intend to wait for prices
to drop before they invest in a plasma monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're really interested in quality, it's not necessary to
wait,'' he said. ``Prices drop when companies start putting out
lower quality products with more compromises in the internal
components and in the bodies of the units.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's available now are mostly high-end units. The
top-of-the-line products are going to be selling for the same
prices in a few years as the products available now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
