<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VANGUARD-JAZZ-ART-NYT     02-20 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGUARD-JAZZ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ CLUB TURNS 65, NO RETIREMENT PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a jazz-crazed member of the Hot Club of Newark,
N.J., 17-year-old Lorraine Stein made her first pilgrimage to the
Village Vanguard in 1940, five years after it opened in a former
basement speakeasy on Seventh Avenue South in the West Village. She
and American jazz have not been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Vanguard that she met her first husband, Alfred
Lion, the founder of Blue Note records. It was there, too, some
years later that she fell for the Vanguard's owner, Max Gordon, and
left Lion to become Lorraine Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way the funky, pie-wedge Vanguard, with its superb
acoustics, became a jazz shrine, a refuge for musicians holing up
against the onslaught of rock 'n' roll in the 1950s and '60s, a
soapbox for poets and an incubator for entertainers from Lenny
Bruce and Woody Allen to Judy Holliday, Betty Comden, Adolph Green,
Harry Belafonte, Wally Cox, the Weavers, Bobby Short and the comic
billed as Prof. Irwin Corey, the world's foremost expert.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with an indomitable presence encompassing 60 of the
Vanguard's 65 years, Gordon is to preside Monday night at a private
65th birthday party for the club that is expected to draw many of
the artists who have played it over the years, including Roy
Hargrove, Jim Hall, Tommy Flanagan, Marian McPartland, Joe Lovano,
Etta Jones, Houston Person, Joshua Redman, Geri Allen, Jimmy Heath,
Eric Reed, Cedar Walton and Helen Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've invited every musician in town,'' said Gordon, 77. While
a jam session is not officially on the agenda, she said, ``if they
don't play, this is not a jazz club.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1934 that Max Gordon, a Lithuanian immigrant who
stumbled into the nightclub business, opened the first Vanguard on
Charles Street. The police quickly plastered it with violations,
and the following year he reopened at 178 Seventh Avenue South,
where the club remains. Lorraine Gordon took over when her husband
died at age 86 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``You figure it out as you go,'' said Mrs. Gordon, who wasted
little time asserting herself, replacing staff members and hiring
new lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max was beautiful,'' she said. ``He taught me how not to do
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have to make a decision,'' she said, ``I ask, `What
would Max do?' Then I do the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   With a throaty laugh she added, ``Ahh, I say those things; I
don't mean it exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, friends say she is clearly her own woman, keeping a
sharper eye on business than Max did _ although when it came to
salaries, Corey cracked, ``Max gave musicians jobs, and they'd
still be unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed up by her younger daughter, Deborah, Mrs. Gordon is
everywhere at the Vanguard, taking reservations over a rotary
telephone in the ancient former kitchen that serves as the office,
monitoring deliveries and, once the music starts, shushing talkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's tough, always has been,'' said the jazz writer Nat
Hentoff, who credited Mrs. Gordon with ``the taste and business
acumen'' to keep the 123-seat club clear of faddish distractions
and commercialism and focused on mainstream modern jazz. Hentoff,
who wrote the introduction to Max Gordon's 1980 memoir, ``Live at
the Village Vanguard,'' said that despite the danger of being
shushed, ``When somebody calls me from out of town and asks me,
`What club should I go to?' I always say, `You can't go wrong at
the Vanguard.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tough? Mrs. Gordon begged to differ. ``That's not tough, to tell
people not to use a cell phone, not to talk while the music is
on,'' she said. ``You can cough. You can sneeze. But this is not a
conversation pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Perched at a back table the other afternoon and sipping a vodka
and soda in a wine glass, she monitored a tide of deliverymen and
technicians setting up for the night's 9:30 and 11:30 shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I help you?'' she challenged one stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the piano tuner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' she said, ``try.''
</P>
<P>
   New as she was to the nightclub business when she took over _
``He didn't really listen to me,'' she said of her husband _ she
was no neophyte when it came to jazz. As a teen-ager in Newark, she
and her brother, Philip, were charter members of the Hot Club,
whose young jazz devotees shared an obsession for collecting
recordings and frequenting jam sessions in mostly black dives like
the Alcazar, then featuring a stirring trumpet player named Jabbo
Smith. (To her delight, in 1979 she rediscovered him, alive and
playing in the show ``One Mo' Time'' at the Village Gate, and
helped revive his career.)
</P>
<P>
   Times were hard, she said. ``But we didn't know it was the
Depression. We thought it was normal.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Vanguard in 1940 she met Alfred Lion, a debonair
immigrant from Germany who had founded Blue Note records, a premier
jazz label. He showed her his record collection, and she was
smitten.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother loved him, too,'' Gordon said. ``She said, `He's too
good for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the war came and Lion was drafted, she followed him to
Texas, where they were married. He was discharged with an eye
ailment, and the couple resettled in Greenwich Village, socializing
with jazz giants like Louis Armstrong, Sidney Bechet and Miles
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   They also met a struggling Hells Kitchen pianist named
Thelonious Sphere Monk and, impressed, tried to sell his records.
Mrs. Gordon said she had some under her arm during a 1948 visit to
Fire Island where she spotted Max Gordon in a restaurant eating a
Danish. She appealed for a gig at the Vanguard for Monk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked me over and said, `Well, I just happen to have a
week in September,''' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another, she said, and by 1949 she was Mrs.
Gordon. The pair became a fixture on the jazz scene, turning up at
Newport, R.I., and dividing their time between the Vanguard and
other clubs that Max Gordon opened, the Blue Angel and Le
Directoire. While raising their two daughters, Mrs. Gordon became
active in campaigns against nuclear weapons and the Vietnam War,
joining demonstrations for Women's Strike for Peace around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   From her perch in the back of the club last week, Mrs. Gordon
suddenly noticed that a photograph on the wall was askew. ``Hey!''
she called to technicians setting up. ``You knocked the picture.
That's Jabbo, my little Jabbo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
