<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CONSPIRACY-BOOK-REVIE     02-20 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSPIRACY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A CONSPIRACY OF PAPER': MONEY AND MURDER ON THEIR MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the beginning of David Liss' strikingly authentic-sounding
first novel, ``A Conspiracy of Paper,'' which is set in London in
1719, there is mention of a character ``profiting in his
speculation, taking advantage of the fluctuations in the markets
caused by the rivalries between the Bank of England and the South
Sea Company.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately you assume the conspiracy of paper mentioned in the
novel's title must somehow refer to the famous South Sea Bubble or
Scheme, which involved a plan to buy up England's national debt in
return for a trading monopoly in the South Seas and in South
America, and which led to a speculative frenzy and England's first
stock-market crash, in 1720.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this turns out to be not literally the case. The events
surrounding the Bubble are not mentioned until the novel's final
page. But in a figurative sense the novel's subject is the South
Sea scheme. For in Liss' rich historical imagination, a London
ripening for investment hysteria comes vividly to life.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of the story is Benjamin Weaver, born Lienzo, a
former boxer known as the Lion of Judah because he is Jewish, who
has given up the ring for work as ``protector, guardian, bailiff,
constable-for-hire and thief-taker,'' this last duty being most
lucrative, Weaver explains, ``for by bringing felons to justice I
received not only the reward of my hirer but also the considerable
forty-pound reward of the state as well.''
</P>
<P>
   His memoir begins with a visit to his lodgings by one William
Balfour, who is convinced not only that his own father, an apparent
suicide, was actually murdered but also that Weaver's father,
Samuel Lienzo, a stock-jobber from whom Weaver had long been
alienated, shared the same fate. Balfour wants Weaver to
investigate. Weaver, though put off by Balfour's anti-Semitism,
agrees for the sake of the fat fee.
</P>
<P>
   He is upset by the subject of murder, because of his own
responsibility for a man's death while he was handling another
unsavory assignment: the retrieval of a purse from a prostitute for
Sir Owen Nettleton, a baronet with a weakness for night life who
wants his purse back for a packet of compromising letters it
contains.
</P>
<P>
   At first the reader is puzzled over what the connection, if any,
may be between Sir Owen's letters and the possible murders. But as
Weaver reconciles with the survivors of his family and begins to
explore his father's and William Balfour's pasts, the mysteries
pile up so thickly that it's hard to keep any connections straight.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the plot draws you in from page to page, just as Weaver
is enticed by his beautiful in-law Miriam, the widow of his cousin
Aaron, who died when a trading vessel sank. And the author has the
leisure to explore every aspect of early 18th-century London life
from the precarious relations of Jews with English society to the
way the underworld was organized to the behavior of people high and
low.
</P>
<P>
   In a concluding historical note, Liss writes that in the
language of his novel he has tried to suggest the rhythms of
18th-century prose, which seems evident in amusing passages like
the following, in which Weaver comments on his life after the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame that I did not anticipate the pugilists of today
who, like the famous Jack Broughton, in their retirement open
fighting academies to train the young bucks that would take their
place. Broughton has indeed been ingenious enough to construct a
piece of apparel he calls mufflers _ a kind of voluptuous padding
for the fist. I have seen these things, and I suspect to be hit by
a man wearing these gloves is quite like not being hit at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Liss further writes in his afterword that his novel grew out of
his work as a doctoral candidate at Columbia University, ``where my
research focused on the ways in which 18th-century Britons imagined
themselves through their money.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``After years in the archives, reading pamphlets,
poems, plays, periodical essays and long-forgotten novels, I failed
to find the source that told me precisely what I wanted to know
about the new finance. So I wrote one. My goal in this novel has
been to capture both the unbridled enthusiasm and the pervasive
anxiety of the period leading up to the South Sea Bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the anxiety overwhelms the enthusiasm as Benjamin Weaver
battles the mysterious forces that try to keep him from the truth.
But ``A Conspiracy of Paper'' is an evocation of English history
that you can happily get lost in for days.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A CONSPIRACY OF PAPER'
</P>
<P>
   By David Liss
</P>
<P>
   442 pages. Random House. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
