<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TALENT-AGENTS-MEDIA-A     02-20 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENT-AGENTS-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT AGENTS STRIKE DEAL IN EFFORT TO RECLAIM INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ This town's talent agents, facing rising competition
from talent managers, are no longer satisfied with merely being
powerful and rich. They want an even bigger share of the
entertainment industry's financial pie.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last week, the talent agency business took the first
significant step in decades to expand its power as well as its
financial muscle. Under a tentative agreement with the Screen
Actors Guild, talent agencies will soon be able to participate in
the financing and distribution of films and television shows as
well as have a noncontrolling interest in a production companies.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, because of the potential for conflict of interest
in the negotiating process, talents agents were legally barred from
investing in such companies or sharing the financing of films and
television shows.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the agreement enables talent agencies to open the
door for the first time to investors, who could range from
advertising agencies to Internet companies. This would give talent
agents not only capital to grow, but a vehicle to make them
wealthier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three driving issues here,'' said Jeff Berg,
chairman of International Creative Management, one of the town's
top talent agencies. ``The first is, agents have been living under
60-year-old regulatory guidelines which are not responsive to the
agency business in the 21st century. The second is, we need to
attract capital and investments to our businesses and we need to be
invested in other kinds of companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the third is, we need to be competitive as a source of
executive talent,'' he said. ``We're concerned about the migration
of agents to the management ranks. We need to retain our best and
brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the agreement, between the Screen Actors Guild and
The Association of Talent Agents, which represents 100 talent
agencies in the Los Angeles, rests on an acknowledgment on the part
of agents that their power has diminished over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Talent agents in the 1980s and early 1990s ruled the town. They
earned huge fees packaging films and television shows, controlled
the careers of stars, demanded lavish sums for even mid-level
actors and even became _like Michael Ovitz _ more powerful than the
television and studio moguls who dominated Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Not any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Although agents still have extraordinary leverage, the
ascendancy of talent managers who can also produce films and
television shows has unhinged top talent agencies like Creative
Artists Agency, International Creative Management and William
Morris. Some stars like Leonardo DiCaprio, Kevin Costner and Robin
Williams no longer have agents, but rely on managers or lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   What has disturbed agents is that they are regulated, while
talent managers face few such legal barriers. Agents are licensed
by the state and earn their money finding work for clients and
negotiating contracts for them. Managers, on the other hand, are
unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Managers charge anywhere from 10 percent to 15 percent of
clients' pay, but are also able to create and produce projects and
collect potentially substantial film and television fees. In
contrast to agents, managers, by law, are only supposed to advise
and secure employment for their clients but not negotiate
contracts. But this rule has never been enforced and managers often
work out the details of a client's deal. The line has become
increasingly blurred between managers and agents, even though
actors now often pay commissions to agents as well as managers.
</P>
<P>
   What made talent agents especially nervous was Ovitz's decision
less than two years ago to enter the ranks of talent management
after his dismissal as president of the Walt Disney Co. by Michael
Eisner, the chairman. Previously, the relationship between agents
and managers was generally friendly _ they often worked together
for clients.
</P>
<P>
   But Ovitz began luring some of his former clients at Creative
Artists to his management company, which outraged the agents. Last
year, Creative Artists told its clients that Ovitz was a direct
competitor, and that the agency would no longer represent anyone
who also used Artists Management. The result was that some Creative
Artists clients, like the directors Sydney Pollack and Martin
Scorsese, as well as Williams, joined Ovitz, and left the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Ovitz's company, Artists Management Group, represents
a number of stars like DiCaprio, Cameron Diaz and Williams. Ovitz's
management company had not succeeded, though, in luring substantial
numbers of movie stars and directors.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of Ovitz on the management scene _ as well as
the success of top management companies like Basic Entertainment
(formerly Brillstein-Grey), which produces HBO's ``The Sopranos'' _
left agents worried that they were locked in by legalities that
diminished their leverage and hurt them financially. The result was
that an increasing number of agents joined the management ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Top agents, though, are hardly suffering or trading in their
Armani or Prada outfits. A senior agent who is not a partner at
Creative Artists can earn annual base pay of $500,000 plus a $1
million bonus, depending on his or her track record. (At
International Creative Management and, to some extent, William
Morris, agents can also buy stock in their companies. But equity in
Creative Artists is only given to its half-dozen partners).
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the Screen Actor's Guild, which has to be
ratified by the union's executive committee, allows talent agencies
for the first time to retain a minority investment in television
and film production companies. It not only increases the leverage
of agents but allows them to reap profits from a successful
television or film production.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Stuart, executive director of the Association of Talent
Agents, said the agreement had been worked out over the last year.
``Our proposal was never designed to combat managers,'' she said.
``This is designed to deal with the realities of the entertainment
world today. The new media is exploding. It's a world of vertical
integration. We have got to be in a position to make new business
arrangements for ourselves and our clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart added: ``Agents have been at a competitive disadvantage.
At long last, it's time for a change.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
