<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-TALKS-ART-2     02-20 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TALKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHEST DRAMA IN MICROSOFT TRIAL IS BEHIND CLOSED DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The closing arguments in the Microsoft antitrust case in
Washington on Tuesday promise to provide moments of courtroom
theater, but it is the settlement talks taking place behind closed
doors in Chicago that are the greater drama.
</P>
<P>
   The private deliberations, mediated by Richard A. Posner, a
leading antitrust scholar and chief judge of the 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, are at the settle-or-fold stage.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for both sides in what one person close to
the talks called ``the ultimate antitrust poker game.'' Walking
away from the settlement talks, under way since November, could
well mean waiting a couple of years for a final outcome in the
courts, including appeals.
</P>
<P>
   For the government, that means the risk inherent in a change of
administration, perhaps a Republican one with different views on
antitrust matters. For Microsoft, the risk is a likely legal ruling
that it violated the law, a wave of follow-on private antitrust
suits, and the business uncertainty of whether it will eventually
have to cope with severe sanctions or more modest ones.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the odds are against a settlement, people close to the
talks say. The trial judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, indicated
earlier to both sides that he might delay closing arguments if the
government and Microsoft appeared near a settlement. But the court
issued a statement at the end of last week, detailing the itinerary
for Tuesday's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The government and Microsoft remained far apart as of last week,
despite a painstaking process employed by Posner to try to find
common ground. Typically, he has met one day a week in Chicago with
each side, not bringing the two camps together. Over the last few
months, the representatives have included William Neukom,
Microsoft's in-house counsel, and David Boies, the Justice
Department's chief trial lawyer in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Posner, according to people close to the talks, has issued sets
of written questions, sometimes a dozen or more to each side: How
does this contract work? How does this technology work? Often, he
will then ask one side about a conflicting answer from the other.
</P>
<P>
   The process is intellectually rigorous, these people say, and
there is homework. ``His approach is iterative, step by step,'' a
person close to the talks said. ``He's not retrying the case, but
he's really gotten down to immerse himself in the contracts and the
technology. He's not interested in just hearing lawyers talk.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to encourage a settlement, Posner assured both sides at
the outset of the talks that if they reached an agreement, he would
publicly support it, including testifying before Congress, if
asked. Under the Tunney Act, a court must give at least 60 days'
notice for public comment before a proposed settlement can be
approved. That review period is intended for a court to hear
witnesses and accept friend-of-the-court briefs. But it would also
provide time for wider public scrutiny in other forums, including
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two sides _ sizable throughout the
trial that began in the fall of 1998 _ grew even wider in November,
when Jackson issued his findings of fact. Though not a final
ruling, his findings emphatically supported the version of the case
presented by the Justice Department and 19 states suing Microsoft.
He found the big software maker to be a monopolist whose business
practices stifled competition and harmed consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's findings gave the government a very strong hand at
the settlement talks. Microsoft's settlement proposals, a person
close to the talks said, must ``effectively address every issue
raised by the government.'' Yet one of those issues, and an
accusation in the suit, is that Microsoft tied its Internet
Explorer Web browser to its industry-standard Windows operating
system to unfairly squelch competition.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denies the charge, saying that its browsing software
is an integrated feature of Windows, not a separate product.
Microsoft also cites a June 1998 ruling in a related case that
supports its stance.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Microsoft has maintained throughout its
long-running dispute with the Justice Department that its bedrock
principle has been to defend the ``freedom to innovate'' _ that the
company should be free to design Windows as it sees fit, unfettered
by government oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department maintains that a monopolist like
Microsoft can indeed engage in anticompetitive product designs, and
that the practice should be curbed.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the issue of tying products together is one of
several obstacles to a settlement. ``The government has such a
strong hand at this stage, I can't imagine there is any settlement
the government would find acceptable that Microsoft would agree
to,'' said a Silicon Valley software executive who has talked to
the Justice Department about legal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's findings, according to government officials, suggest
one of two types of remedies: a powerful set of prohibitions on
Microsoft's conduct in the future or breaking up the company in
some way to foster competition.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with ``conduct'' remedies _ like forcing Microsoft
to ensure rivals access to its Windows technology and prohibiting
exclusive contracts _ is that they require the government or courts
to constantly police Microsoft's actions. Both the courts and the
Justice Department are reluctant to take on such a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long list of serious conduct remedies really does start to
look like regulation, continually looking over Microsoft's
shoulder,'' a person close to the talks said. ``You can argue that
a breakup is extreme and a bit scary, but its virtue is that it is
simpler and less regulatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has refused to even consider the breakup option at the
settlement talks. Steven Ballmer, its president and chief
executive, has said it would be ``absolutely reckless and
irresponsible for anyone to try to break up this company.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, recent strategy within Microsoft has, if anything,
drifted in the opposite direction _ to more tightly bind its
various groups together. It is, for example, trying to take its
Windows business model from desktop computing and extend it to the
Internet with what it is calling ``next-generation Windows
services,'' a software platform for the Internet that other
programs run on.
</P>
<P>
   And after shifting strategies for years, Microsoft's consumer
group, which includes the MSN Web site and MSN Internet access
service, is adopting a course that links it closer to the software
plans of the rest of the company. Asked recently if there was any
consideration of making the consumer Internet unit a stand-alone
company, Richard Belluzzo, who heads the consumer group, replied:
``Our strategy is built around software integration with the rest
of Microsoft. It wouldn't make any sense if we were a separate
company.''
</P>
<P>
   In striking Internet deals with other companies, Microsoft has
sold itself as a concern that can supply the widest array of
necessary software and services, from Windows to WebTV to software
for smart phones. Last November, Tandy Corp., with its 7,000 Radio
Shack stores, struck a distribution deal with Microsoft. It chose
Microsoft over a competing bid from America Online, explained
Leonard H. Roberts, the Tandy chairman, because he believed that
Microsoft could provide ``the technology glue, the operating
system'' for all the Internet devices he plans to sell in his
stores.
</P>
<P>
   What if, as some have proposed, Microsoft is broken into three
to five companies as the result of the antitrust case? ``One way or
another, that case will resolve itself,'' Roberts said. ``Whatever
form Microsoft is in _ and I hope it's in the same form _ they have
committed that they will be able to deliver this technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've signed a contract that is 120 pages long that was also
signed by Bill Gates and Steve Ballmer,'' he added, ``and it
includes ultimate issues of change of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Such language is reasonably standard in business contracts,
Microsoft insists, adding that it has not altered its contracts
with an eye toward the possibility of a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Microsoft's message to business partners is: There
is no need to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Some antitrust experts agree. Robert Litan, a former senior
official in the Justice Department and now an economist at the
Brookings Institution, personally advocates breaking up Microsoft
into four companies _ three competing operating-system companies
and a fourth that takes Microsoft's other software businesses.
``But if Microsoft fights this long and hard enough in the
courts,'' Litan said, ``I think it can avoid a breakup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
