<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2842 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-ARIZONA0221-COX     02-20 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT, Ariz. _ The national media's infatuation with Arizona
Sen. John McCain is only weeks old, sparked by his upset victory in
the New Hampshire GOP presidential primary. Like any new love, it
is intense and glosses over faults.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Prescott Mayor Sam Steiger has known McCain since
McCain burst onto the Arizona political scene in 1982. He even
worked for the senator for three years in the early 1990s. That's
why, Steiger says with a smile that stretches his walrus mustache,
he is supporting Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like John as a person, but I just think his commitment to
big government is much stronger than anyone knows,'' said Steiger,
70, who was a freshman U.S. congressman with Bush's father. ``If I
knew George W. as well as I know John, I might have a hard time
voting for him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that McCain will win the Arizona
Republican primary Tuesday _ the question is by how much.
Presidential candidates usually win in their home states by huge
margins, often by more than 40 percentage points. Though many polls
showed McCain ahead of Bush by less than 10 percentage points last
summer and fall, his standing has improved considerably since his
New Hampshire victory. Several recent polls show he leads Bush by
about 20 points, and in one poll Thursday he had a 36-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign says a win is a win, but if its candidate
falls short of a landslide, many will interpret the results as a
telling statement from the voters who know McCain best.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a direct connection between McCain's lack of support
among many key Republicans in Arizona and his lack of support in
the Republican Senate caucus,'' said Larry Sabato, a political
science professor at the University of Virginia. ``What should
disturb people the most is that the people who know John McCain
best seem to have the most doubts about a McCain presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Arizona political scientists say there are reasons for the
relatively tight margins that have little to do with how much
people here like McCain. McCain won re-election to the Senate in
1998 with 69 percent of the vote _ almost identical to the 68
percent that Bush got in his own gubernatorial re-election bid the
same year.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that popular Gov. Jane Dee Hull endorsed Bush.
McCain and Hull just don't like each other, in part because McCain
was close to former Gov. Fife Symington and Hull was not. Hull was
the secretary of state who took over Symington's office in 1997
after he was convicted of lying to banks to obtain loans to shore
up his foundering real estate empire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been endorsed by all but one of Arizona's Republican
congressmen, most GOP state lawmakers and most of the state's
big-city mayors and county officials, however.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for McCain's less-than-stellar performance in the
polls, according to Arizona GOP director Nathan Sproul, is that
Arizona has so many newcomers _ almost a million in the last 10
years. The state population is 4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some also point to the disparity in political advertising.
Arizona is a far cry from the super-charged political atmosphere of
New Hampshire and South Carolina. There are few signs or bumper
stickers for either candidate, and neither has campaigned in the
state recently. But Bush has had television commercials running
since the beginning of year, while McCain had been absent from the
airwaves until this weekend when he began running radio
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's game was never necessarily to win here, but to tie
McCain down,'' said Ken Goldstein, a political scientist at Arizona
State University. ``Every dollar McCain had to spend in Arizona was
a dollar he couldn't spend in South Carolina and Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hull, the governor's son who is heading Bush's Arizona
campaign, would not reveal the campaign's overall strategy in
Arizona. ``We've put in a good effort here, and that's the
important thing. The people in the state know a lot about Governor
Bush. If he wins the nomination that will be highly critical in the
general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein says McCain's improved standing in the Arizona
presidential polls is a recent phenomenon because here, as in many
other states, people didn't view him as a serious contender until
after his New Hampshire victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Prescott, a town of 35,000 in heavily Republican Yavapai
County north of Phoenix, the people who support John McCain like
him for the same reasons they do in other states. In many ways the
town is a microcosm of Arizona: Fifty years ago, Prescott had fewer
than 7,000 people, many of them miners and ranchers. Today, its
Victorian homes and 100-year-old saloons are surrounded by
subdivisions, chain stores, Indian casinos and golf courses.
Retirees are pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fairly cynical about politics, but I suppose I like McCain
more than most politicians _ he seems to have some integrity,''
said antique store owner Pete McNey, 47.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Chilleen, who works behind the desk at a local hotel, said
he is attracted by McCain's heroism as a prisoner of war in North
Vietnam for five years and the fact that he isn't part of the ``in
crowd'' of Republicans on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bit of a maverick. He's been through hell and he still
has a great outlook on life,'' Chilleen said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Arizonans like McCain's independence from his
Republican colleagues. Arizona is a deeply conservative state: It
produced Barry Goldwater, the father of modern American
conservatism, and voted Republican in every presidential election
between 1952 and 1992 (it went for Clinton in 1996) _ the only
state to do so. Despite McCain's solidly conservative voting record
during his 17 years in Congress, some see his recent crusades for
campaign finance reform and against tobacco companies as betrayals
of conservative principles. The Arizona primary, unlike those in
New Hampshire and South Carolina, is limited to registered
Republicans, so McCain won't get any boost from independents and
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of McCain's prickly personality. On the
campaign trail, he jokes that he isn't a contender for the Miss
Congeniality award in the Senate, a line that goes over well in
other states, but hits a little close to home for some here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a president who is not only tough-talking, but
someone who's a diplomat, and who can negotiate,'' said state Sen.
Scott Bundgaard, who has endorsed Bush. ``He's a hothead _ the
governor of Arizona said so herself. She's had those sort of
run-ins with him. Most of us have, and we know other people who
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Arizonans even say they are a little tired of hearing about
McCain's war record, the part of his campaign that seems to
resonate the most with people outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first (congressional) campaign was based almost entirely
on his being a prisoner of war. I'd go to meetings and he'd have
little old ladies crying, and he was crying, and I don't like
that,'' said 76-year-old Anna Cocklin of Prescott, who's been
active in GOP politics in Arizona since 1953.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
