<HEADER>
A2847 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-20 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD LIFE: ENJOYING HIGH ON THE HOG, THANKS TO GEORGE AND
MARTHA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no surprise that a Washington, D.C., resident named Graff
would frequently be called to lead German tour groups of the
capital. And my cousin, Don Graff, has discovered that the visitors
from Friedrichshafen, Ludwigshafen and Baden-Baden like pork
stories.
</P>
<P>
   So he tells them about George Washington, particularly when the
first president's birthday is approaching.
</P>
<P>
   The way Don tells it, between the time Washington left office
and his death, he and Martha were alone at their dining table only
once.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, supporters, ex-soldiers and near strangers would arrive
at Mount Vernon to ``pay their respects'' and then forget to leave.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a problem for those of us who reside near the Pacific
Coast. All you have to do to get rid of a family of freeloaders
from Mandan, N.D., is to surprise them at dinner with a heaping
bowl of steamed clams. John the Baptist's tonsils, served on
skewers, would not provoke such a severe reaction.
</P>
<P>
   If steamed ``little necks'' will not do the job, just lead your
visitors past one of the fish counters at Pike Place Market. Point
at the largest geoduck in the bin and remark, ``I think I'll cook
that up for dinner tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodby Seattle, hello Mandan.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't have geoducks on the shores of Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   What George and Martha often served their guests was pork.
Servants were under orders to carve a prime cut from the roast, for
the most honored guests. It was a common practice known then and
now as ``eating high on the hog.''
</P>
<P>
   When visitors had overstayed their welcome, they were liable to
confront a lesser cut of meat, often a leftover haunch from the
kitchen cooler. That was known, then and now, as ``getting the cold
shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's what Don told me. Are you going to call my cousin a
liar? As far as I know, the visitors from Munster never do. But
they really like pork stories. And they would probably like this
meal.
</P>
<P>
   High on the Hog
</P>
<P>
   1 3-pound pork loin roast
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, cut in slivers
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried thyme, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons soft bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Using a thin-bladed knife, make several deep insertions in the
roast. Shove a slice of garlic in each. Plunk the roast in a baking
pan and rub with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the thyme with the wine, pour over the roast and let it sit
for 1 to 2 hours at room temperature. Don't rush things. It's not
like the redcoats are coming to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Tent a sheet of aluminum foil over
the roast and shove the pan (including the marinade liquid) into
the oven. Let roast for 50 minutes. While it is cooking, hum two
choruses of ``Yankee Doodle'' while mixing together the bread
crumbs, mustard and chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Remove roast from oven. Discard the foil. Baste with the pan
juices, adding more red wine to the pan if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the mustard mixture over the top and sides of the roast
and return to oven for 40 minutes or until the thermometer reads
170 to 180 degrees. Let meat rest out of the oven a couple of
minutes then carve into thick slices.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have a cow if the roast is pink inside. Pork is safe to
eat once it exceeds the temperature of 137 degrees. This roast
should serve six or more, and you might serve it with:
</P>
<P>
   Martha's Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   5 potatoes, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup flour
</P>
<P>
   13 ounces chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Quarter cut cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Alternate layers of potatoes and onions in a casserole.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan melt the butter and stir in the flour. When
foaming, slowly stir in the broth and mayonnaise. Cook until sauce
thickens. Add salt and pepper and pour the sauce over the potatoes.
Sprinkle top generously with paprika and bake in a 350-degree oven
for about 75 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
