<HEADLINE>
INTERNET USERS: ISOLATED, MAYBE, BUT NOT SO DIVIDED  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Stanford University survey on the social impact of the
Internet sparked debate last week because of its contention that
the rise of the global computer network is leading to a new wave of
social isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Internet enthusiasts rose en masse to complain that the study
overlooked the community-building aspects of the Internet. They
rejected the idea that more time spent in front of computers means
more isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Largely overlooked in the uproar was another striking finding
made by the researchers: that the so-called ``digital divide''
between higher-income individuals with access to information
technology and others who lack such access is largely a myth.
</P>
<P>
   According to Norman Nie, a Stanford political scientist and a
former Gallup Poll researcher, the most significant variables in
predicting Internet access at home or at work were education and
age. College education increased the rate of Internet access by
more than 40 percent, and Internet access was 40 percent more
common among people under 25 than among those over 65. High-income
individuals were 21 percent more likely to have Internet access,
while women, blacks and Hispanics had lower rates of access by just
4 percent, 5 percent and 8 percent, respectively, than the average.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was conducted by the Stanford Institute for the
Quantitative Study of Society, polled 4,113 individuals and 2,689
households, including both Internet users and nonusers. The
researchers found that overall, some 55 percent of those surveyed
had Internet access at home or at work and that 43 percent of
households were online.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that age differences in Internet usage reflect
generational differences, suggesting that Internet use will
increase sharply over time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
