<HEADLINE>
WEIRD AND FUN, ANYTHING GOES WHEN IT'S CYBERPALOOZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: disinfo.con is the name of the event; disinfo.com is the
organization's Web site) 
(lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The gathering at the Hammerstein Ballroom on Saturday
was something like an academic conference. Lecturers spoke about
their latest research, showing slides on a screen overhead. But the
slides were of designs for a time machine, alien handwriting and
portents of apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering was also like a religious service, with preachers
insisting on the truth of their revelations, and a sideshow,
complete with a sword swallower and unclad women. And at times it
could have been a motivational lecture or a self-help infomercial,
not about diets or relationships but the application of Aleister
Crowley's ``magick'' and the dissolution of dualities.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering was Disinfo.con, an 11-hour event that its
organizer, Richard Metzger, summed up as ``Cyberpalooza.'' It drew
an audience in the hundreds who were largely clean-cut, in their
20s and, in a random sampling, mostly working on the Internet or in
other media jobs; they paid up to $99.95 a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Metzger promised, in opening remarks, ``The speakers appearing
on this stage will be messing with your head, playing with your
files and committing acts of higher revolutionary mutation.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those acts were a sermon from the artist Joe Coleman, who
declared that humanity was a cancer on the body of Mother Nature;
meanwhile, videotapes of corpses being dissected were shown. ``I
call on the cleansing fires of holy extermination,'' he said; then
he lighted a Roman candle attached to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Women from the rock group the Voluptuous Horror of Karen Black,
nude or in blue body paint, performed a punk version of the Celine
Dion hit ``My Heart Will Go On.'' But most participants confined
themselves to speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Disinfo.con brought together artists, authors, rockers,
filmmakers and less categorizable characters like Paul Laffoley,
whose ``architectonic thought-forms'' envision futuristic projects
like homes grown from genetically engineered gingko biloba seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture is liquefying,'' said Grant Morrison, who created
``The Invisibles,'' a comic book that, he said, ended up
prophesying his life. ``People are wondering: Why don't we fit into
this world? Why don't we think they're telling us the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Genesis P-Orridge, of the rock groups Throbbing Gristle, Psychic
TV and Thee Majesty, told the audience: ``You want people to say
stuff that nobody dared say. That's why you're here.'' He ruminated
on whether the earth was a recording device and how to escape the
territorial imperatives built into DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Of course a Web site was involved: www.disinfo.com, which has
been providing what Metzger calls alternative news since 1996. He
also has an Internet talk show and a television series, ``Disinfo
Nation,'' for Channel Four in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   With articles and links, disinfo.com covers attacks on the World
Wide Web, opium cultivation in Afghanistan, death-metal bands in
Scandinavia, religious cults and anything else that strikes its six
staff members as interesting. ``A lot of people just want a
reliable source for something weird, something fun,'' Metzger said.
</P>
<P>
   Disinfo, Metzger cheerfully admitted, is out to build brand
recognition. But he's doing this at a time when culture's
transgressive fringe is just one more niche market.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Rushkoff, who has written books about corporate
colonization of the Internet, pointed out that would-be outsiders
soon find knockoffs of their clothes at the local mall. He urged,
in a keynote address, that the counterculture consider itself
victorious and not agonize over selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they just buy the thing that we really believed in,
that's them surrendering to us,'' he said. ```Teach us,' they say.
`Here, take our money.''' He said that after his speech,
advertising-agency representatives approached him with invitations
to speak to their employees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marilyn Manson, transmitted live by satellite from Los Angeles,
brooded over being considered a cause of violence among teen-agers.
``I'm an obvious and easy target because I look like I cause
problems and I do, I try to,'' he said. Condemning parental
pressure, he said, ``Bad parents make bad kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Anton Wilson, whose ``Illuminatus'' trilogy of novels
presented a grand unified conspiracy theory, suggested that the
difference between Federal Reserve notes and counterfeit paper
money was that the Federal Reserve Bank waved a magic wand over its
currency.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of conspiracy buffs spent much of their time saying
conspiracy-mongers can go too far. ``The idea that there's an
absolute answer to anything is patently wrong,'' said Kenn Thomas
of the magazine Steamshovel Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in a post-`X-Files' world, so what's weird after
that?'' asked Mark Pesce, the chairman of the interactive-media
department at the University of Southern California film school,
whose presentation was a mock-indoctrination and initiation for his
church. ``Now that the weird is gone, maybe what's left is to play.
That's what we've been doing today, playing with the weird.''
</P>
</TEXT>
