<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOUR FROM ORIGINAL APPLE TEAM WILL FOCUS EFFORTS ON LINUX
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the original Apple Macintosh team are regrouping
in order to take the best of the quirky Apple computer and move it
to the world of Linux software.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hertzfeld, Mike Boich, Susan Kare and Guy Tribble are
trying to recreate the innovative tone originally set by Apple's
founder, Steve Jobs, when he led a band of renegades to design the
Macintosh in the early 1980s. They plan to take some of the best
ideas on computer ease of use and blend them into a new visual
desktop interface for Linux.
</P>
<P>
   THOMSON TO SHED MOST OF ITS PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Corp. said last week that it would sell all its
newspapers _ 55 dailies and 75 other periodicals _ with the lone
exception of its flagship daily, The Globe and Mail, which is based
in Toronto but printed and sold across Canada. Thomson plans to put
some of the $2.5 billion these 130 papers could fetch into
expanding its electronic databases.
</P>
<P>
   FOX'S MULTIMILLIONAIRE PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   The Fox broadcasting network created an unexpected television
phenomenon last week by marrying off a man who said he was a
multimillionaire to one of 50 female contestants vying to be his
wife, but now it has to deal with the fallout from ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multimillionaire?'' Besides questions about the propriety
of having a woman agree to marry a man she had seen for
approximately one minute, they had to explain how the groom _ a
comedian with a penchant for stunts _ could be taken seriously as a
wealthy man in need of a wife.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY'S BOOM IN BUSINESS NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Pearson Group, publisher of Britain's Financial Times, will
start a German version of its business daily on Monday with the
Hamburg magazine publisher Gruner &AMP; Jahr, which is owned by
Bertelsmann, putting new life in the static market for business
news in Germany and re-energizing its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ADVOCATE ACQUIRES OUT MAGAZINE
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of Out magazine, the United States' most widely
read magazine aimed at the gay and lesbian community, has been
acquired by the publisher of The Advocate, its major rival,
according to the two companies. Out, which was badly in need of
capital and was suffering from a recent decline in readership, had
been for sale after a failed management buyout.
</P>
<P>
   REVLON TO SELL A PRODUCTS UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Revlon has agreed to sell its professional products business to
an investment group led by the unit's chairman for $315 million.
The sale is part of a plan to help Revlon pay off debt and return
to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   TRAFFIC REPORTERS FOR THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Internet analysts say the recent service disruptions for several
high-profile Web sites may lead to the introduction of regular news
updates on Internet traffic that could focus on security concerns,
traffic tie-ups or both. But even with the reports, the average
Internet consumer, unlike drivers stuck in a traffic jam, has
little recourse in devising a route around whatever is causing the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS CLOSED FOR HOLIDAY
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States are closed Monday in observance of Presidents' Day. They
will reopen Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
