<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-MICH-0221-COX     02-20 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MICH-0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain uses fiery rhetoric to regain momentum
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    Dayton Daily News
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ John McCain combined fiery populist
rhetoric, biting humor and an appeal to patriotism Sunday in an
attempt to regain the momentum that George W. Bush interrupted by
soundly defeating McCain Saturday in South Carolina's Republican
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   On the Michigan State University campus and at other campaign
stops, McCain urged Michigan's Republicans, Democrats and
independents to vote for him in Tuesday's presidential primary so
that together they can take back their government from ``the
special interests and big money people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in a hotel where there was no mint on the pillows,''
said McCain, who spent more than five years a prisoner of war in
North Vietnam. ``I know how to take a punch and I know how to fight
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The flag-waving crowd of 600 here _ a mixture of students and
adults _ roared and waved American flags as McCain paced the stage
in a campus gym.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Republican primary is open to all voters. Vice
President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley are not
listed on the Democratic ticket; Michigan Democrats will pick
convention delegates in caucuses on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign, McCain said earlier in Livonia, a Detroit suburb,
is ``fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win in the state of Michigan,'' he said.
Arizona also holds a primary Tuesday and McCain said he expects to
win his home state.
</P>
<P>
   This state's 58 delegates will be the biggest campaign prize so
far, and the contest offers Bush and McCain the first opportunity
to test their appeal in a large state that reflects the nation as a
whole. The outcome will be closely watched as it may offer a
glimpse of what's likely to happen on ``Titanic Tuesday'' March 7
when primaries will be held in 12 states, including Ohio, New York
and California.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain insisted that he is running a positive campaign, he
blasted Bush as a captive of the special interests and mocked the
Texas governor's claim that he is the real reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush called himself a reformer,'' said McCain, whose
signature issue has been campaign finance reform. ``If he's a
reformer, I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush used to call himself a compassionate conservative.
Now he calls himself a reformer with a record. Soon he'll call
himself a Texan with tenacity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At both stops he said Bush would do nothing to shore up Social
Security and that the Texas governor's tax cut proposals would
unfairly benefit the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, I don't think Bill Gates needs a tax cut,'' said
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the students, he told them that he wants to inspire
them to sacrifice and serve their country the same way Theodore
Roosevelt, Franklin D. Roosevelt, John F. Kennedy and Ronald Reagan
inspired earlier generations of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what being president of the United States is all
about,'' McCain told the campus crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He also blasted President Clinton and Gore for money-raising
scandals in their administration. He recalled Gore's statement that
``no controlling legal authority'' prevented him from raising money
at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give him a controlling legal authority, a
controlling ethical authority. And then I'm going to beat him like
a drum,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   He blasted Clinton for letting Democratic contributors sleep
overnight in the Lincoln bedroom in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States treated the Lincoln bedroom
like Motel 6 and he was the bell hop,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's broad appeal seemed to be reflected in the enthusiastic
crowds that greeted him.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Golick, 18, a college freshman, coaxed her father into
joining her in greeting McCain when he arrived at a suburban
Detroit hotel in the early morning hours Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Golick said McCain's crusade for reform and
truth-telling in what it will take to get young people interested
in government again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the first Republican I've ever voted for,'' said
her father, 45, a supervisor with the Ford Motor Company.
</P>
<P>
   He said he got involved in Jimmy Carter's insurgent presidential
campaign in 1976 but that his interest in politics had all but
disappeared until McCain came along. He said he supports abortion
rights - McCain doesn't - but that he's willing to overlook that
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls have shown that strong support from
Democrats and independents is the key to McCain's victory hopes.
Bush has a strong lead among Republicans, but McCain draws much
more support than Bush from non-Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Schwarz, a Battle Creek Republican and McCain's
Michigan chairman, told the Michigan State crowd that McCain has
across-the-board appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is as conservative as the United States
Constitution, as liberal as Abraham Lincoln and as progressive as
Teddy Roosevelt,'' said Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was accompanied by his wife Cindy, Schwarz, Republican
Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee and Gary Bauer, the conservative
activist and former Reagan White House aide who dropped out of the
presidential race and now backs McCain.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
