<SLUG> BC-LATRY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, A GENEROUS DOSE OF MESSIAEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who could have guessed a year ago, when there came
the seemingly rare opportunity to hear all of Messiaen's organ
works in expert performances and relatively quick succession, that
another would come around so soon, with the time frame even more
condensed?
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jon Gillock, an American, played the works over five
months at Riverside Church. Now, Olivier Latry, a Frenchman and the
organist at the Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris, is performing
them over two and a half weeks on the splendid Mander organ at the
Church of St. Ignatius Loyola on Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the simplifying mystics of Eastern Europe so much
in vogue, Messiaen proves something of a mystical maximalist at
times, with his polymodal textures and cathedral-like complexes of
sonority. Yet his standing has only grown in the eight years since
his death.
</P>
<P>
   That is clear from the advertisement on the back of the program
for this event, in which Deutsche Grammophon touts seven major
Messiaen recordings of recent vintage and announces that Latry is
to record the complete organ works at Notre Dame. He recently
finished a cycle there and soon goes on to do another, at St.
Paul's Cathedral in London.
</P>
<P>
   The second of the six programs here, on Feb. 15, was especially
attractive in its symmetry, presenting the ``Diptyque,'' from 1930,
and ``Les Corps Glorieux,'' from 1939, with a substantial diptych
of its own as centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Several programs this season have sensitized listeners to years
like 1939, when so many European composers were haunted by the
prospect of war. But just how little regard Messiaen, a fervent
Roman Catholic, had for worldly affairs is apparent in the
``Diptyque,'' where earthly life is depicted as a vain bustle in
contrast to the sublime stasis of paradise. The last note of the
gradual ascent of the second part stretches to half a minute or
more.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, ``The Combat of Death and Life,'' at the center of
``Les Corps Glorieux,'' refers not to war but to the suffering and
death of Christ. The work as a whole is a meditation on glorified
bodies, resurrected after death. Although its spiritual intent is
evident in its repeated use of chantlike monody and its repeated
specification of the ``celestial voice'' registration, the music is
abstract, colorful and multifaceted enough to rivet even the
skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity of Messiaen's cosmology, if not his music,
remains a wonder. He seems to be on familiar terms with angels and
co-opts even the fallen ones, here using the tritone _ the interval
of three whole tones, the long-shunned ``devil in music'' _ as a
cadential figure, a point of repose, in the movement ``Refinement
of the Glorified Bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Latry's readings were excellent, unhurried yet intense. And as
with Gillock, the unseen Latry was shown via closed-circuit
television, a happy innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The next program is on Tuesday. Despite present evidence, such
an abundance of this rich yet rarefied music may not return any
time soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
