<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PAPERS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMSON JUMPS HEAD FIRST INTO AN ELECTRONIC FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The last 65 years, the Canadian media giant Thomson
has been in and out of nonmedia businesses that held temporary
promise _ oil and travel, to name two. But it has always owned
newspapers, dailies and weeklies through which millions of
Canadians and Americans knew the Thomson name.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, though, the Thomson Corp. said it would sell all its
newspapers _ 55 dailies and 75 other periodicals _ with the lone
exception of its flagship daily, The Globe and Mail, which is based
in Toronto but printed and sold across Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson plans to put some of the $2.5 billion these 130 papers
could fetch into expanding its electronic databases. These
subsidiaries already account for half of the company's $6 billion
in annual sales _ albeit through companies the public may know
little about.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's other businesses include a legal and regulatory group,
led by the legal publisher the West Group and its Westlaw online
research service; Thomson Learning, a seller of textbooks for
professionals and students; Thomson Financial, a provider of
financial information that includes First Call/Thomson, which polls
financial analysts to produce earnings forecasts; and Thomson's
scientific, reference and health-care group, which sells
information to researchers and other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, 80 percent of its revenue will come from the
electronic distribution of information, Thomson said. Investors
like this strategy, and since the announcement on Feb. 15 shares of
Thomson have gained 5.4 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange. They
closed Friday at $34.56.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale of the papers has been a catalyst,'' said Jeremy
Burge, media and telecommunications analyst at TD Securities in
Toronto. The decision to sell the newspapers has made the financial
world aware that Thomson is a global leader in electronic content,
Burge said, even if the move has nothing to do with entertainment,
which many think is how content is defined.
</P>
<P>
   Nominally, Toronto is Thomson's main office, but its operating
executives work in Stamford, Conn., and the bulk of its business is
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's databases are valuable research tools for lawyers,
accountants, investment advisers and educators. Other systems
developed for the financial services sector manage a variety of
activities, keeping records of securities transactions and
measuring comparative performances _ of mutual funds, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Globalization is creating a demand for these services around the
world, Burge said, ``and Thomson can leverage off what it's got in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company has spent more than $2 billion on
114 database acquisitions, he said, and there are still hundreds of
smaller companies that could be brought into the fold in Europe and
North America.
</P>
<P>
   A big takeover is also within Thomson's means. What fits in the
company's future must be electronic and global, not print and
local, Thomson's president and chief executive, Richard J.
Harrington, said last week. The newspapers on the block are mostly
in small cities in the United States, though five are in Canada.
Together, they had revenues of $810 million last year and earnings
before interest, taxes and depreciation of $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no shortage of buyers for the 125 papers in the
United States, said Jeremy Halbreich, chairman and president of
American Consolidated Media, a Dallas-based company that owns 22
small-circulation papers. Thomson is known for running good
businesses that are particularly strong in sales and marketing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dailies with circulations over 50,000 include The Tribune in
Mesa, Ariz.;nnecticut Post in Fairfield County, The
Repository in Canton, Ohio; and The Post-Crescent, in Appleton,
Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective buyers are thought to include Knight Ridder of San
Jose, Calif.; the MediaNews Group of Denver; and Hollinger
International, a Toronto company that already has 90 papers in the
United States. But dozens of smaller regional chains will be
looking at opportunities to either fill a gap in their coverage or
expand. Although Thomson would prefer to sell everything at once,
analysts say it is more likely the papers will be sold in regional
clusters. Goldman, Sachs is Thomson's adviser on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   These days, weekly papers are being sold for five to six times
profit before taxes, interest and depreciation, analysts said. The
multiples on small dailies, depending on size and growth, can range
from eight to 12, and sometimes more if they have broadened their
services _ with Internet sites, for example, as many Thomson papers
have done.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, only a handful of bidders exist for the five papers
on the block, the largest being The Winnipeg Free Press. Newspaper
ownership has become highly concentrated in Canada, partly because
of restrictions against foreign buyers. The Canadian publishers
that have expressed interest in this rare chance to expand are
Hollinger; Quebecor Inc. of Montreal, which owns the Sun chain; and
the Torstar Corp., owner of The Toronto Star.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe and Mail, Thomson said, fits with its new objectives,
in part because its base is national, not regional. More important,
though, The Globe has developed four Internet sites _ two
specializing in business information _ and a business television
channel. Those sites could lead the way to selling a wider range of
electronic services, which in Thomson's view might be easier to
market around a well-known core product, the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
