<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, Feb. 21. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-REPUBS (Dateline TK) _ Attention turns to the Michigan
primary. By Frank Bruni and Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   OILPRICES-ECON (Washington) _ For the past year, even as the
price of oil tripled to $30 a barrel from a record low of $10,
policy makers, economists and many in the oil industry itself hewed
closely to the same line: oil doesn't matter much anymore.
Technology, which depends much less on energy than manufacturing
does, now drives economic growth. Such thinking was, and to a
certain extent remains, conventional wisdom. But it has taken only
a few weeks of $2 a gallon home heating oil, $20 airline ticket
surcharges, and $75 to gas up Ford Expeditions to make people
wonder if oil is really so irrelevant. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECTION (Tehran, Iran) _ Returns are still trickling in
from the parliamentary elections, and they show more gains for
reformers. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UNREST (Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ Angry Serbs stoned,
punched and kicked American troops in the northern, Serb-dominated
district of this town today, forcing them to beat a hasty retreat
and cut short their part in a citywide search for weapons. German
troops also came under a hail of stones in the same area. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-LAWSUIT (Undated) _ In the art world Herbert Black is
known as a man who loves art and antiques, and loathes the auction
houses where he buys and sells them. Suddenly he has a lot of
company. Black, a copper trader from Montreal, is suing the two
major art auction houses, Sotheby's and Christie's. He and other
disgruntled customers contend that they were overcharged because of
collusion by the two rival auction houses, and they are basing
their suits in a criminal antitrust investigation being conducted
by the Justice Department. The fallout is likely to be not just
embarrassing but also expensive for Sotheby's and Christie's, which
could end up paying their irate clients tens of millions of
dollars. By Leslie Eaton and Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-HOMESTEAD-REBUILD (Homestead, Fla.) _ Homestead has still
not reclaimed its old self. Andrew chased out much of the white
middle class, obliterated an Air Force base that poured more than
$400 million a year into the area's economy and reduced houses,
trailer parks and 3,000 acres of lime groves to a horizon of
sticks. Still, in the rubble of Hurricane Andrew, an entirely
different Homestead has begun to bloom, a transformed community
that says much about the changes that are sweeping small towns
across this state and much of the South. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRASH (New York) _ The closing of Fresh Kills Landfill, which
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has predicted could happen before the
state-imposed deadline of December 2001, has already evoked
reserved celebration on Staten Island. But the huge effort to
achieve that goal has come at an unexpectedly high price. By Eric
Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GORE-MRSCLINTON (Albany, N.Y.) _ Al Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton have left the White House nest and are learning to fly on
their own. Sunday at the Wilborn Temple, a red brick historic black
church in downtown Albany packed with 1,500 worshippers, the two
came together for the first time as candidates, he for president,
she for senator from New York. They praised each other to the
rafters, and their spokesmen said the two would be eager to appear
together again. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
