<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-20 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND BEGINS DEFENSE WITH A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Three-and-a-half-million Kiwis let out a
collective sigh of relief Sunday after Team New Zealand, an unknown
quantity before Sunday's contest, began its first defense of the
America's Cup with a decisive victory over Italy's Prada Challenge
in Race 1 of the 30th cup competition. Race 2 of the best-of-9
finals is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On a spectacular summer afternoon, a massive spectator armada of
more than 2,000 vessels watched the Team New Zealand boat, NZL 60,
approaching from the starboard end of the starting line, lock up
with Prada's Luna Rossa with five minutes to go. Both crews
appeared tentative, but the Kiwi tactician Brad Butterworth was
jealously protective of the right-hand side, and he was having none
of the Prada strategist Torben Grael's attempts to steal it away.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Luna Rossa hit the line at full speed, with the Kiwis
three seconds behind. Now it was time to finally see what has been
the source of endless speculation along the docks of this
sailing-crazy city for months: would NZL 60 be able to match the
speed of the challenging boat?
</P>
<P>
   Holding to starboard tack, the two boats lined up side by side
and, sliding off to the left, the differences in pace were
indiscernible in the first third of the inaugural beat. If
anything, Luna Rossa appeared to have the tiniest of advantages.
``We've got more speed,'' said a member of the Prada after-guard.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but the Kiwis had Butterworth, the laconic mastermind
who had somehow been pried off his beloved golf course for one of
the most important boat races in his nation's history, and who was
about to reveal his genius. The wind, flowing from the south at
compass readings between 180 and 190 degrees, had a right-hand
bias, and Butterworth played it for all it was worth.
</P>
<P>
   Working up the leg, NZL 60 began to initiate the action, tacking
toward the center of the course and forcing Luna Rossa, unable by
the smallest of margins to cross in front of the Kiwis, to tack
away.
</P>
<P>
   With each successive encounter, the New Zealanders added a few
more yards to their growing advantage. Grael, hoping to force the
Kiwis into an error, twice threw false tacks at NZL 60, instructing
the helmsman Francesco de Angelis to push the bow into the wind as
if beginning the maneuver, then falling back to his original
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were being rolled, so we tried the fake tacks,'' Grael
said. ``You have to do something when you are in the back.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Kiwis would not bite. Prada's moves, undertaken with a
whiff of desperation, had backfired. Their momentum was lost with
each ill-advised head fake, and NZL 60 pulled steadily away. At the
top mark of the 18.5-mile course, the New Zealanders led by a firm
22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiwis performed a perfect gennaker set while the Italians
struggled. ``Too slow,'' Grael shouted, pleading for a jump start
to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their quickness in the final two races of the
challenger series against America One, in light to moderate
conditions similar to Sunday's, many felt the forecast favored Luna
Rossa. But as the race unfolded, the Kiwis seemed as swift as the
Italians, if not faster. That fact was underscored at the second
mark, which they rounded with a lead of 36 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for who has the faster boat, I think it's too early to
comment after a shifty day like today,'' de Angelis said. ``I think
the boats are very close.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Someone had to win and someone had to lose. But it's
just the first day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth was sailing as if he had a lifelong knowledge of the
Hauraki Gulf, which of course he has. He continued to play the
right and, when the wind swung even further in that direction,
spinning around to a compass reading of 215 degrees, he was in the
catbird's seat. At the completion of the second windward leg, with
the race at the midway point, the lead was a whopping 63 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Prada was determined to make it interesting, and it did on the
ensuing run, bringing a hint of a new breeze with it from behind
and closing the gap to 25 seconds at the bottom mark.
</P>
<P>
   But on this day, the Italian's hopes were false ones. With the
wind continuing to shift and fluctuate, Butterworth kept finding
the better air, and NZL 60 opened a lead of 1 minute 16 seconds
with one leg to go. It was business as usual for the closing
stretch of Race 1, with the New Zealanders winning by 1:17.
</P>
</TEXT>
