<P>
   INTERNET _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The network of computers that allows
World Wide Web users access an avalanche of information has slowly
made its presence felt over the last three presidential campaigns,
and may have really come into its own this political season. The
Internet's ability to nearly instantaneously measure and tap
support has been dramatically on display since Arizona Sen. John
McCain's upstart victory in the New Hampshire Republican primary.
But, more than just funneling donations, the Internet is putting
the candidates in touch with supporters and the undecided through
e-mail, online broadcasts and World Wide Web home pages that offer
filing cabinets full of position papers to anyone with a modem.
(Bebbington, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
