<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-2GETHER-REVIEW-NYT     02-20 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-2GETHER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE 5 GUYS, BLEND VOICES, AWAIT FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story has possibilities: a music manager loses his job with
the group he discovered; now he has the chance to create a new
group, but only if he can do it in seven days, in time for ``this
whopper of a gig'' in Jacksonville, Fla. The form has
possibilities: this could be a mock documentary about a fictional
band like ``This Is Spinal Tap.'' But ``2Gether,'' a clunker of an
MTV movie that has its premiere Monday night, is so lacking in wit
and point of view that it makes ``That Thing You Do!,'' Tom Hanks'
film about a Beatles-like American rock band, look like Chekhov.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Buss (Alan Blumenfeld), the manager, knows how the music
business works. ``There are five basic types in every successful
boy band,'' he says, listing them: the bad boy, the shy type, the
little guy, the reassuring older brother and the heartthrob. So how
hard can it be to find five young men who fit those images and can
carry a tune?
</P>
<P>
   He finds his heartthrob, Jerry (Evan Farmer), singing on a
street corner. At the Mr. Teen New York pageant he finds his shy
type, Chad (Noah Bastian), clutching the stage curtain during the
swimsuit competition. And since Chad won't travel without his
brother, Doug (Kevin Farley, who looks a lot like his brother
Chris), Bob signs him on, too, as the older brother type.
Unfortunately, he's a little older than one might expect _ his wife
and two children have just left him _ so Bob puts him in
orthodontia in hopes that teen-agers will identify with him.
</P>
<P>
   The group's bad boy, Mickey (Alex Solowitz), is discovered as he
is about to attack a snack-van operator for selling bad cotton
candy. And Bob finds his cute little guy, Q.T. (Michael Cuccione),
in a juice bar singing ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic'' on
karaoke night. Q.T. has terminal liver disease and smiles big as he
confirms this to the other band members. ``We are going to get so
many chicks,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is actually one of the film's better lines, going for the
risky humor in a young man's taking sexual advantage of his coming
death. The rest of the attempts at humor just seem to establish
that everyone in the story is stupid. Bob tells his group that he's
the boss: ``There can be only one captain on this ship. No
Tennille.'' 2Gether's big hit begins: ``Say it, don't spray it. I
want the news, not the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the supposedly serious dialogue is insipid. When Jerry's
girlfriend (Lauren Smith) urges him not to give up his job at the
hotel to become part of a band, he explains: ``That's all I think
about, Erin, is singing. I mean, when I'm in the hotel carrying
bags or when I'm holding doors open for people, I hum songs to
myself. And when I'm in the parking lot singing with the guys,
that's like my No. 1 element.''
</P>
<P>
   The vapidity seems deliberate, and the moral of ``2Gether''
appears to be that in the age of 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys,
with a little slick packaging anybody can become a star. Yet
viewers are asked to love 2Gether and hate Whoa, the famous band
that came before them. The only definite point of view in the
script is that lip-synching is bad. It's good to know that the
current MTV generation and its moral arbiters can agree on
something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
