<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LONDON-THEATER-ART-2T     02-20 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE RESTORED ROYAL COURT, THE PAST IS GIVEN ITS DUE RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Also being filed in `i' category.) 
(nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It may have a princely name, but the Royal Court
Theater is best known for being where John Osborne's ``Look Back in
Anger'' revolutionized postwar British drama in 1956, siccing the
angry young man character and his alienated world on the genteel
tradition of drawing-room mysteries, parlor dramas and comedies of
manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have swept all that crockery away,'' Arthur Miller remarked
in tribute to the pace-setting theater, ``took a mighty arm.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, the muscle has remained in the programming
of gritty, radical works, but it deserted the aging limbs of the
building itself. An Italianate confection built in 1888, it
increasingly groaned and sagged under its own busy history and
finally closed in 1996 for major repairs. Just how major the
repairs would be and how they would be paid for led to some
offstage restoration dramas, but the curtain is now set to rise
again _ the official reopening is Tuesday _ and the new scene looks
to be a characteristically original one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We inherited a theater with a magnificent tradition, an unsafe
stage, dressing rooms which were a disgrace to civilized society
and maximum discomfort for the audience,'' said Sir John Mortimer,
the playwright and author who is the theater company's chairman.
``We took our chance and created a beautiful and welcoming theater,
in which the size of the auditorium is unchanged and the ghosts of
Shaw, Granville-Barker and Osborne will feel as at home as the
challenging, innovative and exciting new writers we are there to
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century the impresario Harley
Granville-Barker made the Royal Court's first mark on British
theater, staging untried plays by people like Shaw, Yeats, Ibsen
and Galsworthy. By the 1930s it had become a movie theater, and in
the 1940s the blitz of World War II put it out of business. Then
came the 1950s and the Royal Court regained stature as a dramatic
foil to the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   When reconstruction began, the ambitions seemed to outdistance
the possibilities. ``We were contemplating creating a proper
working theater out of the shambolic, unhygienic, aesthetically
problematic mess we had,'' said Stephen Daldry, the former artistic
director. ``At one point we thought of knocking the whole thing
down and starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   The site could not have been more restricting. Only 8,000 square
feet, it was ringed by buildings on two sides, a subway station on
a third and the main sewer for southwest London at the back. ``They
told us if we broke into that, the whole Serpentine would flood
into the theater, `` said Steven Tompkins, the lead architect,
referring to the lake that snakes through nearby Hyde Park. ``That
raised the stakes somewhat.''
</P>
<P>
   The renovators did not want for advice. Everyone in the British
theater world, it seemed, had a sense of possessing a part of the
broken-down jewel box of a theater with its intimate 400-seat house
and its stately facade of columns and pediments and ornamental
windows overlooking Sloane Square in the Chelsea district.
Memories, stories, impressions and counsel poured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Royal Court, in my day, was the most exciting theater in
London,'' wrote the actress Sarah Miles. ``Its smell lingers still,
ripe pears and honey dripping off old, dusty walnut. Can you please
make sure it smells the same?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a grudging affection for its crumbling state. ``I'm
going to miss the throaty roar of the ladies' toilet just off the
stalls flushing loudly in the middle of many a great and moving
monologue,'' said the director Terry Gilliam, ``often just the
right touch of a sorely needed reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Alan Bennett remembered dozing off during a
rehearsal and waking suddenly when the fourth-story window he was
leaning against began to give way. The actress Lindsay Duncan
recalled waiting in the cramped wings, listening for her cue above
a howling sound system and thinking, ``Please God, oh please God _
anybody _ please destroy this building.''
</P>
<P>
   For the actress Maureen Lipman, the Royal Court was ``a place
that vibrated with excitement. It seemed daring, iconoclastic,
intrigue-filled, fashionable, feisty _ before the word existed _
and entirely the place one wanted to be accepted by.''
</P>
<P>
   People prided themselves on surviving its constricted
passageways and damp and drafty backstage areas. The playwright
Richard O'Brien remembered when a young director from a struggling
country theater saw the actress Coral Browne walking down the Royal
Court steps with a friend and asked her excitedly if she would star
in his next production. ``You see,'' she said, turning to her
friend, ``you work here and people think you'll work anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Rickson, the current artistic director of the Royal Court,
said the renovating team wanted to preserve the love-hate
relationship. ``We knew we had to be respectful of our early
history without being precious about it,'' he said. He pointed
upward to the curving rim above the first balcony and made a face.
``There used to be cream-colored stucco there,'' he said through
the grimace, ``the kind of thing that some theater restorations go
in for, all prettified duck-egg blue and pink. You can't put the
dirty world that we put onstage into a place like that.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In place of the unlamented stucco, the design team put nothing,
leaving exposed the riveted cast-iron plating they uncovered from
the original construction. It was an approach they used around the
building, letting the past of the theater catch up with the present
as a stripped-down narrative told through chipped bricks from
wartime bombing, patches of painted plaster from a one-time
executive suite, builders' wall scribblings, the ghostly traces of
steps from a vanished staircase and the grillwork windows from the
famously noisy old women's lavatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger for the Royal Court was that the physical problems
would be solved with impeccable contemporary taste, but people
would still turn up and say, `It's got no soul, something's been
lost, everything difficult or anomalous or humane has been bleached
out by the forces of good design,''' Tompkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Rickson said they wanted to evoke the tension of being a radical
theater in a fashionable neighborhood. The theater is, in the end,
a place with royal in its name and rebellion on its stage. So
beneath the brawny steerage-class ironwork the renovators have
placed ribbed leather seats that would not look out of place in a
gentleman's club. ``Rough and ready with comfort,'' Rickson said.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are tan, the metalwork burgundy, and with the muted
lighting in the domed, narrow house, the atmosphere takes on a
shadowy sepia tone that suggests lurking mystery, maybe even
danger. The lack of ornamentation leaves sightlines uncluttered,
and the iron horseshoe along the edges of the balcony embraces
vision and propels it forward. The renovators seem to have never
forgotten they were building a theater.
</P>
<P>
   Walk about the place with the four principals in the
reconstruction _ Daldry, Rickson, Tompkins and Vikki Heywood, the
executive director _ and you find that they have become such a
seamless team that a thought that begins with one of them ends up
with another.
</P>
<P>
   Take the seats. Daldry said he was fond of running his nails
over the new leather to accelerate the breaking-in process. ``It
has to be knocked about a bit,'' he said. Tompkins said it needed
to mellow, like whiskey. He settled into one of the seats, with its
retractable armrests, to illustrate the cozy alignment with its
neighbors, and said it contributed to a communal spirit of
theatergoing. ``We don't want people to lean back because then you
become too disengaged with what's going on onstage,'' Rickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Daldry added, ``We don't want them to be snooze seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Rickson demonstrated how railings placed in front of the balcony
seats make audience members lean forward and become engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Heywood stepped forward when the conversation turned to
financing. The $43 million project benefited from a $30 million
grant from the National Lottery and a $5 million contribution from
the Jerwood Foundation, an arts-loving charity. ``Please remember
to call the theaters by their full names,'' she implored. The Royal
Court's two performance spaces are the Jerwood Upstairs Theater and
the Jerwood Downstairs Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerwood money put the project over the top, but it caused a
ruckus last year in London's cultural salons when some of the Royal
Court playwrights objected to it as commercial intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rickson dismissed the complaints: ``It's more important what's
happening inside a theater than what it's called.''
</P>
<P>
   With nowhere to go on either side, the renovators came up with
the idea of building down, excavating from beneath the theater and
the eastern end of Sloane Square a sizable area housing a
restaurant, bars, a kitchen, bookshop and bathrooms. In their
unembroidered way, they call the cafe Food and Bar.
</P>
<P>
   The generous lobby windows and entrance give out onto the
square. A red drumwall by Antoni Malinowski forms the back of the
theater space and also links the two floors visually, dispatching a
vibrant, inviting signal out across the busy square. The smaller
upstairs theater is reached by a staircase that narrows
deliberately, Daldry said, to lend the impression of climbing into
an attic to hear a story.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years that its Chelsea headquarters was under
construction, the Royal Court's English Stage Co. kept busy,
putting on 40 plays at two theaters in the West End, the Duke of
York's and the New Ambassadors. The plays included Conor
McPherson's ``Weir,'' David Hare's ``Via Dolorosa,'' Martin
McDonagh's ``The Leenane Trilogy'' and Mark Ravenhill's ``Shopping
and ...'' For its reopening, the Royal Court is staging a new play
by McPherson called ``Dublin Carol,'' which started previews last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Opening night was supposed to have been Jan. 7, but the project
fell behind schedule. With everything else appearing to come out so
well, how did that happen?, Tompkins was asked over the sound of
last-minute sawing and hammering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they say about builders,'' he said. ``They like
to build.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
