right touch of a sorely needed reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Alan Bennett remembered dozing off during a
rehearsal and waking suddenly when the fourth-story window he was
leaning against began to give way. The actress Lindsay Duncan
recalled waiting in the cramped wings, listening for her cue above
a howling sound system and thinking, ``Please God, oh please God _
anybody _ please destroy this building.''
</P>
<P>
   For the actress Maureen Lipman, the Royal Court was ``a place
that vibrated with excitement. It seemed daring, iconoclastic,
intrigue-filled, fashionable, feisty _ before the word existed _
and entirely the place one wanted to be accepted by.''
</P>
<P>
   People prided themselves on surviving its constricted
passageways and damp and drafty backstage areas. The playwright
