<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMBA-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOVA': DNA AS DETECTIVE AGAIN, BUT ON A BIBLICAL CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To support their oral tradition that they are a lost
tribe of Israel, direct descendants of the biblical patriarchs, the
Lemba people of southern Africa point to tribal practices like
circumcision, the avoidance of pork, ritual slaughter techniques,
the wearing of prayer shawls and skullcaps and the ceremonial
blowing of the shofar or ram's horn. Now ``Nova'' reports in
Tuesday's intriguing hour that researchers are using genetic
markers to test whether there is anything to the Lembas' belief in
a Jewish heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the new tests is fascinating. It begins
with the Old Testament's report that the family line of priests,
the cohanim, or Cohens, began with Aaron, the brother of Moses, and
that the role was transmitted down the generations from father to
son. As one of the scholars on the program says, when it comes to
the priestly line, ``The only thing that matters is your
heredity.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a search for similarities in the DNA (in particular
the Y chromosome, which is passed from father to son) between white
Jews named Cohen and the black priests of Lemba. Along the way the
program demonstrates how such an analysis is carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were striking. A group of genetic markers, called
the Cohen Modal Haplotype and found in 10 percent of the general
population, was found in half of the Jewish Cohens. Turning to the
Lemba, researchers found a remarkably high frequency of the Cohen
chromosomes, much higher than in any non-Jewish group tested. In
one Lemba clan, the Buba, about half the men have the Cohen Y
chromosome type.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Tudor Parfitt, an anthropologist from London University who
has taken a leading role in this search, tracks down a somewhat
mysterious village called Sena, to which the Lemba trace their
origins. That leads him into speculation that the Lemba might have
been among the Yemenese Jews who migrated to Africa from the Middle
East perhaps a thousand years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Parfitt is convinced that he is on to something. Whether his
work will offer other clues to the origins of the Lemba or to the
fate of the myth-shrouded 10 lost tribes who were supposedly
expelled from Judea nearly 3,000 years ago remains far from
certain. But he doesn't seem about to give up.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NOVA'
</P>
<P>
   `Lost Tribes of Israel'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paula S. Apsell, executive producer for Nova. Produced for
Cicada Films by Chris Hale. Produced for Nova by David Espar;
narration written by David Espar. A production by Cicada Films for
Nova in association with WGBH/Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
