<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-REPORTER-MEDIA-2TA     02-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REPORTER-MEDIA-2TAKES-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WAR OF `ALL POLITICS, ALL THE TIME,' NBC IS HEAVILY ARMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ ``Good morning, Ann. On this last day of
campaigning, Governor Bush awakes to some good news. Good morning,
Ann. On this last day of campaigning, Governor Bush awakes to some
encouraging news. Good morning, Ann...''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, at 6:53 a.m., with 10 minutes to go before Ann Curry
of NBC's ``Today Show'' would introduce David Bloom's report
previewing South Carolina's Republican primary, Bloom, an NBC News
correspondent, was staring at a camera lens, rehearsing. A
spotlight illuminated the thin clouds of his breath as he repeated
the script he had written the night before, based on an NBC News
poll that showed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas as the solid
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's repetitions, heard in person by an audience of five
chilly spectators near the state Capitol dome, was an apt
distillation of what his employer would do with his work: present
it, with variations and updates, throughout the day and into the
night on the NBC broadcast network, on the MSNBC and CNBC cable
networks and even on the MSNBC.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As he followed Bush around the state, Bloom's image was
broadcast from Columbia to 6.4 million viewers of ``The Today
Show.'' From Clinton, he spoke live to about 150,000 MSNBC viewers
at 10 a.m. Reports from Greenville were heard by 11.3 million
viewers of ``The Nightly News'' at about 6:35 p.m., and by about
285,000 viewers of ``The News with Brian Williams'' on MSNBC a bit
after 9 p.m. Another 295,000 watched a repeat of Williams' program
at 10 p.m. on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical campaign day for Bloom, who is 37 and a former
NBC White House correspondent. He has been covering the Republican
candidates since early summer. Like the days of countless campaign
correspondents, it was relentless. And like the days so familiar to
CNN's campaign reporters or those of The Associated Press, it was
punctuated with updates.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, with NBC News straddling both the broadcast and cable
news worlds, as well as the 24-hour-a-day Web, Bloom and his NBC
colleagues are finding their work spread before more viewers more
often than ever before. And there are signs that this
round-the-clock capability gives NBC News some advantages in
covering the primary campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, Bloom said, the greater exposure helps his
reporting. Politics commands a fervent, if small, following among
cable viewers, many of them political professionals. ``They see us
reporting all through the day,'' Bloom said. ``So who are they
going to pick up the phone and call when they have news? They might
call CBS and ABC. But are they more likely to call us? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, the multiple platforms available to NBC News spread
Bloom's work _ and its costs _ over various network broadcasts, the
two cable networks and Web site.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, which makes heavy use of the coverage, picks up as much
as 35 percent of the total costs of political coverage, according
to an executive. Since MSNBC is a joint venture with Microsoft
Corp., that means if MSNBC runs a loss, Microsoft can pick up $5
million or more of a political budget that, the executive expects,
will exceed $28 million. If, as expected, MSNBC is profitable in
2000, then the cable channel could contribute its full share of $10
million or so.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., is spending more
than it did in 1996, but paying less.
</P>
<P>
   Competing news organizations, particularly Walt Disney's ABC and
Time Warner's CNN, have also invested heavily in campaign coverage.
But their executives know very well how many satellite trucks,
camera crews, hotel rooms, correspondents and producers an extra $5
million could buy. In January, for example, ABC, CBS and the Fox
News cable channel said they had formed a ``news cooperative'' to
save money by sharing footage on breaking news events, like
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Ober, who left the job of CBS News president shortly before
the 1996 birth of MSNBC and now oversees the creation of Web-based
material for E.W. Scripps, noted NBC's current advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gets clearer and clearer _ it's been known for some
time _ that a 24-hour news outlet is critical competitively,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to take care of your costs,'' he added. ``By
dint of having one-and-a-half cable channels on the air, with
politics or with any breaking story, you are on the air 24 hours.
''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said his 24-hour outlets helped him get an exclusive last
Tuesday _that former Republican candidate Gary Bauer would endorse
Bush's main challenger, Sen. John McCain of Arizona. (The
endorsement did little for the Arizona senator, who lost the South
Carolina primary, 53 percent to 42 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   After a McCain campaign official confirmed the Bauer move at
9:30 a.m. on Tuesday, Bloom said, ``I called MSNBC and 30 seconds
later they were on the air.'' Just minutes after that, his report
was on the MSNBC.com site.
</P>
<P>
   The currency of Bauer's endorsement was perishable _ a news
conference was scheduled at noon. Otherwise, Bloom said, ``If I
have a piece of news that I think can hold until the Nightly News
and is not earth-shattering, I will hold it till Nightly, because
that is the broadcast of record.''
</P>
<P>
   Elections have long been a proving ground for network news
divisions and have been a centerpiece of CNN's coverage since its
inception in 1980. Astute political coverage helped make the
reputations of correspondents and anchors like ABC's Peter Jennings
and Cokie Roberts; CBS' Dan Rather and Bob Schieffer; CNN's Jeff
Greenfield and Judy Woodruff, and NBC's own Tom Brokaw and Tim
Russert.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ober and others cautioned, it is important not
automatically to equate quantity with quality.
</P>
<P>
   NBC ``is certainly doing well with volume,'' Ober said. ``But
the differentiators are going to be the Schieffers and Brokaws and
Rathers and Greenfields. It's not just about bulk. It's about
information and the interpretation of the information.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
