<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-REPORTER-MEDIA-2ND     02-20 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REPORTER-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the information.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certainly CNN, which pioneered bulk political coverage, is
devoting considerable resources to the primaries. In the last days
of the South Carolina and New Hampshire primaries, CNN matched NBC
in staffing, sending roughly 50 people to South Carolina and 200 to
New Hampshire. Christa Robinson, a CNN spokeswoman, maintained that
``we basically were the leader in creating the niche'' of cable
political coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the CNN host Larry King moderated a Feb. 15
Republican debate, it drew 2.3 million households, a huge audience
for cable.
</P>
<P>
   Among cable channels, CNN does have an advantage in reach, since
it is available to 77 percent of the nation's 100 million
television households. MSNBC, by comparison, is carried in 54
million households, and Fox, owned by News Corp., on cable, is in
45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Fox News Channel's New Hampshire primetime coverage drew
372,000 households, 70 percent more than MSNBC's 220,000
households. (A spokesman for MSNBC noted that it outdrew Fox among
viewers between 25 and 54 years old, the group advertisers covet.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, NBC News has something no cable rival can match _ a
broadcast network with a news division. When NBC's Tim Russert
interviewed Bush on the Sunday broadcast program ``Meet The Press''
Feb. 13, 4.6 million people watched. And Brokaw's evening news
broadcast on NBC regularly gives prominence to political news.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ABC, which collaborates with The New York Times on
Web-based political coverage, tends to make political reports on
the evening newscast as visible as NBC's. But without a cable
outlet, ABC is hard put to match the volume of NBC's coverage,
though it can offer depth with respected programs like Ted Koppel's
``Nightline.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The strength of the Bush victory Saturday in South Carolina
raises questions about how much longer the primary campaign
coverage will have an engaged audience. Thus far, NBC shows no sign
of retreating on its coverage commitments, or scaling back its
efforts to make MSNBC a real threat to CNN. And on Saturday night,
Brokaw and Russert were prominently featured on NBC's cable
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The risk, MSNBC executives acknowledge, is that the extensive
commitment to political coverage tends to lead cable channels to
inflate marginal events, simply to fill their many politically
oriented shows. On any given day, Bloom may appear on ``Imus in the
Morning'' or Andrea Mitchell's ``Decision 2000'' or Chris Matthews'
``Hardball,'' all on MSNBC, or ``Rivera Live'' on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always juggling'' with worries over inflating news'
importance, the better to fill the maw of a 24-hour channel, Erik
Sorenson, MSNBC's vice president and general manager, said. But, he
added: ``We're not a headline service. We're a big-story service, a
documentary service. We just made the decision to open up the
programming spigot.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the primary race has real suspense, he said. ``And in
the cable news world, suspense is everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
