A2893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-US-AFRICA-0221-COX     02-20 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AFRICA-0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson Calls for African Economic Alliance
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The Rev. Jesse Jackson on Sunday said that if
Africans and African Americans work together they can help each
other to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was addressing the National Summit on Africa here
on the final day of a five-day conference said ``Both sets of
Africans on both sides of the Atlantic need each other.'' The goal
of the conference is to educate Americans about Africa and boost
commercial ties between the United States and the continent,
</P>
<P>
   Citing the end of colonialism, Jackson reminded his audience,
``We are winners. Without dropping a bomb, we beat France, we beat
Britain and we beat Portugal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also echoed the words of many of the summit's speakers,
saying that America needs to do more to slow the AIDS epidemic in
Africa, which has killed nearly 13 million people on the vast
continent.
</P>
<P>
   America must also strengthen economic ties with African nations,
Jackson added.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Jackson spoke, the 2,300 delegates at the conference
unanimously passed a 254 point ``plan of action'' that among other
things asks for an increase funding for AIDS research, education
and prevention in Africa and the United States support of a ban on
land mines and the sale of small arms.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for passage of the Africa Growth and Opportunity
act which was introduced in the U.S. Congress two years ago and
would among other things cut tariffs on African clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in history we have inherited something we
can call a plan,'' said Dr. Mildred McClain, co-chair of the
state-wide Georgia delegation to the summit. ``It will be an
important template for the next decade as we look at U.S.-Africa
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong plan, it's a good plan, it's not a perfect plan,
but it's an excellent start,'' added the Savannah resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want to do is in that document. That's the beauty
of the plan,'' said Earl Shinhoster, chairman of the Georgia
delegation and an Atlanta resident.
</P>
<P>
   Although the participants were impressed with the outcome of the
summit, several said they were concerned the event attracted few
young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so disappointed that we did not have enough student
delegates,'' especially since Howard University is right in the
Summit's back yard, said McClain, who brought three students along
with her delegation.
</P>
<P>
   She said young African Americans' involvement in the planning
and attendance of the summit would have served as a bridge to
improving relations with Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
