<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WHOOPI-Q&AMP;A0221-COX     02-20 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHOOPI-Q&AMP;A0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whoopi promises she won't `be boring'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask Whoopi Goldberg the key to a life-fulfilling
career and one word keeps cropping up: consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a kid from the projects,'' she says. ``I look the same as
when I started. I guess I'm consistent. I say the same things. I
try to be a fairly good person and try to put something back into
the world. I think people are happy I try to make the effort. One
doesn't always succeed, but they do have to make the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg has all the trappings: the Oscar she won for 1990's
``Ghost,'' money (her ``Hollywood Squares'' game show deal alone
brought her $6 million) and worldwide notoriety from her lead role
in 1985's ``The Color Purple'' to ``Girl, Interrupted,'' now
playing in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian and actress will be in Atlanta as the first in a
series of notable women appearing in ``Unique Lives &AMP;
Experiences,'' a lecture series.
</P>
<P>
   She's talking by phone on this early morning while riding from
her New York home to an appearance on ABC's ``The View.'' ``I was
up before the chickens,'' she says. ``I was whispering to them what
kind of eggs to lay.''
</P>
<P>
   And she talked openly on a variety of subjects: from criticism
lobbed at Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John Rocker to her opinions
about the recent Oscar nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've only been to metro Atlanta a couple of times. What's
your impression?
</P>
<P>
   A: I like Atlanta. It's sort of becoming a company town. CNN and
all. I like it because it's got a lot of history. America is really
a younger country. But a lot of what went on and shaped the state
of the union happened in Atlanta. It's also very diverse. ``I'm
looking forward to having some fun,'' Goldberg says from New York.
``I don't know yet what I'm going to say in Atlanta, but it ought
to be interesting. I'll never be boring,'' she says optimistically.
Q: How did the words of John Rocker strike you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't believe that's how he feels. I think he got caught up
in something that we know because we've been around journalists.
And you say things not realizing what they're going to look like
(in print). We'll never know the tone of what he said. When you
read it, it reads really ugly. He didn't realize _ as some people
don't when you're doing interviews _ what it's going to look like.
Sometimes you go to interviews with (a member of your staff) so
they can kick you when you do dumb stuff. I doubt he really feels
that way. At least I hope not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're an Oscar insider. What does the Academy have against
Jim Carrey?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think they have anything against him. Who would you
eliminate (from the best actor nominees)? It's a tough year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Anything surprise you about the nominations?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nobody had said a word about Toni Collette (a supporting
actress nominee for ``The Sixth Sense''). Also, I think
``Magnolia'' is by far the best film of the year, and it didn't get
a best picture nomination. Tom Cruise is brilliant in it. He's
earned this. Without him in ``Rain Man,'' Dustin Hoffman's
performance that year would not have gotten the Oscar. I think in
many years past, Tom has been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: There's Denzel Washington and Michael Clarke
Duncan. Isn't it funny that the two black men who are nominated are
behind bars in their movies. Very strange. Very Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was it like making ``Girl, Interrupted''?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a hard movie. I love Winona Ryder because she's a good
woman. I love the fact she fought to get it done. But, basically, I
think I look a bit like a broccoli spear in it. And for the first
time I was one of the oldest people on the set. The girls were
really great. They asked me a lot of questions about lots of
movies. It was kind of good to have a body of work to look back on
and talk to people about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell me about Angelina Jolie that I don't
already know?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably nothing. Let's leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Part of ``Unique Lives'' is a question and answer segment. So
let's say you're in the audience for Margaret Thatcher. What would
you ask her?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably if she felt as strongly about her kinship to
American politics as she publicly demonstrated. I have a funny
feeling that she went farther to the right than she wanted to. I
don't know why I feel that, but I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What would you ask Candice Bergen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whether she felt that after all the years of waiting to find
just the right thing, whether she found it in ``Murphy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what would you ask Barbara Bush?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
