<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WATTS-PROFILE-ART-NYT     02-20 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATTS-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA'S WATTS, A RISING REPUBLICAN STAR, DOES THINGS HIS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. is the only black Republican in Congress. He
is also the communicator in chief for his party in the House, and a
rising national conservative star.
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks ago, Watts nearly called it quits, frustrated
with his job and its strains on his family back in Oklahoma. He
changed his mind only after constituents in his district, which is
83 percent white, urged him to run again. Speaker Dennis Hastert
begged him to stay in a 40-minute conversation, and his wife and
five children went along with his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deciding factor was that my family said, `We are willing
to stand with you for re-election,''' said Watts, dressed in a dark
pinstriped suit and black cowboy boots in his airy private office
in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Had the 42-year-old former University of Oklahoma football hero
stepped down, it would have been a stinging setback for House
Republicans, who elected Watts two years ago to be conference
chairman, the fourth-ranking leadership job, in an effort to reach
out to African-Americans and shed the image they had under Newt
Gingrich as a party of older white men.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Watts' threatened retirement seems to have swelled his
bully pulpit and his status among House leaders, although he
insists there was no quid pro quo. Last week, for example, Hastert
appointed Watts to lead a group of House Republicans investigating
cybersecurity issues in the wake of recent attacks on high-profile
Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The blizzard of daily faxes and e-mail messages from Watts to
official Washington and beyond seems to have intensified in the
past month. ``The photo-op presidency continues,'' Watts declared
in one typical press release, after President Clinton's news
conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   But honing a common message for all 222 House Republicans has
been an elusive goal. ``Republicans like to talk analytically, they
like to talk legislatively and they like to talk about process,''
Watts said. ``We lose most Americans when we talk in terms of the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   To retain or expand their narrow six-seat margin in November,
House Republicans must connect with voters on a gut level or, as
Watts puts it, ``talk to people in ways they want to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Watts noted, Republicans have long championed
``family values,'' but their handling of that theme has left the
party looking hardhearted at times. ``I don't think you can talk
about `family values' in a way that makes a single mom feel like
she doesn't love her kids as much as my wife and I love our kids,''
he said. ``That's one simple thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts is trying to sand the sharp edges off the public's
perceptions of conservatives, a word he concedes is just as likely
to conjure former Gov. George Wallace of Alabama as, say, Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call it compassionate conservatism; I call it
common-sense conservatism,'' said Watts, an early and ardent
supporter of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for president. Watts
would probably land a top job in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Watts' signature issue, community renewal, fits both of those
descriptions. He disagrees with the liberal premise that government
spending programs help black people, and instead would rely on tax
breaks to help improve education, job training and housing in poor
urban and rural settings. He would use religious institutions,
rather than secular agencies, to carry out the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are underserved communities that you have to focus
attention on in order to get them to the point where they can
compete,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Being the lone black Republican officeholder on Capitol Hill
carries its own burdens. When Donna Brazile, Vice President Al
Gore's campaign manager, who is black, suggested that Republicans
show off prominent African-Americans like Watts and Gen. Colin L.
Powell ``because they have no program, no policy,'' Watts called
her remarks ``racist'' and ``appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are crosses people would love me to bear,'' Watts said.
``Some would love for me to play the role of the black
conservative. I feel no burden to play that role.''
</P>
<P>
   So he resists attempts to make him toe the conservative line on
some issues that are important to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you talk about affirmative action, it's a pretty good
guess that old Watts will get a call,'' Watts said. (For the
record, Watts has advised Republicans to go slowly on opposing
racial quotas and preferences.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good guess I'm one of the first members called
whenever something about the Confederate flag comes up,'' he said,
sitting across from a portrait of the abolitionist Frederick
Douglass. (Watts says that South Carolina should remove the
Confederate flag that flies above its state Capitol.)
</P>
<P>
   Julius Caesar Watts Jr. was born and reared in Eufaula, Okla., a
small farming community, where his father was a Baptist minister
who made ends meet by also working as a police officer and a cattle
trader. He was one of two black children who integrated his
elementary school and was the first black quarterback on his high
school football team.
</P>
<P>
   Watts voted for Democrats as late as the 1988 presidential
election. But he switched parties in 1989 after he became
disillusioned with the Democratic Party's leadership. In 1990, he
ran for a seat on the state Corporation Commission, a utility
regulatory board, and won.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the House in 1994 after a hard-fought primary
campaign, he captured national attention by delivering a passionate
speech at the 1996 Republican National Convention. A year later,
Watts gave the official Republican response to President Clinton's
State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Watts has battled other top House Republicans,
notably Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, for control of
the party's message. He insists those feuds are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our styles are different,'' Watts said of himself and DeLay.
``Tom is smack in the face, 100 miles an hour. I'm a lot more laid
back, wanting to build coalitions and bring in new people. He uses
a hammer. I use a carrot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
