<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MILOSEVIC-CRACKDOWN-1     02-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-CRACKDOWN-1400(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC MOUNTS AN ELECTION-YEAR CRACKDOWN ON HIS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The Yugoslav government of President
Slobodan Milosevic _ its support sliding in an election year _ has
sharply intensified attacks on the democratic opposition and the
news media, calling them traitors and using a draconian press law
to intimidate and impoverish independent publications.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lawsuits, government officials have used open threats of
possible violence.
</P>
<P>
   In a bellicose speech last week to his party congress, Milosevic
called the opposition ``a group of bribed weaklings and blackmailed
profiteers and thieves,'' bought ``with substantial financial
resources funneled from abroad.'' Deputy Prime Minister Vojislav
Seselj of Serbia threatened ``to liquidate'' the independent media,
which he called ``treacherous.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Milosevic left Serbia's disunited democratic
opposition and his urban intellectual opponents a small space in
which to air their opinions, knowing that he could use the cover of
the law to further marginalize or repress them.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the lost war over Kosovo and new efforts by
the opposition _ and Washington _ to oust Milosevic, his
authorities are showing that harsher face.
</P>
<P>
   After a new year's interview in which Milosevic advertised the
crackdown, they are using the press law to damage newspapers and
particularly an independent printing house, ABC Grafika, which
publishes the newspaper Glas Javnosti and prints many other
independent papers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The public information law was enacted on Oct. 20, 1998. Since
then, more than 60 cases have been brought, with fines totaling
more than $1 million _ extremely large in a country where the
average monthly income is now less than $50 _ and the pace has
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, independent media were fined more than $600,000, more
than half of that in suits against ABC Grafika, either for material
in Glas Javnosti or for printing the daily bulletin of last year's
failed political rallies against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   With some presses already seized and the financial police
investigating possible irregularities, the company is battling
bankruptcy, and Glas Javnosti's editor quit because of the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what the regime is doing, it seems they want to
shut us down,'' said Slavoljub Kacarevic, general manager of the
publishing house and now editor in chief of Glas Javnosti. ``The
regime is definitely showing a crueler face, and the way this law
is being implemented is far worse than a year ago. Now they just
fine you every month; it's endless. We look back fondly to the
times when they just banned you for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fifth consecutive trial resulting in a fine for the
daily Danas, its deputy editor, Bozidar Andrejic, said, ``The
bottom line of the punishments is the preplanned wearing down of
the targeted media.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Tanjug, the official press agency, has sued Danas under the
law. On Friday, Danas was fined another $8,000 for quoting
druggists who deplored low-quality imported pharmaceuticals. Danas'
lawyer, Gradimir Nalic, said, ``I expect they'll be in court now
once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the police went to Glas Javnosti to confiscate
some of its electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now legalized chaos, with no protected normative
standards of journalism,'' said Snjezana Milivojevic, a media
analyst who was fired last year from her teaching position at
Belgrade University in a political purge.
</P>
<P>
   Gordana Susa, president of the Independent Journalists
Association of Serbia, says that while editors deny that they are
censoring themselves, ``they are engaging in comforting
self-delusion.''
</P>
<P>
   After the murder in Belgrade this month of the Yugoslav defense
minister, Pavle Bulatovic, Seselj called independent journalists
traitors and accomplices, charging that they took money and
direction from the same governments that bombed Yugoslavia over
Kosovo and, Seselj alleged, that ordered the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gloves are off,'' Seselj said repeatedly. ``Don't think
that we're going to let you kill us off like rabbits, and that
we'll be coddling and caring for you like potted plants. Anyone who
works for the Americans must suffer the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What consequences?'' he went on. ``The worst possible.'' He
named newspapers and radio stations like B2-92, Danas, Glas
Javnosti and Blic _ only the first two of which get Western aid.
</P>
<P>
   In his new year's interview, Milosevic insisted that many
private broadcasters and publishers ``are under the full financial
and political control of some Western governments,'' with the
``task to destabilize the country.'' A key problem, he said, is
poor enforcement of the press law.
</P>
<P>
   The signal given, government ministers are using the law to sue,
bringing cases before government-appointed judges, and state-owned
media are suing independent media. Editors and publishers must pay
fines within 24 hours or face jail and the confiscation of their
property.
</P>
<P>
   The press law puts the burden on the media to prove the truth of
any assertion, even the cited opinion of a quoted person or
organization.
</P>
<P>
   So in December, a small newspaper and its editor in the town of
Vranje were fined $22,000 for printing part of a Western human
rights report that contained material, already published in the
newspaper, about Albanians fleeing town to escape the draft. The
editor suggested that the real cause was another article suggesting
corruption by local officials of Milosevic's party.
</P>
<P>
   Blic, Danas and Studio B were fined for printing a statement by
the Serbian Renewal Movement, the largest opposition party, which
accused two senior officials of organizing an attempt on the life
of the party's leader, Vuk Draskovic. Kacarevic, stung by previous
fines, left out the names, which he later admitted was
self-censorship.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have ordinarily left alone the small-circulation
weeklies of opinion Nin and Vreme, which sell fewer than 10,000
copies each, mostly to people who oppose Milosevic anyway. But this
month, Nin and its editor were fined about $13,000 for an interview
describing the dismissal of law professors.
</P>
<P>
   With local and federal elections due this year and elections in
Serbia _ Yugoslavia's larger part _ next year, one explanation for
the crackdown may lie in the new reach of some independent papers,
notably the daily tabloid Blic.
</P>
<P>
   Independent newspapers like Danas sell about 10,000 copies a
day. But Glas sells about 70,000, and Blic, owned by a Serb living
in Austria, is selling close to 200,000. Together, that is
significantly more copies than all official papers combined.
</P>
<P>
   Blic, a fundamentally serious newspaper with spoonfuls of
gossip, Hollywood and cheesecake, covers the opposition thoroughly,
if not too critically. Its soft-spoken editor, Veselin Simonovic,
said, ``The biggest danger of that law is self-censorship.'' He
tries to work as if it does not exist, he said, but notes that his
journalists and editors constantly press him to read their copy,
``to make me responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's government is in trouble, Simonovic said. ``They use
the law when they are losing support or feeling nervous,'' he said.
``The level of pressure rises as their polls drop.''
</P>
<P>
   The government continues to maintain tight control over the
national television and has increasingly jammed the signal of
Studio B in Belgrade, which is run by Draskovic's party.
</P>
<P>
   But the government is working on a new telecommunications law,
and ``we expect the electronic media will be pressured in the next
stage,'' Susa said. The opposition controls most major towns in
Serbia, with its own radio or television stations. Many are members
of the Association of Independent Electronic Media, which
distributes B2-92's respected news program throughout much of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   After Seselj's attack on B2-92, the association's president,
Veran Matic, said he feared that the government would shut down the
station, formed after the authorities seized his original station,
B-92, during the Kosovo war. ``It's clear that neither myself nor
the people who work at B2-92 feel safe,'' Matic said, ``and we
expect that the radio could be banned again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-20 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN PEPPERS BUSH WITH FRESH ATTACKS IN BID TO WIN MICHIGAN  
 &HT;     (Eds: Dateline stands for Lansing dateline in Hearst budget.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain unleashed a fiery bid
Sunday to rebound from his defeat in South Carolina's Republican
presidential primary, peppering Gov. George W. Bush with fresh
attacks in the critical Michigan primary _ the first
industrial-state showdown of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain vowed to ``get up off the floor'' from his loss Saturday
and relentlessly attack the Texan over the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sending the message that he is ``the reformer and Governor Bush
is not,'' McCain told several thousand students at Michigan State
University here that he is more determined than ever to carry on
with his uphill fight to wrest the nomination from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said popular support for his ``great crusade'' to reform
politics is ``what makes me get off the floor after taking a punch
and going right back at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot, who endured torture for more than five
years in a North Vietnamese prison, told the enthusiastic crowd,
``My friends, I lived in a hotel once where there were no mints on
the pillow. I know how take a punch and I know how to fight back.
I'm going to be fighting for you because you deserve a better
government than the one you have today.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain launched his most sustained ridicule of Bush's claims to
be a reformer. He accused the governor of tolerating a
no-holds-barred campaign-finance system in Texas and suggested that
Bush would permit special interests to seize control the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, McCain accused Bush of boosting state
spending in Texas by more than 36 percent during his tenure _
exceeding the 20 percent increase in federal spending recorded by
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who do you want _ a big-spender non-reformer or do you
want the guy who has a record?'' McCain asked the university
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush is reformer, I am an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he told reporters on his campaign bus that ``anyone who
believes that George Bush is a reformer believes in the tooth
fairy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew to Michigan early Sunday morning and headed for GOP
strongholds around Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, last night lifted my spirits, and my spirits are
</P>
<P>
   still high,'' he said after attending Sunday morning church
</P>
<P>
   services. He added, ``I'm going to continue to talk about how to
bring our country together. I'm going to talk about a better
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also underscored a familiar theme _ that Democrats
shouldn't choose the Republican nominee. He referred to a Michigan
lawyer, Geoffrey
</P>
<P>
   Fieger, who represented suicide advocate Jack Kervorkian.
Fieger, Bush said, has been ``making noises'' about voting in
Tuesday's Republican primary. But Republicans should tell him,
``You're not going to pick the
</P>
<P>
   Republican nominee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed relaxed after his 53 percent to 42 percent victory
over McCain in South Carolina, a victory that was crucial to the
governor since McCain beat him by 19 percentage points in the Feb.
1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan Bush and McCain are in a statistical tie in the
polls. The Detroit News, which showed McCain ahead of Bush 49
percent to 42 percent last week, released a new poll Sunday showing
that McCain's lead had narrowed to 40 percent to Bush's 38 percent.
Michigan, a swing state in presidential elections, has voted
Republican in 8 of the 13 presidential elections since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping his ``reformer with results'' theme will connect
with voters here, as it did in South Carolina and that voters here
will see McCain, not Bush, as the purveyor of negative attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Michigan voters said they were watching the contest closely
before making their final decision. Bob Anderson, 42, attending a
McCain rally in Livonia, a Detroit suburb, said he wanted to see
how the two candidates ``stand the heat'' and added, ``What they're
doing to each other is nothing compared to what Al Gore will do to
them in the fall campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Noga, 60, a franchise development specialist living in
Sterling Heights, Mich., said, ``I'd hate see Michigan sit back and
act like a big sister to little South Carolina.'' Noga added, ``I'd
rather see us do something to help the McCain _ a candidate who can
inspire us to have that feeling about America that we've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would win Tuesday's primary in his home state of
Arizona but needed a victory in Michigan to sustain his
hard-pressed challenge. Asked if Michigan was a ``must-win state,''
McCain replied: ``It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Livonia rally, McCain touted his his willingness to
overhaul the campaign finance system and to take on the ``iron
triangle of lobbyists, money and legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you want your government back, a government
that's been stolen by the special interests and the big money
people _ a system that George Bush wants to perpetuate _ then
you're going to vote for me and you're going to get our vote out,''
McCain declared.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in contrast to Bush, he would make sure that the
GOP was ``not a party of exclusion, not a party of the special
interests, not a party of these pork barrelers in Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We've lost our way since Ronald Reagan was elected
in 1980, and I'm going to bring us back.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest in Michigan marks a turn in the primary road from
small states toward more populous, industrial states.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, with a population of 9.8 million and 18 electoral
votes, is the most politically powerful state to host a
presidential primary so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The four states that have already held primaries or caucuses _
Iowa, New Hampshire, Delaware and South Carolina _have a combined
population of 8.6 million and just 22 of the 270 electoral votes
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, working to pick up the support of Michigan's influential
Roman Catholic community, picked up the endorsement of Rep. Peter
King, R-N.Y., a Catholic who had formerly pledged his support to
Bush. King said that he was switching to McCain because Bush had
demonstrated a ``willingness to take any road the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   King told the Associated Press that he decided to support McCain
after Bush spoke at Bob Jones University during the South Carolina
primary. The southern Baptist school prohibits inter-racial dating
and critics say its officials have expressed anti-Catholic
positions. About 30 percent of Michigan voters identify themselves
as Catholic, according to exit surveys in past elections.
</P>
<P>
   King said America needs ``a Reagan conservative who will not
yield to the temptation of pandering in ways that support
bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the Texas governor regrets
King's decision but ``respects Congressman King's right to be
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
