<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-BOBSLED0221-COX     02-20 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOBSLED0221-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Hines bails out of sled, loses race
</P>
<P>
   By Karen Rosen
</P>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Garrett Hines bailed out of the Winter
Goodwill Games a little early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When his two-man bobsled flipped over at turn 12, the brakeman
from Atlanta calmly ``kicked out of the sled'' as it barrelled down
the track, runners up, at just under 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Was that like jumping out of a moving car?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never jumped out of one, so I don't know,'' said Hines, a
1998 Olympian who was 10th in the two-man and fifth in the four-man
competition in Nagano. ``As soon as my body hit the ground, I got
out.''
</P>
<P>
   He claimed he didn't have any bumps and bruises, while driver
Todd Hays, who stayed with the sled to the finish line at Mt. Van
Hoevenberg, had abrasions on his shoulder and hurt his calf.
</P>
<P>
   This was only Hines' second crash as a bobsledder, and he gave
it a 3 on a scale of 10, with 10 being the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do it again, you gave me a heart attack,'' his wife
Ileana said later as they shared a meal at the Olympic Training
Center.
</P>
<P>
   She had been watching the run on a monitor at the top of track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock because one second he was in the sled,'' she
said, ``and the next second he was laying on the ice sliding
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines and Hays, who form the USA 2 team, were in fourth place
when they crashed. Teammates Brian Shimer, who re-injured the
cartilage in his ribs due to the G-forces at Turn 10, and Pavel
Jovanovic took the bronze behind Latvia and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian team had crashed just before Hines and Hays pushed
onto the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a really bad feeling in my stomach, it felt like a
really bad omen,'' said Ileana Hines.
</P>
<P>
   But her husband wasn't intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get to the top of the hill, it's a part of the
sport,'' he said, ``but you try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because drivers got only six training runs on the brand-new
$24-million track, the inexperience cost some of them. After two
runs Saturday, Hays had warned, ``If you get late in (Turns) 18, 8
and 12, you're in real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   He never made it to 18. He was trying a new line at 12 and
entered it a little too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure took us up and we couldn't come down,'' Hines
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least not right-side up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one race I probably didn't get upset at by losing,''
he said. ``It's the Goodwill Games, not a World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines, who took last year off, was disappointed that he won only
one World Cup medal this year, a silver in a four-man bobsled
driven by Shimer at Igls, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Hays work well together and were sixth at the
recent World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garrett Hines is the best push athlete in the world and I'm
lucky enough to have him,'' Hays said of the former football
player.
</P>
<P>
   Hines doesn't accept the compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're able to beat our competitors on a consistent basis,
then we can say we have some of the best pushers and drivers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Steve Maiorca said that Hays and Hines have some of
the fastest starts in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they stay together the next couple of years,'' he said,
``they're going to be a team to deal with come Olympic time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
