<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY CHARGES 3 KURDISH MAYORS WITH SUPPORTING TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Last Thursday night, Mayor Feridun Celik of
the mainly Kurdish city of Diyarbakir dined with government
officials and foreign ambassadors at a glittering banquet in Ankara
honoring the visiting Swedish foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, he was eating prison food after being taken
into custody on charges that he was secretly supporting Kurdish
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Celik is one of three Kurdish mayors who were arrested over the
weekend on similar charges as the Turkish authorities seemed caught
up in a sudden internal debate over how to deal with Kurdish
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   After December, when the European Union accepted Turkey as an
official candidate for membership, European leaders said they hoped
some formula would soon be found to end the long and violent
confrontation between Turkish and Kurdish nationalism. With the
leader of Kurdish guerrillas, Abdullah Ocalan, under arrest and
calling on his followers to lay down their arms, the moment seemed
propitious.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, however, much of that hope has collapsed.
European diplomats said that Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's
ambitious goal of bringing Turkey into the European Union by 2004
now seems completely unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Turkey and the union chilled unexpectedly last
week after government officials refused to allow members of the
European Parliament to visit an imprisoned Kurdish political
leader, Leyla Zana. In an angry protest, the Europeans canceled
their visit.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests of Celik and the mayors of Bingol and Siirt may
prove even more damaging to Turkey's European ambitions. They are
leaders of the more than 35 Kurdish mayors who have won
considerable international support since their election last year.
Many European leaders view them as ideal figures around which to
build a nonviolent Kurdish political movement.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish prosecutors, however, see them quite differently. They
charged that the three had maintained secret contacts with Ocalan's
rebels, giving them money and ``taking instructions'' from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is disturbing,'' said the Swedish foreign minister, Anna
Lindh, who learned of the arrests shortly after her return to
Stockholm. ``It is rather spectacular that they have been arrested
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   The three arrested mayors were among a group of Kurdish
politicians who met with President Suleyman Demirel a few months
ago. Prime Minister Ecevit, however, has refused to receive them.
So have army commanders in the Kurdish region, many of whom
evidently consider them apologists for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey is shooting itself in the foot again by not ever
thinking about how to have a creative policy toward Kurds and how
to use this window of opportunity, this period of calm, and the
willingness of these political Kurds to try to establish a new
approach,'' lamented one European ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these last couple of months the Europeans have really taken
a very positive attitude toward Turkey, but inside Turkey things
seem to be getting worse instead of better,'' the ambassador said.
``There are so many signs lately of a countervailing force, of
circles that want to undermine the really good dialogue that Turkey
and the European Union have had. It is difficult to pinpoint who
these forces are, but they seem to be everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the mayors' arrests, the government body that
regulates broadcasting ordered the television news channel CNN-Turk
off the air for one day as punishment for transmitting what it said
was separatist propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   During the offending program, an interviewer asked his guest if
it might be possible for Ocalan to become a Turkish version of
Nelson Mandela, who led a guerrilla uprising in South Africa, was
imprisoned and then went on to lead his country toward
reconciliation. Simply posing that question was judged to be
advocacy of separatism.
</P>
<P>
   The station is appealing the order for a one-day shutdown. Prime
Minister Ecevit said he had ``a lot of difficulty'' understanding
the sanction, and many newspapers bitterly condemned it. Referring
to the Iraqi president, one carried news of it under the headline:
``Even Saddam Did Not Do This!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
