<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SNOWBOARD0221-COX     02-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SNOWBOARD0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Victory cut short by protest
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ The U.S. men's snowboard team was at cross
purposes in the boardercross at the Winter Goodwill Games Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Wescott of Farmington, Maine, who broke his skateboard in
an earlier round and had to switch to a backup, was celebrating his
victory until he heard over the public address system, ``There is a
protest on the course.''
</P>
<P>
   The protester was teammate Ryan Neptune of Boise, Idaho, the
1999 U.S. champion. Neptune caught the nose of his board under the
start gate in the finals, sending him flying into the fresh snow.
</P>
<P>
   Officials decided to rerun the race. In boardercross, a pack of
riders negotiate an obstacle course, and Wescott and Neptune
crashed into each other during the second race. Wescott was fourth
and Neptune fifth behind Canadian Scott Gaffney.
</P>
<P>
   Although Neptune could complain about the set of the gates, he
couldn't say anything bad about the gates themselves. His company
produces them.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian snowboarder Kim Dunn fell during training and suffered
a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   MEDAL COUNT
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. won 34 of the 113 available medals (11 gold, 10 silver
and 13 bronze) at the inaugural Winter Goodwill Games, more than
twice as many as Canada (15 total, 8 gold). Germany was third with
10 medals, followed by Austria and Norway with eight apiece.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL HERO, PART 1
</P>
<P>
   Hometown favorite Jimmy Shea won men's skeleton by an astounding
2.83 seconds over four runs. He became the first skeleton driver to
break a minute on the track with a 59.91-second third run. Shea
defeated Chris Soule, who had unseated him as U.S. champion this
season. Shea's grandfather Jack, who won two Olympic speedskating
gold medals in 1932 in Lake Placid, and his father Jim, a 1964
Olympian, presented his medal.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL HERO, PART 2
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Hamill spent her summers training in Lake Placid when
she was growing up. ``This is home for me,'' said the 1976 Olympic
champion, who finished fifth among seven skaters in the women's
competition and was just .4 out of third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I didn't come in last for me was a milestone,''
Hamill said. ``I hope I didn't embarrass my daughter. She has to go
back to school on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd loved Hamill, but the self-deprecating skater shrugged
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty much sympathy applause,'' she said. ``The
people were my age (when she won the Olympics) and are my age now,
so they can understand how painful it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Founder Ted Turner said the Winter Goodwill Games have been
budgeted for a ``small loss,'' but ``we get a lot of bang for our
buck.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the total budget is about $30 million, compared to $38
million for an NFL regular-season game on cable ``that lasts less
than three hours. What would you rather have?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This is expensive, but I've never been a small
thinker. I don't like to think small. I like to thnk big, and this
is big. Nobody else ever put on something that approximates the
Olympics every four years.''
</P>
<P>
   The next Goodwill Games will take place in Brisbane, Australia,
in the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
