<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-20 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN PEPPERS BUSH WITH FRESH ATTACKS IN BID TO WIN MICHIGAN  
 (Eds: Dateline stands for Lansing dateline in Hearst budget.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain unleashed a fiery bid
Sunday to rebound from his defeat in South Carolina's Republican
presidential primary, peppering Gov. George W. Bush with fresh
attacks in the critical Michigan primary _ the first
industrial-state showdown of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain vowed to ``get up off the floor'' from his loss Saturday
and relentlessly attack the Texan over the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sending the message that he is ``the reformer and Governor Bush
is not,'' McCain told several thousand students at Michigan State
University here that he is more determined than ever to carry on
with his uphill fight to wrest the nomination from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said popular support for his ``great crusade'' to reform
politics is ``what makes me get off the floor after taking a punch
and going right back at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot, who endured torture for more than five
years in a North Vietnamese prison, told the enthusiastic crowd,
``My friends, I lived in a hotel once where there were no mints on
the pillow. I know how take a punch and I know how to fight back.
I'm going to be fighting for you because you deserve a better
government than the one you have today.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain launched his most sustained ridicule of Bush's claims to
be a reformer. He accused the governor of tolerating a
no-holds-barred campaign-finance system in Texas and suggested that
Bush would permit special interests to seize control the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, McCain accused Bush of boosting state
spending in Texas by more than 36 percent during his tenure _
exceeding the 20 percent increase in federal spending recorded by
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who do you want _ a big-spender non-reformer or do you
want the guy who has a record?'' McCain asked the university
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush is reformer, I am an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he told reporters on his campaign bus that ``anyone who
believes that George Bush is a reformer believes in the tooth
fairy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew to Michigan early Sunday morning and headed for GOP
strongholds around Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, last night lifted my spirits, and my spirits are
</P>
<P>
   still high,'' he said after attending Sunday morning church
</P>
<P>
   services. He added, ``I'm going to continue to talk about how to
bring our country together. I'm going to talk about a better
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also underscored a familiar theme _ that Democrats
shouldn't choose the Republican nominee. He referred to a Michigan
lawyer, Geoffrey
</P>
<P>
   Fieger, who represented suicide advocate Jack Kervorkian.
Fieger, Bush said, has been ``making noises'' about voting in
Tuesday's Republican primary. But Republicans should tell him,
``You're not going to pick the
</P>
<P>
   Republican nominee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed relaxed after his 53 percent to 42 percent victory
over McCain in South Carolina, a victory that was crucial to the
governor since McCain beat him by 19 percentage points in the Feb.
1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan Bush and McCain are in a statistical tie in the
polls. The Detroit News, which showed McCain ahead of Bush 49
percent to 42 percent last week, released a new poll Sunday showing
that McCain's lead had narrowed to 40 percent to Bush's 38 percent.
Michigan, a swing state in presidential elections, has voted
Republican in 8 of the 13 presidential elections since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping his ``reformer with results'' theme will connect
with voters here, as it did in South Carolina and that voters here
will see McCain, not Bush, as the purveyor of negative attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Michigan voters said they were watching the contest closely
before making their final decision. Bob Anderson, 42, attending a
McCain rally in Livonia, a Detroit suburb, said he wanted to see
how the two candidates ``stand the heat'' and added, ``What they're
doing to each other is nothing compared to what Al Gore will do to
them in the fall campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Noga, 60, a franchise development specialist living in
Sterling Heights, Mich., said, ``I'd hate see Michigan sit back and
act like a big sister to little South Carolina.'' Noga added, ``I'd
rather see us do something to help the McCain _ a candidate who can
inspire us to have that feeling about America that we've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would win Tuesday's primary in his home state of
Arizona but needed a victory in Michigan to sustain his
hard-pressed challenge. Asked if Michigan was a ``must-win state,''
McCain replied: ``It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Livonia rally, McCain touted his his willingness to
overhaul the campaign finance system and to take on the ``iron
triangle of lobbyists, money and legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you want your government back, a government
that's been stolen by the special interests and the big money
people _ a system that George Bush wants to perpetuate _ then
you're going to vote for me and you're going to get our vote out,''
McCain declared.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in contrast to Bush, he would make sure that the
GOP was ``not a party of exclusion, not a party of the special
interests, not a party of these pork barrelers in Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We've lost our way since Ronald Reagan was elected
in 1980, and I'm going to bring us back.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest in Michigan marks a turn in the primary road from
small states toward more populous, industrial states.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, with a population of 9.8 million and 18 electoral
votes, is the most politically powerful state to host a
presidential primary so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The four states that have already held primaries or caucuses _
Iowa, New Hampshire, Delaware and South Carolina _have a combined
population of 8.6 million and just 22 of the 270 electoral votes
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, working to pick up the support of Michigan's influential
Roman Catholic community, picked up the endorsement of Rep. Peter
King, R-N.Y., a Catholic who had formerly pledged his support to
Bush. King said that he was switching to McCain because Bush had
demonstrated a ``willingness to take any road the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   King told the Associated Press that he decided to support McCain
after Bush spoke at Bob Jones University during the South Carolina
primary. The southern Baptist school prohibits inter-racial dating
and critics say its officials have expressed anti-Catholic
positions. About 30 percent of Michigan voters identify themselves
as Catholic, according to exit surveys in past elections.
</P>
<P>
   King said America needs ``a Reagan conservative who will not
yield to the temptation of pandering in ways that support
bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the Texas governor regrets
King's decision but ``respects Congressman King's right to be
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 1923EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-1500(2TA     02-20 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-1500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FIGHT NEARS, DE LA HOYA'S BIGGER CHALLENGE MAY BE HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR, Calif. _ A crisis of confidence had struck the
resident of the big cedar log cabin at the corner of De La Hoya
Street and Golden Boy Avenue in this mountain resort town three
hours east of Los Angeles. It clung to him like a sweat-soaked
T-shirt before, during and immediately after his loss to Felix
Trinidad last September, the first loss of his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past six weeks it has dissolved into the pools of
sweat in the makeshift boxing gym that he set up in the four-car
garage that is 50 feet from the main house. It drifted away slowly,
like the puffs of his frosty breath as he tortured his mind and
body running the steep trails in the San Bernardino Mountains above
his house.
</P>
<P>
   Now, whenever doubt tries to creep back in, Oscar De La Hoya
chases it away with a mantra, ``No more Nice Guy!''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (31-1), the former World Boxing Council welterweight
champion, will carry that mantra into the ring with him against
Derrell Coley (34-1-2) in a 12-round bout on Saturday night at
Madison Square Garden _ his first fight in New York since he
leveled Jesse James Leija five years ago. If he is as good as he
looked in a recent training session, and as fit as he says he is,
Coley is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to reach way down in my pockets and do some things
they have never seen from me,'' De La Hoya said. ``That's the way
I'm thinking now. It's there. I just haven't brought it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley sneered at that and predicted he would knock out De La
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says the same thing before every fight,'' Coley said. ``But
then he does the same thing every fight. I don't see him changing
anything from his last fight.''
</P>
<P>
   If Coley is right, then De La Hoya's problem goes deeper than
the crisis of confidence, deeper than previously undisclosed
physical ailments _ injuries to his left hand and left ankle and
the aftereffects of the flu _ that he said kept him from going full
throttle in the Trinidad fight. If Coley is right, it seems that
there could be something in De La Hoya's makeup that prevents him
from breaking through to a level of superiority _ a character flaw
or mental barrier that he can not overcome even with his immense
talent.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-foot-tall poster, advertising the De La Hoya-Trinidad
match as ``The Fight of the Millennium'' still hung in the gym
here, on a wall adjacent to the ring. Was it there for motivation
or as some kind of twisted reminder of what not to do the next time
around?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even noticed it,'' De La Hoya said as he sat on the
ring apron talking about his bout with Coley. ``I guess I just
haven't gotten around to taking it down.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, De La Hoya walked over and carefully took
the poster off the wall. He laid it in the ring face down and
returned to his spot on the ring apron. Later, a smaller poster,
advertising his bout with Coley on Home Box Office, went up.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a quiet training camp for De La Hoya. He has
isolated himself as much as he can in a residential community. He
recently installed black sheet metal over the black wrought iron
fence around his house. He has not had any public workouts. He has
limited his access to the news media since he arrived here shortly
after New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``No distractions,'' he said. ``I haven't even played golf. I
have seen my daughter only once. Nobody has been around except me
and the people in my camp. I've been able to concentrate 100
percent on boxing. I'm feeling good. I'm pain free for the first
time in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The sting of the loss to Trinidad is gone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left quickly, because I know I won the fight,'' De La Hoya
said. ``People that I meet on the street have a lot of respect for
me because they know I won the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   From now on, De La Hoya said, he would not leave anything up to
the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking knockout a lot lately,'' De La Hoya said.
``I don't want to dance and let the other guy move me back. I lost
a lot of respect because of this boxing stuff. I'm not a boxer.
That's not me. That's not my style. I feel more comfortable
standing in front and banging with a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent workout, Joel De La Hoya Sr. watched closely as his
son grunted and furiously threw punches into mitts worn by the
trainer Robert Alcazar. De La Hoya was taking a day off from
sparring after going more than 100 rounds before this session. Each
crisp punch hit a mitt with a solid thud. A hard jab followed by a
lightning fast four-punch combination.
</P>
<P>
   Pop! Rat-a-tat-tat! Alcazar would wince, shake his hands and
raise them again. Over and over for eight rounds.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's father seemed pleased with what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is happy, and healthy for the first time in a long time,''
Joel De La Hoya said. ``He is ready to go. Like a racehorse, ready
for the race.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with his son had been more Svengali than Ward
Cleaver. But lately that has thawed. Before the Trinidad fight, De
La Hoya said he could hardly stand for his father to be at his
training camp for a day. Now, Joel is a daily fixture, being sent
away from the mountain home to Los Angeles only when he begins to
sniffle and it looks as if he may be coming down with a cold or flu
that his son could contract.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya broke the ice with his father late last year at a
charity fund-raiser. The boxer gave an emotional speech praising
his father and then presented him with a gold Rolex watch. The
elder De La Hoya, called to the stage by his son, looked at the
watch and then embraced his son, saying he loved him. It was the
first time Joel had ever made such a public display of affection to
his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always loved him,'' Joel said. ``He knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, De La Hoya has said that his father has never
praised him after one of his professional fights. Joel is asked
which of his son's bouts was the best in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in the Olympics and he won the gold medal,'' Joel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, that was the fight that De La Hoya dedicated to his
mother, Cecilia, who died before De La Hoya went to the 1992
Olympic Games in Barcelona, Spain. What does De La Hoya need to do
to become the very best as a pro?
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be 100 percent healthy and train very hard for a
fight,'' Joel said. ``He will probably be 85 to 90 percent for this
fight. This will be the best one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel, like a lot of his son's boxing fans, is still waiting for
that ultimate performance _ the one that forces De La Hoya to
summon all of his will and drives him to dig into his vast untapped
talent and put on a display of boxing that leaves everyone gasping.
It could be against Coley or it may never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Against Trinidad, De La Hoya put on a masterful display of
boxing for the first eight rounds, fluidly floating around the ring
and tagging the stiff Trinidad at will. If De La Hoya had chosen to
press forward in an all-out attack in those early rounds, he would
probably have won by a knockout. But De La Hoya held back, and then
in the final four rounds he retreated. It looked as if he were
taking the cautious approach and coasting to victory.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, however, said he was physically unable to do what
his instincts were telling him to do: attack Trinidad. Two weeks
earlier, De La Hoya spent two days in bed with the flu. Then, he
twisted his ankle and could not run. A sore left hand became
aggravated and he could not throw a jab in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad,'' he said. ``But I didn't want to make any
excuses, and I didn't want to pull out of the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fight, De La Hoya did not bring up the injuries,
explaining later that it would sound as if he was making excuses.
Instead, he said, the keep-away approach was all a part of his
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the fight plan for Trinidad was the same as it had
been against Ike Quartey _ box and then pick spots to slug it out
and look for the knockout. Though he did not knock out Quartey, De
La Hoya put on one of his finest performances, getting up from a
knockdown and knocking down Quartey twice before capping the fight
with a vicious flurry in the first few minutes of the 12th round.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Clancy, the veteran New York trainer, took the hit for the
loss to Trinidad. Clancy was fired. De La Hoya said there was too
much confusion in his corner during that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point they couldn't even find my mouthpiece,'' he said.
``That's how bad it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is only Alcazar, De La Hoya's brother, Joel Jr., and the
cut man Chuck Bodack in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more tactics,'' Alcazar said. ``We go in and knock them out
as soon as possible. Everybody can keep their own ideas. We're back
to where we used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
