   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   OILPRICES-ECON (Washington) _ For the past year, even as the
price of oil tripled to $30 a barrel from a record low of $10,
policy makers, economists and many in the oil industry itself hewed
closely to the same line: Oil doesn't matter much anymore.
Technology, which depends much less on energy than manufacturing
does, now drives economic growth. Such thinking was, and to a
certain extent remains, conventional wisdom. But it has taken only
a few weeks of $2 a gallon home heating oil, $20 airline ticket
surcharges, and $75 to gas up Ford Expeditions to make people
wonder if oil is really so irrelevant. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Photo refer:
</P>
<P>
   NY-GORE-MRSCLINTON (Albany, N.Y.) _ Al Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton have left the White House nest and are learning to fly on
their own. Sunday at the Wilborn Temple, a red brick historic black
church in downtown Albany packed with 1,500 worshipers, the two
came together for the first time as candidates, he for president,
she for senator from New York. They praised each other to the
rafters, and their spokesmen said the two would be eager to appear
together again. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
