<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2925 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-20 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN PEPPERS BUSH WITH FRESH ATTACKS IN BID TO WIN MICHIGAN  
 &HT;     (Eds: Dateline stands for Lansing dateline in Hearst budget.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ Sen. John McCain unleashed a fiery bid
Sunday to rebound from his defeat in South Carolina's Republican
presidential primary, peppering Gov. George W. Bush with fresh
attacks in the critical Michigan primary _ the first
industrial-state showdown of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain vowed to ``get up off the floor'' from his loss Saturday
and relentlessly attack the Texan over the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sending the message that he is ``the reformer and Governor Bush
is not,'' McCain told several thousand students at Michigan State
University here that he is more determined than ever to carry on
with his uphill fight to wrest the nomination from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said popular support for his ``great crusade'' to reform
politics is ``what makes me get off the floor after taking a punch
and going right back at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot, who endured torture for more than five
years in a North Vietnamese prison, told the enthusiastic crowd,
``My friends, I lived in a hotel once where there were no mints on
the pillow. I know how take a punch and I know how to fight back.
I'm going to be fighting for you because you deserve a better
government than the one you have today.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain launched his most sustained ridicule of Bush's claims to
be a reformer. He accused the governor of tolerating a
no-holds-barred campaign-finance system in Texas and suggested that
Bush would permit special interests to seize control the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, McCain accused Bush of boosting state
spending in Texas by more than 36 percent during his tenure _
exceeding the 20 percent increase in federal spending recorded by
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who do you want _ a big-spender non-reformer or do you
want the guy who has a record?'' McCain asked the university
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush is reformer, I am an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he told reporters on his campaign bus that ``anyone who
believes that George Bush is a reformer believes in the tooth
fairy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew to Michigan early Sunday morning and headed for GOP
strongholds around Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, last night lifted my spirits, and my spirits are
</P>
<P>
   still high,'' he said after attending Sunday morning church
</P>
<P>
   services. He added, ``I'm going to continue to talk about how to
bring our country together. I'm going to talk about a better
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also underscored a familiar theme _ that Democrats
shouldn't choose the Republican nominee. He referred to a Michigan
lawyer, Geoffrey
</P>
<P>
   Fieger, who represented suicide advocate Jack Kervorkian.
Fieger, Bush said, has been ``making noises'' about voting in
Tuesday's Republican primary. But Republicans should tell him,
``You're not going to pick the
</P>
<P>
   Republican nominee,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed relaxed after his 53 percent to 42 percent victory
over McCain in South Carolina, a victory that was crucial to the
governor since McCain beat him by 19 percentage points in the Feb.
1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan Bush and McCain are in a statistical tie in the
polls. The Detroit News, which showed McCain ahead of Bush 49
percent to 42 percent last week, released a new poll Sunday showing
that McCain's lead had narrowed to 40 percent to Bush's 38 percent.
Michigan, a swing state in presidential elections, has voted
Republican in 8 of the 13 presidential elections since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping his ``reformer with results'' theme will connect
with voters here, as it did in South Carolina and that voters here
will see McCain, not Bush, as the purveyor of negative attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Michigan voters said they were watching the contest closely
before making their final decision. Bob Anderson, 42, attending a
McCain rally in Livonia, a Detroit suburb, said he wanted to see
how the two candidates ``stand the heat'' and added, ``What they're
doing to each other is nothing compared to what Al Gore will do to
them in the fall campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Noga, 60, a franchise development specialist living in
Sterling Heights, Mich., said, ``I'd hate see Michigan sit back and
act like a big sister to little South Carolina.'' Noga added, ``I'd
rather see us do something to help the McCain _ a candidate who can
inspire us to have that feeling about America that we've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would win Tuesday's primary in his home state of
Arizona but needed a victory in Michigan to sustain his
hard-pressed challenge. Asked if Michigan was a ``must-win state,''
McCain replied: ``It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Livonia rally, McCain touted his his willingness to
overhaul the campaign finance system and to take on the ``iron
triangle of lobbyists, money and legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you want your government back, a government
that's been stolen by the special interests and the big money
people _ a system that George Bush wants to perpetuate _ then
you're going to vote for me and you're going to get our vote out,''
McCain declared.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in contrast to Bush, he would make sure that the
GOP was ``not a party of exclusion, not a party of the special
interests, not a party of these pork barrelers in Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We've lost our way since Ronald Reagan was elected
in 1980, and I'm going to bring us back.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest in Michigan marks a turn in the primary road from
small states toward more populous, industrial states.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, with a population of 9.8 million and 18 electoral
votes, is the most politically powerful state to host a
presidential primary so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The four states that have already held primaries or caucuses _
Iowa, New Hampshire, Delaware and South Carolina _have a combined
population of 8.6 million and just 22 of the 270 electoral votes
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, working to pick up the support of Michigan's influential
Roman Catholic community, picked up the endorsement of Rep. Peter
King, R-N.Y., a Catholic who had formerly pledged his support to
Bush. King said that he was switching to McCain because Bush had
demonstrated a ``willingness to take any road the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   King told the Associated Press that he decided to support McCain
after Bush spoke at Bob Jones University during the South Carolina
primary. The southern Baptist school prohibits inter-racial dating
and critics say its officials have expressed anti-Catholic
positions. About 30 percent of Michigan voters identify themselves
as Catholic, according to exit surveys in past elections.
</P>
<P>
   King said America needs ``a Reagan conservative who will not
yield to the temptation of pandering in ways that support
bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the Texas governor regrets
King's decision but ``respects Congressman King's right to be
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
