<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-DERBY-PREVIEW-ART     02-20 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-PREVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH YIELD TAKES LEAD AMONG DERBY PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ He may be a Western horse who became an
Eastern winner, and he may simply be a horse who made the most of
the ``track bias'' at Gulfstream Park that favors leaders on the
rail. But whatever he is, after his victory in the Fountain of
Youth Stakes on Saturday at Gulfstream Park, High Yield stood
Sunday at the head of the class of 3-year-olds aiming for the
Kentucky Derby on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   He still had to face several showdowns with the West Coast stars
he abandoned last week: Anees, last year's juvenile champion, who
recently returned to training after suffering a stretched tendon;
Surfside, the talented and tough filly; Captain Steve; War Chant
and The Deputy. And on the East Coast, he still had unfinished
business with Greenwood Lake, Red Bullet and More Than Ready.
</P>
<P>
   But High Yield, the leader pro tem, had a team of all-stars
surrounding him: Michael Tabor, John Magnier and Bob and Beverly
Lewis, the owners; D. Wayne Lukas, the trainer, who has won three
of the last five runnings of the Kentucky Derby; and Pat Day, the
voice of experience, as his jockey.
</P>
<P>
   As Lukas put it, ``We'll have no trouble finding our way around
Churchill Downs,''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, who has won only three times in 10 starts,
nonetheless reminds people of Cat Thief and other stars of the
Lukas barn. He is a warrior with breeding, a son of Storm Cat with
an aggressive crew calling the shots. And Lukas left no doubt
Sunday that, East or West, he had mapped the itinerary for High
Yield en route to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I map out plans for all our horses,'' he said, ``and we'll
keep High Yield in the East now. We know where we want to go. We're
going to follow the same route that we did with Thunder Gulch five
years ago. He won the Fountain of Youth, the Florida Derby and the
Kentucky Derby, And following the Florida Derby, I'll run him in
the Blue Grass Stakes. That's what our plans are for High Yield.''
</P>
<P>
   Other trainers tended to excuse their losses in the Fountain of
Youth by pointing out that the track favored speed all day; in
fact, all season. Seven horses got the lead in seven races Saturday
and held it, including High Yield. And any horse leading on the
inside was almost unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only run over the strip you give us,'' Lukas said. ``We
make our adjustments. The knock on him has been that he lets other
horses run by him. This time, he didn't let anybody run by him.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, neither did Hal's Hope, who ran second all the
way and finished 3\ lengths behind High Yield, nor Elite Mercedes,
who ran third all the way and finished 2{ lengths behind Hal's
Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope, the upset winner of the Holy Bull Stakes at
Gulfstream Park three weeks ago, had one other distinction: an
88-year-old trainer, owner and breeder, Harold Rose, who complained
that because of his age, he was getting more attention than his
horse.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said Hal's Hope would go for a rematch in the Florida
Derby. And his jockey, Roger Velez, added: ``He's going to improve.
I think he'll give High Yield a run for his money next time.''
</P>
<P>
   But several of their rivals decided not to test High Yield or
the Gulfstream ``track bias,'' which gave late-running horses
little chance to overtake the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ken McPeek, the trainer of Deputy Warlock, who finished seventh,
said: ``I'll just be spinning my wheels if I run him here again.
There wasn't any way that a horse was going to close on that kind
of track. He needs a track where he can come from behind, so I'll
run him next in the Spiral Stakes at Turfway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, though, could not shake off the long-range threat
from Greenwood Lake, who made up 20 lengths in the Fountain of
Youth to finish fourth. He was still six lengths behind the winner,
but Nick Zito wasn't dissuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous performance, considering everything,'' the
trainer said. ``It's very hard for a closer to win here; that's the
way the surface has been for 61 years. I can't do anything to make
him stay closer. But it's amazing what he does. The Florida Derby
might be the same scenario, but racing here puts you in a better
position for things later in the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
