</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ENERGY-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO LIFT RESTRICTIONS ON ISRAELI SCIENTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ The Department of Energy has decided to lift
some cumbersome security restrictions on visits by Israeli
scientists to U.S. national laboratories, Energy Department and
other administration officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is included in an agreement scheduled to be signed
later this week by Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson, who arrived
Sunday in Israel on a 10-day tour of energy-producing states,
mostly in the Middle East. The agreement expands scientific and
technical cooperation between Israel and the United States in the
energy area.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is on the agency's list of sensitive countries _ along
with India, Pakistan, Iraq, Iran, North Korea and other states that
have refused to forswear nuclear weapons or are suspected of
secretly pursuing unconventional arms. And so Israeli scientists
face long delays and intensive screening before they can visit the
United States' 17 laboratories run by the Energy Department, seven
of which do at least some secret research.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department officials stressed that the relaxation
would not apply to any secret work done at the three weapons labs
or other facilities. ``Security will never be jeopardized,'' an
energy official said.
</P>
<P>
   Security measures in general were tightened at the national labs
in the fall of 1998 at Richardson's instructions, following
allegations that Wen Ho Lee, a scientist at Los Alamos National
Laboratory, had shared secret information with China. Moreover,
some kinds of U.S.-Israeli cooperation had already suffered as a
result of Jonathan Pollard's spying against the United States for
Israel in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Energy Department officials said Sunday that relaxing
screening requirements for Israeli scientists engaged in joint
research projects covered by the new agreement would enhance
scientific cooperation in energy, which they said was in both
countries' national security interests. About 150 Israeli
scientists visit U.S. labs each year, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, administration officials said, easing requirements
would reward Israel for recent efforts under Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to make peace with its Arab neighbors. Finally, it would
separate Israel, a key Middle Eastern ally of the United States,
from the nations on the Energy Department's sensitive-countries
list.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, interviewed Sunday en route to Israel from Mexico,
where he discussed with senior officials the need for lower stable
oil prices, said the new agreements would ``expand American-Israeli
ties in energy, technology, nonproliferation and scientific
exchanges.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's trip was part of his effort to persuade members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries cartel to lower
oil prices and adhere to schedules that will help maintain stable
prices. In this political season, the administration is feeling
increasing pressure over soaring oil prices, which reached $30 a
barrel last week.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has acknowledged that the administration was ill
prepared for the price increases and that it should have responded
sooner. Richardson, a former Democratic congressman of Hispanic
origin from New Mexico, is said to be on a short list of people
whom Vice President Al Gore is considering as a prospective No. 2
on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Richardson is to sign several documents intended to
strengthen bilateral and regional energy cooperation and
integration and to slow the spread of certain types of weapons and
the scientific expertise that produces them.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the energy agency and its Israeli counterpart are
to schedule a meeting for this year to review their respective
efforts to help former Soviet weapons scientists find new
nonmilitary jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has spent tens of millions of dollars to keep
Russian scientists gainfully employed, and to keep their deadly
expertise away from terrorists.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One new agreement, known as a nonbinding letter of intent,
provides for joint cooperation to enhance detection of underground
nuclear tests, which are banned by the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty. The Senate refused to approve that treaty last year, but
the administration has vowed to continue abiding by its provisions
while searching for better ways to detect undeclared nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has long refused to sign the 1968 Nuclear
Nonproliferation Treaty, whose non-nuclear member states forswear
programs to acquire such weapons, in exchange for assistance with
their civilian nuclear-power programs. Israel is believed to have a
varied, sophisticated nuclear arsenal, but it has consistently
refused to discuss its nuclear-weapons programs publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, Richardson is scheduled to visit Egypt, a
leader of Arab efforts to persuade Israel to give up nuclear
weapons and sign the nonproliferation treaty. Despite their
differences over nuclear issues, Egypt has agreed to help Israel,
which has few indigenous energy sources, meet its growing power
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to reward Barak's efforts to renew the peace negotiations
that were badly damaged by his predecessor, Egypt announced in
December that it would restore a ``peace pipeline'' project to
carry natural gas across the Sinai Desert to Israel and to the
Palestine Authority. The project had been stalled since 1996 after
strains developed between Israel and its Arab peace partners.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, U.S. officials said that Richardson would announce that
the administration would spend $1 million on a joint solar-energy
development project involving Israel, Egypt and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
