<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS STONE U.S. TROOPS IN DIVIDED KOSOVO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT3-5 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 
(rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ Angry Serbs stoned, punched and kicked
U.S. troops in the northern, Serb-dominated district of this town
Sunday, forcing them to beat a hasty retreat and cut short their
part in a citywide search for weapons. German troops also came
under a hail of stones in the same area.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 troops from 12 countries were deployed at dawn
to search apartments and buildings for weapons and explosives in
both the Serbian and Albanian parts of this bitterly divided mining
town of some 90,000 people. It was one of the biggest operations
mounted by NATO-led peacekeepers in Kosovo and an attempt to curb
the violence that has seen 11 people killed and dozens wounded
since Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a U.S. company of 350 men sent up to the north of Kosovo
on Saturday for the operation headed into northern Mitrovica just
after 6 a.m., working with French troops and the U.N. police to
search buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica is Kosovo's most volatile spot. Just a few miles south
of the border with Serbia proper, it in effect is where the
Albanian-dominated province ends and Serbia begins.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian news media regularly denounce U.S. policy in the
Balkans, and hold the Americans most responsible for NATO's bombing
war over Kosovo last spring.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, it was the Americans who immediately encountered
Serb hostility. First, the Serbs objected to an Albanian
translator, who was withdrawn for her safety, said Capt. Russell
Berg, a public affairs officer who was at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, as the troops finished searching one building, a
noisy crowd at a crossroad began to throw snowballs, stones and
bottles at the troops, Berg said. The U.S. commander, Col. Michael
Ellerby, waded into the crowd alone to talk to the Serbs' leader,
Oliver Ivanovic, and appeal for calm.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, his tactic seemed to work. Then something sparked
the violence, and Serbs began jostling and jeering. Ellerby had to
be plucked out by the Italian riot police, and French troops moved
to contain the crowd. Suddenly, the Serbs broke through the French
cordon, and U.S. troops made a quick dash for their vehicles,
according to Harald Doornbos, a reporter for National Dutch Radio
who was with the U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs were punching these GIs, and they were guarding
themselves with their rifle butts,'' he said. ``The Serbs just went
berserk, and then the Americans suddenly left us and ran for their
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Spc. William Putnam, who was in the search unit attacked by the
Serbs, said later: ``They were very belligerent. They wanted to
make a scene. They wanted to push us to a point where we took
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans did not react, however, and pulled out under a
hail of heavy stones and kicks from the crowd, crossing the river
into the southern, Albanian half of town, which remained calm.
Several of the Americans' Humvee vehicles showed cracked windows
from the blows of heavy stones. One soldier suffered a broken nose,
and another a chipped tooth, Berg said.
</P>
<P>
   German troops who moved their troop carriers through the crowd
after the Americans were also pelted with stones. By contrast, the
French, whom Albanians have accused of showing a pro-Serb bias
here, arrived to cheers from the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was commanded by the French, who control the
northern sector of Kosovo, but was personally supervised by the
overall commander of the peacekeepers, Gen. Klaus Reinhardt of
Germany. He has made a point of involving different nations to try
to avoid antagonism and accusations of bias.
</P>
<P>
   French troops have come under frequent stoning attacks from the
Albanians who dominate the southern half of Mitrovica. Last
weekend, two French soldiers were wounded in a firefight with
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs have meanwhile threatened violence against the British
troops who are deployed on a bridge dividing the city. It was not
clear who decided that U.S. troops should move into the Serbian
area for the search operation, but Ivanovic said it was asking for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not so happy because they are Americans, and
because the Americans are more aggressive in the way they search,''
Ivanovic said. ``Their attitude is: `We are here; we have power; we
are in charge.' People were not afraid, but they were angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Serbs were slightly wounded, Ivanovic said, two from Mace
sprayed in their faces, and two from slight head cuts, apparently
from rifle butts. Together with the U.N. police, U.S. troops had
smashed open doors in a students' hostel, wrecking the place
unnecessarily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Public affairs officials said the U.S. troops had finished their
search and were redeployed to another area of the city, so the
fracas did not stop the overall operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to redeploy the troops because we wanted the
operation to go on,'' said Lt. Col. Patrick Chanliau, a French
spokesman, stressing that the aim was to search for weapons, not
move against people.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the haul of weapons was small: 10 Kalashnikov assault guns,
four bolt-action rifles, a machine gun, a pistol, seven blocks of
plastic explosives and one grenade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   French troops and gendarmes continued where the Americans had
left off, moving quietly and without disturbance into apartment
buildings and an old school inhabited by Serbian refugees from
Croatia. They were heavily armed, and wearing body armor.
</P>
<P>
   They were searching specific apartments that had fallen under
suspicion, a French policeman said, asking that his name not be
used. ``We find a lot of arms hidden in the cellars, and hidden in
the furniture,'' he said, showing how he had just discovered two
Kalashnikovs in one apartment, the magazines tucked under a sofa
and the two weapons inside a folding bed. Several women and
children were tidying up after the search, apparently unfazed. But
several Serbian men outside were still angry. ``This is
occupation,'' said Milan Ivanovic, the deputy director of the local
hospital. ``French or Germans or Americans, they are all occupiers.
They want to throw Serbs out of Serbian land. They want us to have
no protection against the Albanians, they want us out of here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
