<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      02-20 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW VALENTINE KNOWS HIS CONTRACT TALKS MUST WAIT UNTIL SEASON'S
END 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ It was news to Manager Bobby Valentine
Sunday when reporters told him that the Mets' co-owner, Fred
Wilpon, planned to wait until after the season to address
Valentine's contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know _ good,'' said Valentine, adding that he planned to
talk to Wilpon himself. ``Now that I heard it, I understand it. I
don't particularly like hearing it, but it is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what it is: a distraction, and already a prominent one
for a team that is only beginning full-squad spring-training
workouts on Monday. Valentine and Steve Phillips, the Mets' general
manager, are in the last year of three-year contracts, and the
issue is likely to linger until it is addressed by Wilpon and his
partner, Nelson Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will explore that at the end of the year when the contracts
are up,'' said Wilpon, who was at the Mets' training camp Sunday.
``That does not take anything away from the job they've done to
date. I think both of them have done excellent jobs. Nelson and I
are both very pleased with what they've done, but we're going to
wait until the end of the year to address it. It is highly likely
that we will ask them, and hopefully they will want to remain part
of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who signed his three-year, $2 million contract during
the 1997 season, said he had not been told why the Mets will not
consider another in-season negotiation. Wilpon said he was trying
to minimize distractions by waiting, in hopes that people would
focus on games instead of contract talks. But if there was pressure
on a person in the last year of a contract, Wilpon acknowledged
that that might be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't found that to be a bad thing in life, having to meet
the expectations,'' said Wilpon, who said his expectations were to
reach the World Series. ``I've found that to be a motivator _ and
both of those guys are internally motivated, self-starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that, Valentine paused and reflected on the
characterization of him as self-motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's very proper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said last week that if asked the wrong question at the
wrong time, he could say something that would make for ``one heck
of a story.'' Wilpon said that comment did not concern him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby, like all of us _ myself, anybody in the organization _
has to be accountable for their actions and/or their words,''
Wilpon said. ``Bobby's a professional and Steve's a professional,
and they'll handle this and get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he already knew his contract would not be
discussed until after the season. If Valentine did not, Phillips
said, there must have been a miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the assumption I've been functioning under since the
issue was addressed last fall,'' Phillips said. ``I guess I'm not
bothered by it. My view is I understand what the situation is, and
I'll wait until it's addressed and do the best job I can so that
when it is addressed, hopefully I'll get an extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was named general manager during the 1997 season,
Valentine's first full season as manager, and the Mets won 88 games
that year. They won 88 again in 1998, then reached the playoffs
last year by winning 97 games. Phillips said there was ``no way''
he would make his own issue a public one, and had no comment on
reports of his uneasy relationship with Valentine. But he offered a
positive evaluation of his and Valentine's performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby's done a good job,'' Phillips said. ``We've come
a long way as an organization and I think he's an important and
major contributor to the success of the organization the last few
years. I think I've done a good job, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilpon said the potential sale of the Mets _ a topic on which he
would not comment _ was not a factor in the decision to wait on
contracts for Valentine and Phillips. He said the organization was
regularly approached by ``major corporations, Internet companies,
all kinds of people'' wanting to buy into the team, but added he
had no intention of turning over day-to-day operations of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen, period,'' Wilpon said. ``I am never
going to not be involved, by my choice, with the New York Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Wilpon was asked, could the team still be sold?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do a strategic alliance, whatever,'' said the
63-year-old Wilpon, ``but I want to be involved with this team, and
I want to continue to be involved, as long as my health is good,
which it is, and as long as I enjoy it, and the trials and
tribulations.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those ongoing trials is the stadium issue, on which the
Mets have done a year's worth of preparation, Wilpon said. A new
ballpark, to be built in the Shea Stadium parking lot, could be
ready two and a half years after financing is worked out with the
city, he said. City officials have approached the Mets about
scaling down the $500 million project, which includes a retractable
roof and a playing surface that rolls out of the stadium when
baseball is not being played. The Mets, Wilpon said, are not
changing their plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that does for us or the city what we're all
trying to do,'' Wilpon said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
