<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-995(2T     02-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-995(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG MAKERS AND INSURERS LOCK HORNS OVER MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fight between the pharmaceutical and insurance
industries over how to expand Medicare to cover prescription drugs
is imperiling bipartisan efforts in Congress to offer drug benefits
to the elderly this year.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is being played out behind the scenes on Capitol
Hill, as insurance lobbyists conduct briefings for congressional
aides to shoot down the ideas being floated by drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement creates political difficulties for Republican
members of Congress, who have historically been close to both
industries. It also complicates the work of Democrats, who have put
prescription drugs high on their agenda for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies, eager to avoid a big new government program,
want insurance companies to offer drug coverage to Medicare
beneficiaries, with federal subsidies to help low-income people pay
the premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But insurance companies say they want nothing to do with such a
venture, because they fear drug costs for the elderly will grow
much faster than either premiums or the proposed federal subsidies.
Insurers say the government will strictly control the premiums for
such coverage, and they fear they will be blamed if a private
drug-insurance plan fails to meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The top lobbyist for the drug industry, Alan F. Holmer,
president of the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, said: ``You can get insurance for almost anything _
earthquakes in California, tornadoes in Kansas, hurricanes in
Florida. You can get insurance for long-term care, cancer,
infertility, sports accidents. Why not pharmaceutical insurance
coverage?''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Charles N. Kahn III, president of the Health
Insurance Association of America, said: ``Private drug-insurance
policies are doomed from the start. The idea sounds good, but it
cannot succeed in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   For Congress to pass legislation over the objections of either
industry would be difficult. Both have extensive networks of
political contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Political action committees formed by drug and insurance
companies gave $18 million to political parties and candidates for
federal office last year, favoring Republicans over Democrats by
nearly 2-1, according to data reported to the Federal Election
Commission and tabulated by the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the two industries have also spent tens of
millions of dollars on lobbying and advertising intended to
influence the debate in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For about eight months, pharmaceutical companies have been
promoting the idea that Medicare should be ``modernized'' to
provide drug benefits through competing private health plans and
insurance companies. This approach has emerged as a favorite option
for many Republicans and some Democrats, who want to use the
private sector to deliver drug benefits to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry says that it would like to see drug
benefits provided as part of a comprehensive plan to redesign
Medicare, but that it would support federal legislation to provide
elderly people with so-called pharmaceutical insurance coverage as
an interim step this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said insurers did not want to take on the risk of
underwriting drug insurance because the costs were unpredictable
and the people most likely to buy it would have high drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who expect to receive the most in benefits will purchase
such insurance immediately, while those who expect to have few
claims will forgo purchasing it,'' Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug company executives said they were puzzled and frustrated by
insurers' insistence that they could not sell insurance to meet a
serious national need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everybody else agrees that private health plans should
be used in some way to deliver Medicare drug benefits, but the
insurance industry is lobbying against the idea,'' said Lisa J.
Raines, senior vice president of the biotechnology company Genzyme.
``That's unfathomable.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin A. Corry, director of federal affairs at AARP (formerly
known as the American Association of Retired Persons), said the
``spitting match'' between the two industries showed that ``the
private sector is not going to be able to provide prescription drug
benefits'' on the scale required by the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug companies don't want the federal government to set
prices,'' Corry said. ``Health insurance companies don't want to
insure against the risk. Unless the federal government steps in and
bears the risk, this problem won't be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for 39 million elderly or disabled
people. It generally does not pay for drugs outside the hospital,
even though drug therapy accounts for a rapidly growing share of
all medical care.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of Medicare beneficiaries have no insurance to cover
drug costs. Many of them pay full retail prices because they do not
get the large discounts offered to health maintenance
organizations, hospitals and other bulk purchasers of prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such discounts, employer-sponsored health plans report
that their annual drug spending increased between 15 percent and 18
percent in each of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies already sell insurance to fill gaps in
Medicare. Such policies pay deductibles, the patient's share of
doctors' bills and certain other expenses not covered by Medicare.
Drug company executives say they suspect that the insurers'
opposition to drug insurance is motivated in part by a desire to
protect the profits they earn from this Medigap insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers acknowledge that this is a factor, but they have other
concerns as well. They say they fear that if they offer
free-standing drug-insurance policies, the premiums will be
strictly regulated by federal and state government agencies and
they will be required to sell such insurance at similar rates to
all Medicare beneficiaries, including those with disabilities and
chronic illnesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cecil D. Bykerk, executive vice president and chief actuary of
Mutual of Omaha Cos., said, ``I'm convinced that stand-alone drug
policies won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual of Omaha sells Medigap insurance to more than 200,000
people, but no longer offers policies with drug benefits. ``It was
not a good business for us, and we didn't think it was a good value
for beneficiaries either,'' Bykerk said of the Medigap policies
with drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, Medigap insurers can charge higher premiums to
older customers. But sometimes the extra premium for drug coverage
equals or exceeds the maximum benefit payment for drug expenses.
Two of the 10 standard Medigap policies pay up to $1,250 a year in
drug benefits. But people over 75 often pay more than $1,200 a year
in additional premiums to get such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield provide Medigap insurance to more
than 5 million Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Nell Lehnhard, senior vice president of the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association, said: ``It's not feasible, from a business
perspective in a voluntary market, to offer stand-alone drug
benefits. Even with a generous subsidy, the premiums will be so
high that healthy people will drop out, and the only people buying
insurance will be those with high drug expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug company lobbyists insist that Congress could solve this
problem _ for example, by giving beneficiaries an opportunity to
buy drug insurance for a modest price when they first become
eligible for Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
