<HEADER>
A2936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-YARNALL-NYT     02-20 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-YARNALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LOOK TO YARNALL FOR COMPETITIVE CONSISTENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ If Ed Yarnall's professional self-esteem was built
on what others thought of his raw ability, he would be in serious
trouble. He knows hitters watch him warm up and see him in the same
open-mouthed way lions view a zebra. He knows because he has heard
their taunts.
</P>
<P>
   He bores scouts, and he understands this: When Yarnall was a
high school senior, the Yankees called to tell him they had drafted
him, and they never called again, never making an offer. But now,
at 24, Yarnall is projected by the Yankees as their No. 5 starter _
with confidence, because the more they have seen from Yarnall, the
more they like him.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, whom Yarnall is expected to replace in the
rotation, threw much harder than Yarnall, by as much as 10 miles an
hour. Irabu's split-finger fastball has more movement than anything
Yarnall throws, and on any given day, Irabu is capable of throwing
a two-hitter. But the Yankees believe that Yarnall will give them
uniform effort and competitiveness, something Irabu never did.
</P>
<P>
   With Irabu, said Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach,
``you were always guessing which guy was going to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you hope for is consistency,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was unimpressed by Yarnall last spring, but his
feelings have changed since then, after watching Yarnall at the end
of last season. ``He definitely has the ability, and his makeup is
good _ he seems to be very solid there,'' Stottlemyre said. ``He's
a good listener, a good watcher.''
</P>
<P>
   And, above all else, he is deceptive. He does not throw hard,
but he overpowers hitters. He has an understated mound presence,
but those who know him best say he is a determined competitor who
embraces a challenge. He has been traded twice, first by the Mets
to the Florida Marlins in the deal for Mike Piazza and then by the
Marlins to the Yankees in a swap for third baseman Mike Lowell. But
now the Yankees consider him close to untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll always figure out a way to win,'' said Skip Bertman,
Yarnall's coach at Louisiana State. ``If he runs into trouble, he
will make the adjustment and he will always figure out a way to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall throws a fastball in the range of 88 to 92 mph, average
in the major leagues. The nature and the deception of Yarnall's
delivery is often compared to that of Sid Fernandez, the former
left-hander for the Mets. Like Fernandez, Yarnall's most prominent
feature in his left arm action, from the vantage point of the
hitter, is his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   As most pitchers begin to drive homeward in their delivery, the
ball is held at the end of the outstretched hand, as Lady Liberty
holds her torch. But what a hitter sees, as he faces Yarnall, is
the bend in his elbow. Behind the bend is Yarnall's hand and the
ball, obscured, until Yarnall's elbow rotates quickly and the ball
is suddenly en route to the plate. There is little visual warning
for the hitter; in effect, Yarnall's delivery knocks out the
hitter's long-range radar. There is no arm extension for the hitter
to track.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Ripplemeyer, a pitching coach in the Mets' system, watched
Yarnall pitch several times and noticed that even when he was not
throwing hard, right-handed hitters constantly fouled the ball into
the stands along the right-field line _ late swings, because the
hitters just did not see the ball coming out of Yarnall's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first see him, he's one of those guys you want to
jump on, as a hitter,'' said Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher.
``You're like, `OK, this is a cookie.' Then six or seven innings go
by and he's still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada and Tim Lanier, who was Yarnall's catcher at Louisiana
State, both say the left-hander throws what is known as a heavy
fastball. It hits the catcher's glove with extra life, generating a
dull thud, and Lanier and now Posada have felt that heaviness in
their hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart in the way he used his fastball, too,'' said
Bertman, who saw Yarnall transform from a freshman disappointment
to a sophomore star, with the same steady progression. ``He'd move
it around, go upstairs, sink it. He wasn't always throwing hard,
but he knew how to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall's potential revealed itself to Stottlemyre and Manager
Joe Torre at Anaheim last Sept. 5. Recalled from Class AAA Columbus
_ where he went 13-4 with a 3.47 earned run average and generally
dominated the International League _ Yarnall started a game against
the Angels and got a 7-2 lead. But Chuck Knoblauch made an error in
the sixth, Yarnall walked two hitters, and the bases were loaded
with nobody out. Rather than panic and try to overpower hitters,
Yarnall conceded a run, tried to generate ground balls and pitched
to preserve the lead. ``That made a great impression on
everybody,'' Stottlemyre said. ``It wasn't so much that he got out
of it, but how he got out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   They saw a part of him that they had never seen before, a
competitiveness that had always been apparent to his mother and
stepfather. Pitching in Little League, Yarnall hit some batters
unintentionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my problem,'' the 10-year-old told John DiMartino,
who married Yarnall's mother when the boy was 4 and has always been
close to his stepson. ``It's my plate, and they need to get off of
it. They need to get out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   He thrived on that, the competition. There were times when other
children stopped by the house and asked if Ed wanted to play, his
mother, Fran DiMartino, recalled, and Ed declined, preferring to
throw a baseball against a fence in the backyard or hit off a tee.
``If he lost, he was pretty good-natured about it,'' she said.
``But he would want to go back and play even harder the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall pitched against Austin Peay in the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament one year, and one hitter had taken
too much time before an at-bat, delaying the game. Yarnall walked
halfway to home plate and snarled, ``Just get in the box.'' He
completely intimidated the guy, Lanier thought, and the batter
struck out on three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, the hitter is definitely your enemy,''
Yarnall said. ``He's up there trying to get a hit off of you;
you're trying to get him out. If you are a pitcher _ especially
with the way the hitters are today, the size of them _ you've got
to get a little mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hitters have tried to intimidate him as well, mocking his
stuff. ``The guy has nothing out there,'' they have yelled, loud
enough for Yarnall to hear. He really doesn't care what they think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand I'm not a guy who throws 94, 95,'' Yarnall said.
``I'm not a guy with a conventional windup. You wouldn't teach the
way I pitch to anybody. I'm definitely not one of those guys where
people in the stands are going to be like, `Wow, this guy is going
to win the Cy Young award, he's going to be the next Clemens.' I
don't have that kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do have the stuff that surprises you, whether it be in a
game or over time, and I don't have a problem with that, as long as
I get hitters out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
