<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-DAYTONA0221-COX     02-20 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett wins the Daytona 500
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Who wants to be a millionaire? Dale
Jarrett, who crossed up long-time friend Mark Martin and jilted
Johnny Benson to win the Daytona 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the 1999 Winston Cup champion, applied a nifty maneuver
with four laps remaining in the season-opener and had the victory
clinched two laps later when the caution flag was raised.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford No. 88 driver's win was his third in circuit's biggest
race. By the winning the Winston No Bull million, he pushed his
paycheck to $2.5 million. As part of the No Bull promotion, fan
Melissa Brown of Pittsburgh also received a $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what, that's the money car,'' Jarrett said. ``It
won a million dollars at Talladega in `98, won another million
here, won a another million for (Brown). Man, this is fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett left the garage area Saturday night with his car
battered and bruised. But his crew put in overtime and rolled out
what looked like a brand new car to the starting line 50 minutes
before the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible job,'' Jarrett said. ``That's where the
credit goes, to those guys for getting it back. The car drove just
like it had been ... just as good as it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like he has every time a green flag has been dropped on a
Winston Cup race for the past two weeks, Jarrett left his
competitors to decide the also-ran positions. Some of them weren't
too happy.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said Jarrett reneged on a radioed deal between the two
crews and hung him out on the high side of the race track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lied to,'' said Martin, who dropped from second to fifth
when Jarrett went to the front without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was in Mark's position, I'd feel the same way,'' Jarrett
said. ``But when I looked up and saw Jeff Burton, knowing he had
Bill Elliott right behind him, I was getting ready to lose my spot
for sure and didn't know how far back I would go. All I wanted to
do was to protect my position.''
</P>
<P>
   At Daytona and Talladega, where NASCAR mandates restrictor
plates, two cars together run faster than one alone. The problem is
getting drivers to work together. But in the Bud Shootout
exhibition last Sunday, Jarrett went one way _ to victory _ and his
teammate Ricky Rudd went the other _ on his roof.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt and his son Dale Earnhardt Jr. both exited their
cars Sunday complaining about a lack of assistance from the other.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was part of five-car fleet of Ford Tauruses that
overtook Pontiac No. 10 driver Johnny Benson, a surprise front
runner, in the closing laps. After the green flag was displayed on
lap 197, Jarrett faked high on the second turn. Benson set up for
the block, but helplessly watched Jarrett sweep by low with a boost
from Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, minus a drafting partner, was sucked all the way to the
back of the pack and finished 12th. It was a bitter ending for the
good-natured driver who was only two laps from the first win of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   After holding the lead for nearly two laps, Jarrett clinched the
victory when Jimmy Spencer wrecked in turn four and brought out the
caution flag for the final pair of laps. Jarrett was followed by
Burton and Dawsonville's Bill Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the pits after the race, Martin motored up to the
side of Jarrett's car for several seconds. Jarrett said he didn't
seem too happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Martin) didn't shake his fist, and he didn't give me the
finger,'' Jarrett said. ``He threw his hands up like `what
happened?' And I totally understand that. I would've been the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
