<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS STILL SEARCHING FOR THEIR ANGEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. - Angel Pena is considered the Dodgers catcher
of the future, which translates into the Dodgers catcher next
season. But before that can happen, the discipline must improve.
</P>
<P>
   Serious questions about the talented young catcher's future are
being raised after he reported to spring training weighing 262
pounds, well above his listed weight of 228.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll learn one way or another,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``If you're really blessed with a lot of talent, that
overrides whatever condition you're in. But at a certain level, and
he hit that level last year, the big leagues, it takes a large
commitment to get to that extra level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have that ability, you may never get there because
people pass you by because you have to be able to do certain things
at that level or you're not going to get there. You learn, or you
don't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers bought out Todd Hundley's option for the 2001 season
after he was acquired from the Mets during the 1998 offseason to
ensure he wouldn't ask for a trade, but with the understanding
Pena, 25, could be ready to catch next season.
</P>
<P>
   That's still the plan, but the current development brings
uncertainty. It was evident during conditioning drills the first
few days of camp. Pena lagged behind the rest of the catchers. He
also had trouble finishing some drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands what's at stake,'' general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``He shows signs of being committed. We're going to work with
him to help him be consistent in his dedication and commitment
level. I think he wants it, but I don't think he's ever been taught
what it really takes to be the best he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for Pena to catch all season at Triple-A
Albuquerque, but Johnson hasn't ruled out using Pena as Hundley's
backup.
</P>
<P>
   However, the current situation isn't great considering the way
Pena's 1999 season concluded. He was sent to the minors because of
poor work ethic, then was suspended for seven games after missing
team meetings and refusing to catch in the bullpen. His season
ended with a stint on the disabled list with a right elbow sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Pena said his weight gain came after he finished playing winter
ball in the Dominican Republic. He already has dropped five pounds
in three days thanks to extensive conditioning work that begins
before the team workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come in every morning and work because I know maybe next
year I could have that job,'' said Pena, who hit .208 with four
homers for the Dodgers in 1999. ``I want it. I have to try and lose
weight. That's my job. I have to. I know Hundley's going to be a
free agent, and I don't know if he's going to sign, so I have to be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Business-like Brown: For just the second time since leaving
Texas in 1994, Kevin Brown is returning to a team for consecutive
seasons. And after a season in which expectations were astronomical
because of that huge contract, Brown's arrival at Dodgertown this
spring was very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good in that it's not starting from scratch again with a
new team, new faces and have that get-acquainted phase,'' Brown
said. ``It's not like everything's different where you have new
coaches, new players.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Brown's first spring with the Dodgers, there is much less
talk of winning titles. Instead, there's a much more calm and
workmanlike atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at it, I think we're trying to move in the right
direction,'' said Brown, who went 18-9 with a 3.00 ERA last season.
``I think it's the situation now where it's time to keep your mouth
shut and let's do it all on the field instead of talking about it
and giving it mouth and lip service. Let's see how things pan out
on the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
