<HEADLINE>
MOISO STRUGGLES, AND SO DO BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A month ago, UCLA sophomore forward Jerome Moiso
had one eye on the All-Pac-10 team and the other on the NBA draft.
In a three-game stretch against North Carolina and the Arizona
schools, Moiso averaged 21 points and 10.7 rebounds and was
unstoppable in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   The second time, Moiso's slumping, and so are the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   In his last three games (Syracuse and the Arizona schools),
Moiso is averaging 6.7 points and five rebounds. The Bruins lost
all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be more aggressive,'' Moiso said. ``I have to get
back to what was working for me earlier in the season, and that's
creating shots for myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt. I'm struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso's natural state is passive. Only when he forces himself to
be aggressive, to carve position in the low post, demand the ball
and take it strong to the basket - only then does he produce
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   In recent games, he hasn't established position, hasn't called
for the ball and hasn't taken it strong. He had several shots
blocked or altered at Syracuse. He took two shots at Arizona State
and four at Arizona, and he was not a presence in the paint in
either game.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Moiso said he's reconsidering his NBA plans
and might return for his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome and Dan (Gadzuric) are the biggest keys to the team,''
guard Earl Watson said. ``But Jerome is Jerome. He's not going to
play great every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, 6-10, is not solely to blame. The Arizona schools
double-teamed him the second time around, and the Bruins don't
always give him the ball when he's open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I need to gain weight to be more visible,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: If Moiso's not aggressive, he won't score
consistently, and if he doesn't score consistently, UCLA won't win
five of its final six gams and make the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Lonely at the top: The gap between star freshman Jason Kapono
and his floundering teammates widens each game. In the desert,
Kapono scored 51 of UCLA's 159 points and took 36 of its 120 shots.
Without him, the Bruns would have lost each game by 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono is worried teammates and fans consider him selfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the consummate team player, but I just want to win,''
Kapono said. ``I'd be happy to have no points and 10 assists if it
meant we'd win.''
</P>
<P>
   Young update: Reserve guard Ray Young bruised his tailbone early
in the second half Saturday and did not return. He dressed gingerly
and was dreading the flight home, but he expects to play Thursday
against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to block Michael Wright's shot when someone took
out my legs and I went down parallel,'' Young said. ``My tailbone
was the first thing to hit the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Kapono has lost as many games this season (11)
as he did in four years at Artesia High. ``It's frustrating,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Sagarin rating dropped from 39th to 42nd after its
disaster in the desert. That's not good enough for an at-large bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
