<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-FINANCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  
 AS TOP FUND-RAISER, BUSH BUILDS `FIREWALL' AGAINST McCAIN MADE OF (rk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the South Carolina primary, Gov. George W. Bush
reaped the enormous benefits of his overstuffed campaign treasury,
which allowed him to refuse federal matching funds and spend as
much as he needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   And while his heavy spending in South Carolina and elsewhere has
depleted much of the money he collected earlier, he is still in a
position to significantly outspend the McCain campaign for the next
few weeks, even as he launches a new round of fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   According to the estimates of several senior Republican
fund-raisers, Bush's campaign spent roughly $5 million in South
Carolina on an aggressive campaign that flooded the airwaves with
attacks against Sen. John McCain and the winning message that the
Texas governor is ``a reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes were high, and the campaign made an all-or-nothing
bet that turned out to be a very smart bet,'' said one long-time
Republican fund-raiser who is a Bush supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCain has no choice but to accept federal matching
funds, his campaign was forced to abide by the state's spending
cap. Sunday, McCain blamed his defeat on being outspent. ``Governor
Bush has raised more money than any campaign in history and they've
spent more money,'' McCain said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``One
of the reasons why we had a little trouble getting our message out
in South Carolina _ because we were outspent 5-, 6-, 10-to-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin might not have been that great, and it may be months
before each campaign's spending totals in South Carolina are
revealed. Bush's campaign said Sunday that it spent $3.1 million on
advertising, compared with the $2.8 million the McCain campaign
said it spent. But those figures do not include the costs of phone
banks, direct mail pitches, staff, travel and other campaign costs,
or the expenditures by independent interest groups who joined the
fray.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the emphatic Bush victory in South Carolina
illustrates the overarching importance of money in this year's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a Bush firewall in this presidential election, it
turns out to be money, not South Carolina or any other individual
state,'' said Fred Wertheimer, a campaign finance expert and the
president of Democracy 21, a nonpartisan public policy group here.
``Bush's financial flooding of South Carolina is the first
on-the-ground, concrete example of just what his huge money
advantage really means in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pace of his spending, Bush still holds a strong
financial edge over McCain. In Michigan, the Bush campaign intends
to outspend McCain by more than 25 percent; the Bush campaign
expects to spend $2.6 million on advertisements compared with the
$2 million that the McCain campaign said it planned to spend.
</P>
<P>
   And that spending difference could widen in some of the 13
states that have Republican contests on March 7, such as New York,
California, Massachusetts and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a Bush spokesman, declined Sunday to disclose
how much money the Bush campaign had in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has about $8 million remaining. That figure includes more
than $6 million in matching funds the campaign says it has
qualified for but has not yet received. Since the New Hampshire
primary on Feb. 1, the McCain campaign has raised $3.5 million on
the Internet. The campaign has also received $70,000 since the
polls closed in South Carolina, McCain advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is scheduled to appear at two fund-raising events in
California later this week. Aides say those events should raise
several hundred thousand dollars, but they concede that they will
probably be dramatically outspent in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've definitely come down off my high,'' said Dan Schnur, the
communications director for the McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bush campaign is scrambling to organize at least
a half-dozen fund-raisers between now and mid-March. One Republican
fund-raiser said there were plans for events in New York, Florida
and Richmond, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended the rate of spending, saying the cash was used for
television commercials that have not yet gone on the air in crucial
primary states such as California, Michigan, Virginia and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in every state, and when you talk about spending
money, what we're talking about is spending pre-advance
expenditures,'' Bush explained on ABC's ``Good Morning America''
program last Friday. ``We're running ads and an organization in
California, for example, where the race begins March 7th. I like
where we are, and that's part of our strategy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
