<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CONSERVATIVES PLAYED BIG PART IN BUSH'S SOUTH CAROLINA
VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S. C. _ On the morning after a sobering defeat in
South Carolina, Sen. John McCain of Arizona complained bitterly
that his rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, had been swept to
victory on a tide of misleading commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the senator said, sent ``a negative message of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   But a detailed analysis of voter surveys carried out by a
consortium of television networks and The Associated Press showed
that there was more to it than that. Bush did indeed succeed in
drawing a new, unfavorable picture of McCain in the minds of voters
here; he also convinced many of them that McCain bore more
responsibility than he for any mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain got the worst of things in any number of ways in the
primary voting on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning demonstration of the power of a sustained
television barrage and an energetic, sharply targeted personal
campaign against an opponent whose focus seemed shaky at crucial
moments, Bush raised doubts about McCain's sincerity, his
conservatism, his credentials as a reformer and his capacity to
beat the Democratic nominee in November.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Bush took a machete to the very quality
that had enabled McCain to transform himself from an obscure
insurgent into a serious contender for the presidency _ his ability
to convince voters that he was profoundly different from most
politicians, including Bush, because he was committed to
truth-telling and hewing to principle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether they thought McCain said what he believed, 52
percent of the voters said yes. Asked the same question about Bush,
50 percent said yes. Two peas in a pod, the voters clearly thought,
despite all McCain's efforts to set himself apart from the
political norm.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing changed more radically or more significantly from
New Hampshire to South Carolina, over just 18 frenetic days, than
the willingness of self-avowedly conservative voters to support
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain did every bit as well as Bush among
conservatives, polling 37 percent to Bush's 36 percent. But in
South Carolina, Bush took twice as many conservatives as his main
rival, winning the backing of 65 percent of them compared with
McCain's mere 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding McCain's problem, there were more conservatives
here. For all the suggestions that the South Carolina electorate
had grown more moderate with the creation of high-tech jobs and the
influx of retirees, that portion of the electorate that turned out
for the primary remained profoundly conservative. Just over half of
the voters in New Hampshire's Republican primary called themselves
conservatives; here, 61 percent did so.
</P>
<P>
   One element in the change was the Bush campaign's suggestion,
directly and indirectly, that McCain was a closet liberal or at
least unreliably conservative. Another may have been the withdrawal
of Steve Forbes and Gary L. Bauer, two other conservative
candidates, whose absence here helped Bush draw a clearer
distinction between himself and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, South Carolina's conservatives are different
from those in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Christian conservatives are thin on the ground in New Hampshire;
they accounted for only 16 percent of the Republican primary vote
there. But in South Carolina, they were more than twice as
numerous, accounting for 34 percent of the primary vote, and they
gave Bush a huge lift.
</P>
<P>
   Final voter survey figures here showed the governor winning by a
lopsided margin among members of the religious right, taking 67
percent of their votes compared with 24 percent for McCain and 9
percent for the third contender, Alan Keyes, a former State
Department official. Among those who professed no interest in
Christian conservatism, McCain eked out a victory, 52 percent to 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That same sharp split showed up within the electorate when
viewed through other lenses useful in discerning conservative
tendencies. For example, among those who think abortion should be
mostly or always illegal, Bush took about 6 of every 10 votes;
among those who said abortion should be legal in most or all cases,
McCain took close to the same proportion.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian conservatives were younger and less educated than
the electorate as a whole. Poll analysis indicated that 41 percent
of those under 30 identified with the religious right, compared
with 28 percent of those over 60, and 42 percent of those with no
college education identified with the religious right, compared
with 29 percent of those with a degree.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won only one age category, those over 75, and only one
education category, those with graduate degrees. His other strong
showings came among veterans, though Bush very nearly held his own
among that group, on whom the senator had counted strongly; the 31
percent of Saturday's voters who said that they had never before
voted in a Republican primary in this state; the 10 percent who
identified themselves as Democrats crossing over to cast Republican
ballots and the 30 percent who described themselves as
independents. People born outside South Carolina were divided.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those newly arrived in the state have settled in
Beaufort County, which includes Hilton Head Island; Horry County,
which includes Myrtle Beach, and Charleston County. McCain carried
all three.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest primaries in the days immediately ahead, which
take place in California, New York, Michigan and Ohio, Bush will be
able to rely much less on Christian conservatives, who are much
less numerous in those states, as are conservatives of any stripe.
Furthermore, he faces potential difficulties with Roman Catholic
voters, many of whom deeply resent what they have long considered
the intolerance of the Southern evangelicals with whom Bush has now
very thoroughly linked his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, Pat Robertson and other Christian activists, who
proved a major asset for the Texan here, could prove a liability as
the action shifts north. Bush must find a way, both for the
big-state primaries and, if nominated, for the general election, to
reclaim his inclusive, centrist image. McCain served notice that he
would resist another makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan electorate, which votes on Tuesday, is a great deal
more like that in New Hampshire than the one that voted here on
Saturday. That gave the McCain backers a certain tincture of hope
after a rotten day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
