<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE FLAG ISSUE RAISES CONCERN WITH KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After regularly training at the College of Charleston
twice a year for eight seasons, New York Knicks players are
considering whether they want the organization to continue its
affiliation with South Carolina, where the Confederate battle flag
flies above its Capitol, even though the banner is considered a
symbol of slavery and segregation.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became a source of heated political debate during the
prelude to the Republican primary there last Saturday. Last
Thursday, after it was reported that USA Track and Field had issued
a statement in support of the removal of the flag from the
statehouse in Columbia, S.C., site of the United States women's
marathon trials this month, the issue was raised with the Knicks,
whose roster is predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials declined to be interviewed on the subject, but
last Friday, Steve Mills, the executive vice president of franchise
operations, said in a statement: ``The Knicks aren't prepared to
make any decision right now regarding changing locales for training
camp. But this is obviously an issue that concerns us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy addressed the issue with his players at a
team meeting last Friday. The players said they were asked to think
about their position regarding the team's association with the
state and provide the organization with some feedback. If the
players are against operating their preseason camp _ and often
their workouts before the playoffs _ at the College of Charleston,
the team may decide to look for an alternate site.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, several players were asked if they would
prefer the team look elsewhere for a training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a state that wants to fly that flag knowing what
it means to people, and me being black, I don't need to be in that
state,'' Larry Johnson said. ``As an individual, no, I wouldn't
want to practice there. But if management says it's going to be
such and such dollars or another place won't be as sufficient, then
I don't know if we have much of a choice. But if we have another
choice, let's get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has a multiyear contract with the College of Charleston
but the financial toll of breaking it is said to be minimal,
according to one team official. The logistics of finding another
suitable site might be more complicated. As it is, the Knicks have
access to a state-of-the-art training center and gym and have
luxury hotel accommodations within walking distance of the college.
</P>
<P>
   For eight seasons, since Pat Riley arrived to coach the Knicks
for the 1991-1992 season, the Knicks have packed up in October and
headed to camp at the College of Charleston, where they patronize a
hotel, shopping areas and restaurants, and bring publicity to the
school. Last July, the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People began to call for an economic boycott of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding the flag has left some wondering
what responsibility athletes have in using their celebrity to bring
attention to political and social issues. Some college sports
programs have canceled trips to South Carolina in support of the
NAACP boycott, and track and field athletes have contemplated a
protest during the women's marathon trials on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issue is something that should be brought up,''
Charlie Ward said. ``The flag is symbolic of slavery, power, and I
think we should think about it and make a statement on it. At least
we can send some type of message. There are a lot of people who
walk around with that flag and use it for power and racism. When
the flag flies, it's more than just about slavery. There are a lot
of negative images tied to that one flag.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance for a compromise to be reached in South
Carolina. Gov. Jim Hodges has reportedly won support from some
black legislators for moving the Confederate flag from the
Statehouse to a monument of a Confederate general on the Capitol
grounds. It is unclear when the Knicks will make a decision on
whether to continue training in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd rather not go back,'' Chris Childs said.
``Unfortunately, the flag is a part of life that hasn't changed in
some places. It's not an issue as far as the way we've been treated
down there _ because the people have treated us nice _ but just
knowing the flag is flying there is offensive. The flag stands for
slavery and the Ku Klux Klan, and my idea would be for us not to
practice there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a week to think about it. The guys will talk about
it and discuss it, and let the organization know what our feelings
are about it. It's good that we get a chance to give some input.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-U.S.-585&AMP;ADD-NYT     02-20 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WELCOMES IRANIAN ELECTION RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With IRAN-ELECTION) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In unusually bold language, the Clinton
administration welcomed the election results in Iran on Sunday and
said it interpreted them as an unequivocal demand for greater
freedom within the country and for improved relations abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all indications this is an event of historic proportions,''
the State Department spokesman, James Rubin, said Sunday evening,
referring to the partial results available by then.
</P>
<P>
   The vote showed, he said in a statement, that the Iranian people
want ``engagement with the rest of the world'' and ``made clear
their preference for greater freedoms within Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary election, the most open since the fall of the
shah, has been long awaited by the Clinton administration as a test
of whether it could turn around the hostile relations of the last
20 years before President Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   A series of U.S. inducements for opening a dialogue over the
last several years, including a secret message from Clinton last
August, have all been spurned by the Iranian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   With the strengthening of President Mohammad Khatami's moderate
forces in Iran, the Clinton administration clearly hopes that the
stonewalling will at least be reduced and that Khatami will be able
to make inroads into the power preserves of the supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who controls the military, intelligence
services and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday night's statement, the State Department cautioned that
it remained to be seen whether the ``clear hopes of the Iranian
people can be translated to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we hope that the trends of the elections will be
reflected by a different approach to the outside world,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, he said, the United States was most concerned to
see whether Iran would change its opposition to the Middle East
peace negotiations and whether it would cease its support of
terrorist groups seeking to derail the current rounds of
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians and between Israel
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has recently stepped up its accusations
against Iran for supporting such terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would also be watching closely to see whether
the new Parliament would force ``a re-examination of the utility of
developing weapons of mass destruction,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of the Iranian government to acquire nuclear weapons
have been one of the most pressing concerns of the Clinton
administration, and talks at the White House last week with a
senior Russian official, Sergei B. Ivanov, focused on trying to
persuade Moscow to stop the export of nuclear materials to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   As the parliamentary election approached, Clinton administration
officials were watching very closely for trend lines. But most
seemed to believe that while the reformers would gain, and probably
gain considerably, this would by no means signal the end of Iran's
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States to take real advantage of the election
results, it must first find someone authoritative to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   The first move by the administration will most likely be to
search for a way to open substantive talks, a senior administration
official said Sunday. The official pointed out that even North
Korea _ which has hostile relations with the United States and
which, like Iran, is on the State Department's list of countries
that sponsor state terrorism _ has official talks with the United
States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ever since Secretary of State Madeleine Albright offered in June
1998 to draw up a ``road map'' to re-establish relations with Iran,
the Iranian government has rebuffed the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the administration was rebuffed again when Clinton
sent a message that the United States had information concerning
the involvement of ``Iranian government officials and others'' in
the bombing of a U.S. military building in Saudi Arabia, which
killed 19 American servicemen. In the letter, Clinton attempted to
gain Iranian cooperation in the case and at the same time to test
the willingness of the moderates in Tehran to engage the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, in addition to trying to start a dialogue
with Iran, has some leverage with the wide range of sanctions that
have been imposed on its government. Many of these were imposed by
executive order and can be lifted without the approval of Congress,
where there has been criticism of Clinton's efforts to reach out to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Clinton cited Iranian support for terrorist groups as
the reason for banning all U.S. trade with the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these sanctions were relaxed to allow the sale of grain
and medicine. And last December the administration allowed Boeing
to sell parts to Iran's national airline so as to ensure the safety
of its Boeing 747 passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But major changes in the sanctions are unlikely, given the high
national security concerns that the United States has with Iran,
officials said. What is more likely is that there will be stronger
encouragement for the forces of reform now that the parliamentary
elections have shown that the pre-election low-key encouragement of
the reformers from Washington did not lead to a backlash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
