</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHEN RULES TAKE THE FUN OUT OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun heard the leather slam against the
hardwood and an anguished bellow as the basketball ricocheted high
above the Huskies' home court. He was not sure who angrily slammed
the ball, but he knew when and why. It was about three weeks ago,
when the police were investigating whether two of his freshmen had
improperly received merchandise from a clothing store in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges were filed against the players, Tony
Robertson and Doug Wrenn, though both were suspended from the team.
Robertson has returned; Wrenn has not. The coach was recounting the
incident to show how hard it has been for his team to have fun this
season.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult enough that the Huskies are the defending
national champions, he said, and each opponent is taking its best
shot at beating them. It is vexing enough, he said, for his
players, who are ranked 18th, to grow into the roles necessary to
win another title without last season's scoring star, Richard
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there have been the offcourt stumbles _ the police
investigation and subsequent suspensions of his freshmen; an early
season incident in which Connecticut asked the National Collegiate
Athletic Association to decide whether center Jake Voskuhl had
violated association bylaws by using a friend's car. The
organization ruled he had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really heavy, heavier than I expected,'' Calhoun
conceded last week. ``The offcourt things are distracting, really
distracting _ don't let anyone tell you they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn's opponent Monday night, St. John's, knows all about
distractions. The team is doing its best to eke out some fun as it
heads toward the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three weeks, the NCAA's investigators have
investigated everything from a car swap between Erick Barkley and a
family friend to whether the player had improper dealings with
``street agents'' to who paid his tuition at a prep school in
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was declared ineligible for two games when the NCAA
decided switching sport utility vehicles with a Rucker League coach
violated its extra-benefit regulation. An appeals committee sliced
a third game off the suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators returned to New York last week and wanted to talk
with a New York City basketball enthusiast who was implicated in a
recruiting scandal at Syracuse a decade ago, which resulted in a
two-year probation for the men's basketball team. Two people
associated with St. John's and the current investigation have
identified Rob Johnson as a ``street agent'' or ``runner'' for
sports agents. They say Johnson alerted the NCAA to alleged
improprieties after Barkley turned down money from him on behalf of
an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, Mitch Frankel, represents Ron Artest, a former St.
John's star and a close friend of Barkley's. Johnson has declined
to be interviewed by the NCAA and denies the allegations. Frankel
has not commented on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   An NCAA investigator also spoke with officials at Maine Central
Institute about whether people from the Riverside Church basketball
program, or any other benefactors, paid part of Barkley's tuition
when the St. John's guard attended the school in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Lorch, a Manhattan lawyer who helped build Riverside's
basketball program, has acknowledged he has provided financial
assistance to hundreds of kids in his 40 years with the basketball
program. Lorch declined to say whether he paid part of Barkley's
$23,500 tuition at Maine Central Institute. He said he had not been
contacted by the NCAA about Barkley, who played for Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Lorch and Riverside have close and visible ties with St. John's.
Former Red Storm stars like Walter Berry, Chris Mullin and Artest
have played for Riverside. Dermon Player, a St. John's assistant
coach, and Alex Evans, the university's director for basketball
operations, are former Riverside coaches. Lorch is frequently seen
at Red Storm games and sits behind the bench, as he did in
Saturday's 76-75 victory over ninth-ranked Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   By obtaining financial information from Maine Central,
investigators are following a path similar to that in other
inquiries that have resulted in suspensions of college basketball
players in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Another former Maine Central Institute player _ Andre Williams
of Oklahoma State _ was declared ineligible for five games and
ordered to pay $5,000 to charity when the NCAA discovered his
tuition in Maine had been paid by a Kansas City, Mo., businessman,
Tom Grant. Like Lorch, Grant is deeply involved with a high-profile
traveling summer team.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tumult, St. John's (18-6 over all and 10-3 in the Big
East) has won five games in a row and appears bound for the NCAA
tournament. Beginning Monday night with UConn (18-7, 7-5), the Red
Storm has one final, and treacherous, stretch _ at No. 3 Duke
(21-3) and at Miami (16-9, 9-3), which upset UConn on Saturday, and
a home game with No. 23 Seton Hall (18-6, 10-4). Basketball-wise,
Coach Mike Jarvis has declared this stretch ``fun time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest games _ the ones we can't lose _ are behind us,''
Jarvis said. ``From here on, we either play a tournament-caliber
team or a tournament game,'' Jarvis said before beating Syracuse on
Saturday night. ``Now all we need to do is go out and play the best
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis and his players will not talk about the NCAA
investigation. They will not say whether they are slamming
basketballs at practice out of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Rick Evrard of Bond, Schoeneck &AMP; King, is in New
York working with St. John's officials on the NCAA investigation.
The law firm, based in Overland Park, Kan., specializes in these
matters. It has represented Connecticut and, Evrard said, consults
quarterly with the school in an attempt to head off any violations.
</P>
<P>
   In a case like St. John's, the firm conducts a thorough
investigation and issues an independent report, according to
Evrard. The NCAA investigator also has more questions for players,
St. John's officials and associates that could be asked as early as
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Calhoun spoke about how heavy the season had been, he was
looking back. His team had weathered the distractions; he liked its
chances in the NCAA tournament. He did not believe there was a
superior team in the nation _ like his Huskies or Duke last season
_ that could not be upset. Calhoun smiled when he said his Huskies
finally were having fun, finally getting in touch with their
talent, and finally finding focus.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis smiled, too, and urged his team to have fun. But the Red
Storm is learning what heavy means, as Barkley's summation of his
teammates' character after the Syracuse game illustrated: ``Only
the strong survive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no good time for NCAA investigators, lawyers and
reporters to be asking about potential improprieties in a school's
program. There also is no worse time than now, when the games _ and
that's all they are _ matter the most. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0142 </DOCNO>
