<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      02-20 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY CALLS FOR INQUIRY INTO '96 FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley publicly endorsed the
appointment of a special prosecutor Sunday to investigate campaign
finance abuses by the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996, saying he
thought there was clear evidence that laws had been broken.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on ABC's ``This Week,'' Bradley, who is running
against Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic presidential
nomination, asserted that the decision by the Democratic National
Committee to return money that may have been collected improperly
in 1996 and the criminal prosecutions of several low-level
Clinton-Gore fund-raisers indicated that a broader investigation
was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to note that Al Gore had said in New
Hampshire that there were no legal violations,'' Bradley said in
response to a question from Sam Donaldson. ``Well, if that's so, I
would ask him where are the hundreds of thousands of dollars that
were returned by the DNC? What about the 12 people who were
convicted, the 70 people that essentially took the Fifth Amendment
and the 16 or 17, the exact number I'm not exactly sure of, who
actually fled the country?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged that it was highly unlikely that a special
prosecutor would be appointed to investigate the 1996 abuses, since
the decision was in the hands of the Clinton administration. In
1998, Attorney General Janet Reno determined there was insufficient
evidence to appoint an independent counsel to investigate Gore's
fund-raising role in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had been sharply criticized for making fund-raising phone
calls from the White House as well as for attending a fund-raiser
at a Buddhist temple in Los Angeles in 1996. Many nuns and monks
who contributed money then were reimbursed by the temple in
violation of federal law, and the Democratic National Committee
later returned the money. Gore has said he did not know the event
was a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said, ``As Democrats
continue to reject Senator Bradley's candidacy, he's beginning to
sound more and more like the scandal-crazed Republicans such as
Newt Gingrich, Dan Burton and Trent Lott.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has been gradually ratcheting up his attacks on
Gore in preparation for a wave of major primaries on March 7, has
said he thinks the vice president will be ``a risk'' to the party
because the Republicans will attack him ferociously about the
fund-raising problems in the general-election race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I will not have the problems that he will have in
a general election against a Republican,'' Bradley said Sunday.
``We know what's coming with regard to the fund-raising scandals of
1996. We know that we're going to see the Buddhist temple and the
Buddhist monks. We know that we're going to see his finger saying
`no controlling legal authority' on fund-raising in the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used his appearance Sunday to preview the sharp
contrasts with Gore his aides said he would try to draw in a debate
Monday night in Harlem. But he dodged a question about whether he
thought Gore was morally fit to be president, saying: ``I think
there is a record there of not telling the truth. It's a record
over a long time. And I think the American people want a president
to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley faces political risks in attacking Gore for the 1996
fund-raising problems, since many Democrats seem to view the
party's aggressive fund-raising as necessary to defeat Republicans.
Gore has tried to exploit such sentiments by accusing Bradley of
being divisive and of aiding the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns also announced Sunday that as of Feb. 1 they had
nearly $16 million available for the final push to March 7, when
the campaign will be waged heavily through television commercials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-HNS &LR;      02-20 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Pontiac driver Johnny Benson was only four
laps away from pulling off an upset of David-and-Goliath
proportions until the mighty Fords ganged up on him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the Ford Taurus that was the best of the best all along came
to the front at the end when Dale Jarrett passed Benson and held on
to win the Daytona 500 on Sunday for the third time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible,'' Jarrett said. ``I never would have
dreamed coming into the sport that I could win three Daytona 500s,
but it shows what can happen when you have a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton finished second, Bill Elliott was third, Rusty
Wallace came in fourth and Mark Martin crossed the finish line in
fifth place as the Fords swept the top five spots.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the defending Winston Cup champion, earned $2,277,975
for his victory in the Quality Care Ford, the largest winning purse
in NASCAR history. The total included a $1 million bonus for
Jarrett as one of the five drivers eligible for the Winston No-Bull
5 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   He also made a happy woman of Melissa Brown of Pittsburgh, who
won a $1 million bonus. It was the second consecutive year a fan
won the $1 million bonus at the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who started on the pole, led a train of Fords past
Benson on turn 2 after a restart on lap 197 of the 200-lap event at
the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who drives for Tyler resident Tim Beverley and the Tyler
Jet Motorsports team, didn't even have a sponsor until the night
before the race when the team signed a deal with Lycos Inc. But
Benson, who started 27th, was in position to earn the biggest
victory of his career until Jarrett made his move.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett started to go high, and Benson moved up to block him,
but Jarrett veered back inside and got past Benson, along with a
train of Fords.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny made just enough of a move when I faked outside for me
to get under him down low,'' Jarrett said. ``As soon as I saw him
head up the racetrack, I cut my car dead left. But I wouldn't have
felt bad to lose to Johnny, because he's a good guy and that team
needs a break.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Benson got back in the draft line, he had been
shuffled back to 12th, but he wasn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those Fords against one Pontiac isn't going to work,''
Benson said. ``I knew it was going to happen either on the restart
or the last lap. We finish 12th, but I'm happy because we had a
chance to win the Daytona 500 until they ganged up on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of more than 200,000 didn't get a chance to see
whether Jarrett would have been able to hold off his fellow Ford
drivers, because Jimmy Spencer hit the wall coming out of turn 4
with two laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive time Jarrett has won a Winston Cup
points event at Daytona under a yellow flag. He won the Pepsi 400
night race last July under caution.
</P>
<P>
   But this victory was a little surprising to Jarrett, who damaged
his car in an accident during Happy Hour Saturday. Three
fabricators from the Robert Yates team were flown from Charlotte to
Daytona on Saturday evening and worked throughout the night to help
rebuild the dented body of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The range of emotions in a 24-hour period are pretty
incredible,'' Jarrett said. ``We felt the things it takes to make a
car fast here were taken out of our hands, but this shows the kind
of people we have in this organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why we were able to win the championship last year. The
fabricators did a fantastic job, and what an engine. That's what
did it for me, with a little push from Jeff Burton.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Todd Parrott said the team worked on the car until it
was rolled to pit road Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every corner of the car was damaged,'' Parrott said. ``The
rocker panels were bent, and so was the back bumper. But the big
thing was the nose. We had to fix everything and get it lined up
right. The paint was still wet when we left the line. I was hoping
the decals wouldn't fly off.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's car had been the best since the Winston Cup teams
unloaded the haulers at Daytona 12 days ago. He had the top
qualifying lap and won the Bud Shootout all-star race Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But it took a pass of veteran driver Martin with 14 laps left
for Jarrett to get in position to win. Jarrett was third behind
Martin when their teams made an agreement to go together to try to
get by Benson, but Martin went high in turn 2 and Jarrett stayed
low.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing I hate about the whole day,'' Jarrett
said. ``I told Mark I would work with him high. He went high, but
Jeff started to go past me down low and I had to protect my
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it happened to Mark, but I know that doesn't make him
feel any better. I wasn't trying to set him up, even though I know
he will never believe that. When Mark got beside me (after the
race) he threw his hands up like to say, `What happened?' I totally
understand that, and I would have felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin would not criticize Jarrett, but he was upset about how
things transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a good thing going there, and I was trying to
win the race,'' Martin said. ``I would rather have tried and lost
than not tried. That's all I have to say about it. I had a chance,
and that's all I ever really ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he angry with Jarrett?
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is over with,'' Martin said. ``We just have to go to
Rockingham now.''
</P>
<P>
   With three victories in NASCAR's biggest show, Jarrett is tied
with Bobby Allison for third on the all-time list of Daytona 500
victories behind Richard Petty (seven) and Cale Yarborough (four).
</P>
<P>
   ``Today when it was over, Richard Petty came into Victory
Lane,'' Jarrett said. ``He shook my hand and told me, `Great job.'
It sent chills up my spine for `the King' to come over and say that
to me. I think that explains how special this win is to me.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
