<HEADLINE>
JOHN W. HANNON JR., 77, RETIRED BANKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John W. Hannon Jr., a former president of Bankers Trust, died
last Feb. 14 at Carolina House, an assisted living facility in
Pinehurst, N.C. Hannon, a resident of West End, N.C., was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was cardiac arrest, said his son, Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon worked for Bankers Trust, which was acquired by
DeutscheBank in 1999, for 32 years. He was appointed executive vice
president in charge of operations in 1971 before being named
president in 1975. He also served as chairman of the executive
committee, part of the board of directors, starting in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon was part of the management team at Bankers Trust in 1978
when it underwent a major reorganization, selling branch offices
and switching its focus from consumer to investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon's career in banking started in 1946 at Commercial
National Bank and Trust, which followed service with the Army Air
Corps during World War II and a short pitching career on a New York
Yankees farm team in Pittsburgh. He graduated from St. Lawrence
University with a bachelor of arts degree in 1946. Bankers Trust
bought Commercial National in 1951, and Hannon became an assistant
treasurer before being named an executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, who lives in London, Hannon is survived
by his wife, Vivien; two daughters, Elizabeth Reichard, of North
Andover, Mass., and Christine Hannon, of Northampton, Mass.; and
five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
