<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULSON GETS BIG CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES -- Dennis Paulson has been saying all along he
deserves to be included among the best players on the PGA Tour. Now
he gets a chance to prove it to the world.
</P>
<P>
   The San Gabriel native plays Colin Montgomerie in Wednesday's
first round of this week's $5 million World Golf Championships at
La Costa Resort and Spa. Montgomerie, who has won the European
Tour's Order of Merit the past seven years, is the world's
third-ranked player (behind Tiger Woods and David Duval) and is
regarded as one of the toughest match-play performers around.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not impregnable. He lost in the WGC's first round last
year to Craig Stadler and Paulson, No. 62 in the world, wouldn't
mind a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan on being out in the first round,'' he said Sunday
after finishing in a tie for 18th at the Nissan Open at Riviera
Country Club. Paulson closed with a one-over-par 72 in cold, rainy
conditions. I'm playing real solid golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, who now lives in Vista, had his best year ever on tour
in 1999. He was 27th on the money list with $1,313,814 and had nine
top-ten finishes, including seconds in the Buick Classic and
Canadian Open.
</P>
<P>
   He has more than $102,560 in earnings this year (including
$37,731 at the Nissan) and heads into La Costa feeling good about
his game. He said he played with Montgomerie three times in college
(Paulson went to San Diego State; Montgomerie attended Houston
Baptist) and twice last year on tour, at Bay Hill and the BellSouth
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But Paulson doesn't have a lot of match-play experience. He said
his last real exposure to that format was the finals of the
California State Amateur in 1985, when he lost to Sam Randolph 3 &AMP;
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was two- or three-under and still lost,'' Paulson
recalled, ``but that's the nature of the deal. I can shoot 75 and
win. I can shoot 63 or 64 and be down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to play solid golf, keep the pressure on him and
hopefully he makes some mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulson said he enjoys match play because he feels it's the game
in its truest form.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any complaints about getting a bad tee time or
stuff like that,'' he said. ``It's just you and him playing the
golf course at the exact same time, and that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory over Montgomerie would send Paulson into a
second-round match against the winner of Glen Day-Thomas Bjorn.
Other players in Paulson's half of the bracket include Vijay Singh,
Mark O'Meara and Greg Norman (who also meet in the first round) and
European Ryder Cupper Darren Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson said he expects to have plenty of fans in attendance at
La Costa. He already has been inundated with ticket requests --
``People are coming out of the woodwork,'' he joked -- but is
unsure if he will employ Stadler's winning strategy of a year ago,
when he did not concede a single putt.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that could work in Paulson's favor is Montgomerie's
inactivity. The Scot has played little, if any, competitive golf in
2000 and could be rusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he also might be ready to go and the juices could be
flowing,'' he said. ``If he plays bad, you could say, Well, he
probably should have played a little golf.' If he plays great, then
you could say, He prepared perfectly for it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Monty is going to have an easy day of it, the
way I'm striking the ball. He's going to have to work. I like the
golf course, I'm at home and I'm going to have a lot of people
supporting me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
