<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-VOTERS-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IN MICHIGAN, McCAIN TARGETS WIDE MIX OF VOTERS  
(lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEVILLE, Mich. _ With time, money, momentum and the Republican
machine in Michigan working against him, Sen. John McCain is trying
to corral an unlikely coalition of moderate suburban Republicans,
poor urban Democrats and feisty blue-collar independents.
</P>
<P>
   But showing the confidence of a front-runner who feels his core
support is secure, Gov. George W. Bush signaled on Sunday that he
would compete for some of the same voters.
</P>
<P>
   That unpredictable electorate is concentrated in southeastern
Michigan, where three counties supply 40 percent of the primary
voters, and where Bush is campaigning Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Macomb County, McCain is bidding for people like Robert
Kraft, who voted twice for Ronald Reagan, before voting twice for
Bill Clinton. A retired tool and die machinist, Kraft plans to
support the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain seems to be honest,'' Kraft said at a supermarket here.
``Bush _ he seems to be honest, but he's got all that money behind
him. He's going to have to pay that back somehow, and he's going to
forget about us people. I have to pay prescription prices, and my
wife does. Do you know how much that costs?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not need Kraft nearly as badly as McCain does. While
polls have shown McCain running strongly among Democrats and
independents in Michigan, his support appeared to be slipping among
Republicans even before his loss in South Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, the candidates had spent one day here since the
New Hampshire primary. Voters do not seem very familiar with them,
which is likely to be a bigger problem for McCain _ since he lacks
a strong organization in the state to turn voters out for him _
than for Bush. At both the western and the eastern ends of
Michigan, voters were heard in recent days to refer to the senator
as ``McLaine.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of aisles away from Kraft, Ann D'Amato, a clerical
worker, was grocery-shopping for her family. D'Amato also voted
twice for Ronald Reagan and twice for Bill Clinton. But though she
is most concerned about drugs and violence in the streets and in
the media, D'Amato has not even considered voting for anyone but
Vice President Al Gore. She just has not seen much of McCain, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only times I've seen him talk _ just a few times on the
news _ he doesn't come across as forceful enough,'' D'Amato said,
making an unusual criticism of the blunt-spoken senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's allies here have complained about Democrats making
mischief by voting in the Republican primary, which is open to all
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush appeared on Sunday to be reaching out to some
of these same voters, or at least discouraging them from seeking to
punish him at the polls, by appearing in heavily Democratic Wayne
County and releasing a new commercial that presents him as a gentle
man concerned with the well-being of children.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain made a play for the core of Bush's support,
campaigning in conservative western Michigan, and he is advertising
himself on radio as a ``proud, pro-life Reagan conservative.'' On
Monday he planned to campaign in Saginaw to the north and Ypsilanti
to the west, in a swing planned before his loss in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hudome, McCain's top adviser in Michigan, said that the
senator wanted the support of Democrats and independents. ``We're
reaching out to all voters like President Reagan did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been reaching out to Democrats here through the mail.
Leo and Joyce Lalonde, Democrats who live in Macomb County,
received a mailing from McCain on Friday at their home in
Eastpointe, which adjoins Roseville. The Democrats are not holding
a primary, it noted (they are holding closed caucuses next month).
</P>
<P>
   ``Make your voice heard by voting for the one candidate
committed to reform,'' it continued. For those Democrats concerned
about the consequences of a crossover vote, it continued, ``Even if
you vote in Tuesday's Republican primary, you can still participate
in future Democratic Party political activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has not bought any mailing lists of
Democrats, Hudome said. But the campaign has been appealing to some
Democrats by sending fliers and placing pre-recorded telephone
calls to all residents of some towns with a mixture of Democrats
and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Lalonde, who is the chairman of the Democratic committee
for the 10th Congressional District, said she was amused by the
letter but had no intention of complying. ``You've got to
understand,'' she said. ``Their primary is Tuesday and ours is
March 11. If we mess around in theirs, they're going to mess around
in ours. That would be politically not a smart move on our part.''
She said she doubted that many Democrats would cross over for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lalonde disavowed any Democratic effort on McCain's
behalf, other Democrats have been trying to help him, for their own
purposes. On Saturday, Geoffrey Feiger, a former Democratic
candidate for governor and the lawyer who represented Dr. Jack
Kevorkian, began running a radio advertisement excoriating Bush and
Gov. John Engler, who has thrown his party organization behind
Bush, as ``dumb and dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When John Engler and George W. Bush talk about lawsuit abuse,
they really mean they helped their friends in the insurance
industry and denied all of us access to the courts,'' Feiger says
in the commercial. In an interview, Feiger said he was seeking to
help McCain and had had no contact with his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has his own radio advertisements on the air here, warning
that unnamed forces were ``coming after him here in Michigan,'' and
stating that he would never run a negative commercial: ``They
insult your intelligence, and hurt our chances against Gore in
November.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In another Democratic boost to the senator, the Michigan
Democratic Party and College Democrats of Michigan plan to hold a
protest against Bush on Monday at 11:45 a.m. at Michigan State
University in Lansing, where the Texas governor is scheduled to
appear at noon. Dennis Denno, the state party's spokesman, insisted
that the protest did not signal that Democrats were siding with
McCain, although he said that no protests were planned against the
Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   LaMar Lemmons III, a state representative from Detroit, visited
churches Sunday to urge predominantly black congregations to
support McCain, in what he called an effort to embarrass Engler,
Bush's leading supporter here. Lemmons said that he was upset that
Engler had pushed through state legislation eliminating Detroit's
elected school board and separate criminal courts. ``We're out to
send the Republican establishment a message: They have meddled in
our affairs,'' Lemmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons said that other Democrats were quietly helping McCain in
10 of Michigan's 16 Congressional Districts, but were doing so
secretly to avoid offending the party's leaders. Mark Brewer, the
chairman of the Michigan Democratic Party, said that he did not
know of any other Democratic politicians who were supporting
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in what LaMar is doing, but he's one state
representative out of 52'' Democrats in the Michigan House, Brewer
said. ``Any thought this will have a significant impact next
Tuesday is silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons said that he wanted to persuade 100,000 Democrats to
vote in the Michigan primary, through a a 12-line phone bank and
pamphlets and faxes sent to 200 churches. But Ed Sarpolus, a
pollster at EPIC/MRA, a polling firm in Lansing, said that based on
previous primaries, about 100,000 Democrats could be expected to
vote anyway in the Republican primary, which could draw anywhere
from 600,000 to 1 million voters altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters interviewed Sunday insisted that the campaign in
South Carolina would not influence them. McCain on Sunday attacked
Bush for appearing at Bob Jones University, a conservative
Christian college in South Carolina whose president has made
critical comments about Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   But Ned McGrath, the spokesman for the Catholic Archdiocese of
Detroit, said that he had not even heard about any controversy
involving Bush's appearance at the college. The local media have
made no mention of the issue, nor has the archdiocese's weekly
newspaper, the Michigan Catholic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sterling Heights, a middle-class industrial suburb north of
Detroit, several voters interviewed as they headed for services at
St. Malachy Catholic Church said they would support Bush because
they believe he is a staunch opponent of abortion. But Mike Kovacs,
31, who considers himself an independent voter and who voted for
Clinton in the last election, plans to support McCain this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his stand on the issues is a little more solid than
George Bush's,'' said Kovacs. ``I kind of like the idea of someone
who has honesty and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   As bells pealed through an overcast sky Sunday morning at the
Most Holy Trinity Church in Detroit's Corktown neighborhood, Alanna
Reyes-Ali, 49, said she would vote for McCain to send a message to
the state's Republicans, particularly Engler whom many city
residents blame for legislative moves that they say will hurt
Detroit's tax base and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the problems we've had with Engler with their attack
on Detroit, it gives the Democrats a chance to wreak havoc back on
them,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
