<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-TIMBERWOLVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HIS 23RD BIRTHDAY, MARBURY HAS A GAME TO CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Stephon Marbury strolled into the Target Center on
Sunday knowing that an entire state was eagerly awaiting his
failure, that almost everyone in the crowd of 19,449 wanted to see
him broken and humiliated. He knew there would be boos, taunts and
disparaging signs and that the fans who once cheered him would do
everything in their vocal power to make his 23rd birthday a
horrible one.
</P>
<P>
   But in a performance that proved he is as mentally strong as he
is athletically gifted, Marbury emerged from the emotional gauntlet
as a champion. In a nationally televised game that many thought
would confirm him a fool for forcing last season's trade from
Minnesota to the Nets, Marbury almost single-handedly defeated an
arena full of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring 39 points, including 12 of the Nets' 15 in the fourth
quarter, Marbury made his first trip back to Minnesota a victorious
one, leading the Nets (21-30) to an improbable 91-89 victory over
the Timberwolves (28-23). By game's end, the earsplitting chorus of
boos Marbury heard every time he touched the ball had fizzled into
a whisper, and dozens of Timberwolves fans huddled near the exit to
pat him as he jogged off the court, some of them yelling, ``You're
the man, Steph!''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best birthday by far,'' said Marbury, who fell
just 3 points shy of matching his career high. ``There was so much
hype built up around it. It wasn't unnecessary, but I knew and
everyone else knew that a lot of people were going to boo. By just
playing through that and knowing that I can do that, I learned
something about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he entered the arena to the time he left,
Marbury handled the potentially distressing situation like a
professional. Since he and his agent, David Falk, pressured the
Timberwolves into trading him last March 11, he had been vilified
in Minnesota as selfish and ungrateful for spurning the team he
played with for his first two and a half seasons in the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota fans, many of whom believe Marbury left because of
jealousy over Kevin Garnett's six-year contract worth $126 million,
showed up with signs that labeled him a ``crybaby,'' perhaps
referring to his complaints about the state's cold weather and his
insistence that he left the Timberwolves to be closer to his family
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the derision, Marbury entered with giddiness and a
smile, greeting everyone from security guards to former teammates
with a hug. He seemed to be relishing the situation, and when the
crowd drenched him in boos as he walked out for the opening
tip-off, he smiled widely, as if knowing he would reduce them to
silence and grudging admiration soon.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett, the Timberwolves' outstanding forward, with whom
Marbury shared a close friendship and a glistening future, was not
as strong. The hype, much of which revolved around these two, got
to Garnett, and he uncharacteristically lost his composure. Playing
as if rushed, he attempted a career-high and franchise-record 33
field goals, making just 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out too hyped at the start,'' said Garnett, who shared
a pregame hug with Marbury and says their friendship is strong as
ever. ``My shots were either too long or too hard. I just have to
learn to control my emotion and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Garnett clanged shots off the rim, going 3 for 9 in the
first quarter and 4 for 13 in the first half, Marbury stayed within
the flow of the offense and shot the ball tremendously. As if
motivated by the boos, he scored 9 first-quarter points to lead the
Nets, then 5 more in the second to send them into the locker room
ahead by 46-42.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury scored 13 more points in the third, including 6 on
3-pointers, to give the Nets a 76-65 lead heading into the final
period, and in a delicious conclusion, the fourth came down to the
two stars and pals. With the other Nets shooting 0 for 7, Marbury
took over the offense, hitting all three of their field goals in
the fourth quarter. And Garnett, still without his touch, began
dominating the backboards to score on putbacks or free throws. He
grabbed 8 of his 18 rebounds and scored 11 of his 27 points in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a one-on-one battle,'' Nets forward Kendall
Gill said. ``I started to go get some popcorn and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   With 1 minute 31 seconds left, Marbury scored what would be the
game's final point by hitting 1 of 2 free throws to put the Nets
up, 91-89. Garnett, who all but nullified Keith Van Horn (12
points) by getting him in early foul trouble, fouled out Jim
McIlvaine with 1:15 remaining but missed both ensuing foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   With the rookie Evan Eschmeyer, playing admirable defense on
Garnett, the Nets forced Minnesota into a 24-second violation with
just 32 seconds to play. But they failed to seal the outcome when
Marbury's &QC; 3-point attempt missed with 8.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   As the teams set up for the final play after a timeout, Marbury
smiled at Garnett and gave him something to think about. ``I was
telling him that I knew he was going to get the ball, and he just
kind of looked at me like, `You know I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett did, of course, and when he wheeled into the lane for a
six-footer, Eschmeyer was right there to contest it. Malik Sealy
tipped the rebound toward the basket but missed, and Kerry Kittles
grabbed the ball just before time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through this situation has definitely made me build
character,'' Marbury said. ``I know that I can't say certain
things, and I know that I was wrong for a lot of things that went
on. But coming in tonight and playing the best basketball that you
can possibly play was the main thing. This is the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2125EST &QL; 
