<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECTION-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMERS EBULLIENT FOLLOWING ELECTION GAINS IN IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran's reformers, increasingly convinced that
they have wrested control of the Parliament from religious
conservatives, put their confidence on full display Sunday by
paying homage to the most outspoken clerical advocate of change and
democracy, Abdullah Nouri.
</P>
<P>
   As if to symbolize the buoyancy of the reformers, Nouri, who has
been in prison for three months after being convicted of apostasy
by a clerical court, was allowed to go home late Saturday for a few
days. As he received his guests, early tallies and various
prognoses indicated that reformers and moderates who have pledged
to back President Mohammad Khatami will have a significant,
probably dominant, place in the new 290-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
   With about two-thirds of the 31 million votes cast in Friday's
elections already counted, analysts for the main reform parties
said their candidates had already trounced more hard-line
candidates in key provincial towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Results from the capital of Tehran, as well as the large cities
of Qum and Mershhad, have not yet been announced. But the reform
strategists, who have observers in the Ministry of Information
offices where the ballots are being counted, said preliminary
figures showed that pro-Khatami forces would hold a firm majority.
</P>
<P>
   The reformers speculated that the large turnout _ a record 80
percent _ worked in their favor. Khatami, who has invigorated
Iran's political life with his talk of creating a civil society and
the rule of law, was swept into office in 1997 on the strength of a
massive turnout by Iran's young people and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this vote, they have shown that the most important thing
is political development and the guarantee of legal freedoms,''
Nouri said of the reformist voters. ``It was not a personal fight
against anyone. It was an election about programs and issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has not provided a breakdown of the winners so
far, leaving the task of analyzing their political orientations to
journalists and political parties. Many candidates are unknown or
ran as independents. Even those who presented themselves as
supporters of Khatami's liberal agenda are unlikely to be united on
every issue and so may be hard to classify, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's election opened the way for some liberalization of
Iranian life, but he has been unable to achieve fundamental changes
in part because of conservative opposition in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters in the elections pinned their hopes on the young,
who make up more than half the population, and on people fed up
with the conservatives who have dominated the Parliament since the
Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Nouri was sentenced to prison after he enraged the
religious hierarchy by questioning their near-absolute power over
how Iranians conduct their private lives.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon, his north Tehran home had become a place of
pilgrimage for government ministers, provincial officials,
presidential aides and many of the pro-Khatami reform candidates
who seem assured of becoming Iran's new power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall's trial of Nouri, 51, mesmerized the public and became
a metaphor for the struggle between the reactionary clergy and the
impatient young reformers.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of Nouri's standing among those in power who have been
chafing under the restraints imposed by the hard-liners, his
visitors included Khatami's chief of staff, Sayed Mohammad Ali
Abtahi, several ministers, the head of Iran's Central Bank, and a
few provincial governors.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Also among the guests was Khatami's brother, Mohammad Reza
Khatami, who was a candidate on a reform ticket and appears to be
the top vote-getter in Tehran, according to analysts who have
studied the preliminary results from more than half of the
capital's polling places.
</P>
<P>
   As the results trickled in from outlying sections of the
country, Nouri gently chided his guests for not having more
definite results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know anything about computers,'' he said. ``That's
why you don't know the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Iranian state television reported Sunday night that nearly 23
million votes had been counted, covering 203 parliamentary
districts. In 52 of the races, it said, a runoff would be held
sometime in late April because no candidate received the minimum 25
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Tehran accounts for 30 seats in the 290-seat Parliament.
Analysts for Iranian newspapers and political groups said the
leftist Islamic Iranian Participation Front, the most unabashed of
the reformist parties, appeared set to win at least a third of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates from a more moderate party, Executives of
Construction, also were doing well, although their titular leader,
former president Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, was believed to be
fighting hard just to make the cut on the first round.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the provinces, Mohammad Reza Tabesh, a nephew of Khatami, won
as a reformer in Ardakan, Khatami's hometown. In traditional
conservative strongholds like Isfahan and Shiraz, candidates
running under the pro-Khatami banner captured seven of nine seats.
</P>
<P>
   One of those defeated in Ifsahan, the second-largest city and
traditionally a religiously conservative one, was the former
intelligence minister Ali Fallahian. An incumbent, Fallahian has
been accused of knowing about the assassinations of prominent
liberals two years ago, a plot that Khatami has said was carried
out by ``rogue'' intelligence officers.
</P>
<P>
   Another losing conservative was Ahmed Rasouli-Nejad, a
parliamentarian from northern Iran who was among a group of
hard-liners who impeached the liberal culture minister last year.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If they win a majority of seats, the pro-Khatami forces could
enable the president to make good on his pledge to create a society
of laws, to depoliticize the judiciary and to guarantee a free
press.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts for the moderate and reform parties said the election
results so far show that the hard-liners may end up with a mere 25
to 30 percent of the Parliament seats, although conservative
newspapers in Tehran predicted a better showing for their
candidates. The outgoing Parliament had a slight majority of
conservative members.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Bourghani, a key strategist for the reform movement, said
that his analysis of the returns reported by Sunday afternoon show
that the winners of 104 out of the 167 seats already announced are
either members of the leftist Islamic Iran Participation Front or
its more moderate ally, the Executives of Construction.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates' party has pledged support for Khatami on
reforming the judiciary and freeing the press, but differs from the
reformers on economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes involved in the parliamentary elections have led
to clashes in some cities. Although the elections were
trouble-free, there were reports Sunday of violence in two towns
after the results were announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that 15 people were
injured in riots in the southwestern town of Shush when police
tried to disperse demonstrators who threw stones at the governor's
office and accused the incumbent parliamentarian of winning
re-election by fraud. But a Tehran newspaper, Kahan, reported that
eight people were killed in the riots.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes also occurred in the town of Shadegan, in the same
province, when crowds protested the election results.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged on the carpeted floor of his basement and
leaning against pillows covered in the rich patterns of classic
Persian carpets, Nouri received a steady flow of visitors who bowed
in deference before him, kissed his cheeks, answered an unrelenting
stream of calls on their cellular phones and sat spellbound as he
spoke cryptically of his imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four hours in prison seem longer than a week,'' he
said, as his little grandson played near his feet. Asked if he
thought he might be spared the ordeal of returning to his cell to
serve out the remainder of his five-year sentence, Nouri smiled.
``That would be rational,'' he said, ``but it's not the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was free and running the newspaper Khordad, Nouri called
for a public debate on the role of the clergy in general and the
supreme leader in particular. The leader has wide powers over the
judiciary, the military, the security forces and, effectively, over
the legions of volunteer militias that have been the main enforcers
of the clergy's puritanical rules of dress and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The leader's role is defined in the Iranian constitution that
was written after the revolution 21 years ago. Nouri said Sunday
that he believed the first priority for a new Parliament would be
to pass laws allowing the creation of real political parties and
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the constitution, he added, is ``possible'' but
needs to be evaluated as part of an entire package of fundamental
systemic changes.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the preliminary election results reinforce the
popularity of Khatami and demonstrate again, as in the presidential
election two and a half years ago, that Iranians want fundamental
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities did not give an explanation for Nouri's sudden,
although temporary, release from Evin Prison. But it is not unusual
for some prisoners, particularly those convicted of political
crimes, to get home visits every three months or so during their
jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri said he expected to be taken back to prison on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri's own brother, Ali Reza Nouri, acted as a second host to
the constant flow of visitors. One of the country's newest
political celebrities, he announced his candidacy for the
Parliament on the reform ticket soon after Nouri's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   As young men passed around glasses of juice and trays of sweets,
he told his older brother about his experience speaking to
university students.
</P>
<P>
   One student, he recalled, told him he looked like an
opportunist, jumping into politics on the basis of his relationship
to his popular brother. ``I told him it's like in football: If the
ball drops in front of you, shouldn't you kick it to make the
goal?'' the younger Nouri said. His older brother laughed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
