<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 LOOKING INTO USC-ASU FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pacific-10 Conference has launched an investigation into the
postgame altercation following Saturday's USC-Arizona State
contest, but unless clear videotape evidence emerges, it is
unlikely any players will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific-10 Conference commissioner Tom Hansen said Sunday that
he had already viewed some films of the game, but was awaiting a
copy of the Arizona State game film today before any decision could
be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have some very clear understanding of what
occurred it would be very hard,'' Hansen said. ``We could (suspend
players) if we had a clear agreement on what happened, but I don't
anticipate it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State game film is expected to be a ``very high
shot,'' according to Hansen. So far, none of the film Hansen viewed
offered a clear angle of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   USC guard Jeff Trepagnier and Arizona State forward Awvee Storey
were involved in an altercation after the Trojans' 93-81 loss to
the Sun Devils at Wells Fargo Arena. Both players blamed each other
for the start of the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up and there was a squabble,'' Trepagnier said. ``I
was just trying to protect myself. He got in my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Storey: ``I got cheap-shotted. I didn't see it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said he had already interviewed officials from USC and
Arizona State on Saturday night, and there was no single
explanation of who started the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, there are many different versions,'' Hansen
said. ``It's very, very predictable. Everyone sees things
differently. We almost never get a clear indication.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby was not sure how the conference would
react to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what will happen in the Pac-10?'' Bibby said.
``Nothing hashappened before when guys throw elbows.''
</P>
<P>
   The game officials will not be involved in the matter, because
they had already left the court before the altercation took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the solution is,'' said Booker Turner, the
Pac-10's coordinator of men's basketball officials.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? USC's players realize their predicament the rest of
the season, as they still hold out hope for an NCAA berth. The
Trojans (13-11, 6-6) probably have to win five of their final six
games for any chance at a bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no margin for error and we all know that from now on
out,'' guard Nate Hair said.
</P>
<P>
   Career games: USC had major problems with Arizona State forward
Tanner Shell. The 6-foot-6 freshman had 24 points at the Sports
Arena and 17 in Tempe, his two highest totals this season.
</P>
<P>
   Shell, who yelled at USC's players as they came onto the court
in the second half Saturday, also took a shot at the Trojans'
postseason hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they're not headed for the tournament, they're
headed for the NIT,'' hesaid.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range shooter: Point guard Brandon Granville made 9 of 14
of his 3-point shots last weekend in Arizona, but was only 4 for 15
on his two-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring drought: USC point guard Rashad Jones scored one point
against Arizona State, his first point since the Loyola Marymount
game on Dec. 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
