<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LESSONS IN REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain and the media ran into a reality check in South
Carolina, where Republican voters decisively rejected the Straight
Talk Express and voted instead for the man who once told struggling
workers, ``I know how hard it is to put food on your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere Al Gore is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the moment, Gore is enjoying the best of all
worlds. Bill Bradley's campaign is fading. McCain and George W.
Bush are locked in a blood feud that is diminishing the stature of
both men and devouring Republican campaign cash at a record clip.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rescued his campaign by heading South, where he threw off
even the pretense of compassionate conservatism and spent most of
his time slow dancing with the religious right. It was an ugly
embrace that offended blacks, Catholics, gays and, most of all,
McCain, who made no effort to hide his fury at the way he was
trashed by Bush and his allies.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's supporters spoke bitterly about the cheap tactics
of the Christian conservatives and other elements of the extreme
right.
</P>
<P>
   So what's new? This is what the Republican Party has been for
years _ the party of the religious right and Willie Horton, of the
Contract With America, of gun rights as opposed to gay rights. It
is the party of the big guy against the little guy, and it is far
more often a haven for bigotry than a champion of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain may have mesmerized the press over the past several
weeks, but he's not so different himself. Which is why he got
knocked around by Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The senator acknowledged that he had voted against an increase
in the minimum wage and is opposed to even the minimal gun control
efforts that most Americans favor, including the Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   This period of unprecedented prosperity has not been enough to
convince John McCain to support a tiny pay raise for those at the
bottom of the income heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the small-business person who's hurt when you raise the
minimum wage,'' he said, ``because they can't afford to pay their
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the fellow who is too liberal for the supporters of
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As for inclusion, which is something McCain says he is for _
well, he took a hit on that on Sunday, too.
</P>
<P>
   Russert asked him about Richard Quinn, who was McCain's chief
strategist in South Carolina. Quinn is editor in chief of the rabid
Southern Partisan Quarterly Review, a neo-Confederate magazine that
ritually denounces the likes of Abraham Lincoln and Martin Luther
King Jr..
</P>
<P>
   Russert asked McCain about an article written by Quinn that
said: ``What better way to reject politics as usual than to elect a
maverick like David Duke? What better way to tweak the nose of the
establishment?''
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I haven't seen the whole article and I wouldn't
see the whole article,'' said McCain, suddenly sounding as if the
Straight Talk Express had veered off the road.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, he said, was a man of integrity who didn't agree with the
more repulsive views in his own magazine.
</P>
<P>
   You believe that, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   The blood feud has already shifted to Michigan, which votes
Tuesday (along with McCain's home state of Arizona). The momentum
now supposedly is with Bush. If he hangs around until November (and
perhaps beyond), we can at least count on more of his malapropisms
and other forms of language mangling, a talent he inherited from
his dad.
</P>
<P>
   (The elder Bush gave us such gems as ``I'm not going to
hypothecate that it may.'' And ``It's no exaggeration to say the
undecideds could go one way or another.'' And ``Please just don't
look at part of the glass _ the part that is only less than half
full.'')
</P>
<P>
   George W. tells us we are ``in the beginnings of a long
marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment when it was widely believed that he would
inevitably win the marathon and become president, just as his
father, riding high in the aftermath of the Gulf war, was a sure
thing to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   We know better now. Bush the son is no more of a lock than his
pop. The one thing we've learned from this campaign is that the
Bushes are never inevitable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
