<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH AND McCAIN IN ROLE-REVERSAL IN MICHIGAN  
 (SUBS to correct spelling to Kevorkian in last graf of 1st take.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 14, 15, 16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also SC-REPUBS-ASSESS and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ As the bitter fight for the Republican
presidential nomination shifted to Michigan, Sen. John McCain on
Sunday leveled scorching and sustained attacks on Gov. George W.
Bush's reform credentials, while his rival stayed upbeat and
campaigned as if he were already in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Just one day after Bush's double-digit victory in South Carolina
decisively restored the Texas governor to front-runner status, it
was as if the two candidates had exchanged the roles they had
played in the nearly three-week-long campaign in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Bush who was sunny, once more talking about where he
wanted to lead the nation and his vision of ``a positive,
optimistic, hopeful tomorrow.'' And it was McCain who was
ferociously trying to tar his opponent as a fraud, much as he did
in his caustic concession speech the night before.
</P>
<P>
   At rallies, on his bus and in several television appearances,
McCain sought to reclaim his image as the reform candidate in the
race, and he went after Bush as aggressively as the Texas governor
had targeted him after the senator won the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain assailed Bush on a variety of fronts, from campaign
finance overhaul to regulation of health maintenance organizations,
from his tax cut proposal to state spending in Texas. Several times
during the day the senator said derisively, ``If he's a reformer,
I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   On his campaign bus, he heaped even more scorn on Bush. ``We're
not letting you get away with that, pal,'' he said. ``You're not a
reformer. Anybody who believes you're a reformer believes in the
tooth fairy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about such comments, Bush said, ``It sounds like
Senator McCain spent a lot of time talking about me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Michigan and Arizona holding their primaries Tuesday, and
Bush and McCain having spent virtually all of the past two weeks in
South Carolina, they have precious little time to make an impact on
voters here. McCain is expected to win his home state. But the big
unknown here in the critical industrial state of Michigan is
whether its voters will ratify Bush's decisive win in South
Carolina or show an independent streak of their own.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken on the eve of the South Carolina primary showed the
two men running neck and neck in Michigan, but there was no time to
calculate whether Bush's 11-point victory Saturday would alter the
landscape for Tuesday's primary. The state is now critical for
McCain, who must prove he is something more than a one-state wonder
who benefited from New Hampshire's maverick streak.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, Bush's aides believe that the victory and its
margin allowed him to adopt a new campaign posture. Throughout the
day, he mentioned President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore more
than he mentioned McCain, and his references to the senator came
mainly in response to reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of McCain's concession speech Saturday, in
which McCain used words like ``pretense'' and ``an empty slogan of
reform'' to describe Bush, the governor said, ``All of us have to
react to our victories and defeats in our own ways.'' He added, ``I
think the American voters, the people of Michigan, are going to
have to judge how each of us handles adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp was confident that the governor's South Carolina
success would go a long way toward propelling him to victory in the
approaching round of big state primaries. They were also looking to
benefit from the fact that Michigan is the first contest where Bush
has a sitting governor _ John Engler _ working strenuously for him.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan is less dominated by religious conservatives than
South Carolina, and McCain's aides argued that its blend of
working-class ethnic voters and regular Republicans would prove
more fertile ground for their candidate. They also said that
because of the short time period they would be able to run about
even with Bush in spending on television commercials, even though
outside groups have already weighed in here against McCain as well.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' McCain reached out to Catholic
voters when he was asked about Bush's appearance at Bob Jones
University, a center of the Christian right in South Carolina. He
said his rival should have spoken out against ``the things you've
said in the past about the pope and other religious leaders that
are disgraceful. Let's get into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On his bus, he also placed a thank-you phone call to Rep. Peter
King, a Long Island, N.Y., Republican who announced Sunday that he
was switching his allegiance from Bush to McCain. King, who is
Catholic and from a heavily Catholic district, has complained about
Bush's appearance at Bob Jones.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's new posture, it was clear Sunday that not all of
his and his supporters' aggressive tactics had been left in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   A harsh negative ad by the National Smokers Alliance that
assailed McCain for advocating a huge tax increase (without
mentioning the fact that it was a tax on tobacco) was being
broadcast here as it was in South Carolina. And Bush himself has at
least one ad running in Michigan that mentions McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also used the phrase ``Kevorkian's lawyer'' Sunday to refer
to Geoffrey Fieger, a Democrat who ran against Engler, the
governor, in 1988, and who has been running radio ads criticizing
Bush and Engler as ``dumb and dumber.'' Bush described Fieger, who
has in fact represented the assisted-suicide advocate Dr. Jack
Kevorkian in his murder trials, as ``the most liberal of liberal
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As he did in South Carolina, Bush used a surrogate to help him
attack McCain, in this case Engler. ``McCain has absolutely courted
some of our _ he's fraternized with some of the worst people,
politically speaking, they're our sworn foes,'' Engler said in one
appearance. ``He has tried to bring some of them in to influence
the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also reached out _ briefly _ to Christian conservatives,
who helped provide his margin of victory in South Carolina, as he
worshiped in a church in Grand Rapids. That part of western
Michigan has perhaps the densest concentration of religious
conservatives in a state that is otherwise largely Catholic and not
particularly fundamentalist.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an appearance in Southfield, at Lawrence Technological
University, Bush made one of his most energetic speeches in weeks.
``Listen to me now,'' he told the crowd. ``There are 260 days more
to no more Clinton-Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides said that their candidate had made several
mistakes in South Carolina, straying from his winning themes of New
Hampshire to run a campaign that focused too heavily on political
technique as he talked about abandoning negative ads or complained
about ``push-polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, appearing at rallies to the theme song of ``Star Wars,''
the senator let his enthusiastic audiences know that he would not
let his loss in South Carolina stop him. He made references
throughout the day to his years as a prisoner of war in North
Vietnam, locked away in the infamous ``Hanoi Hilton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends,'' he said to several hundred cheering suppoorters
at Michigan State University, ``I lived in a hotel once where there
were no mints on the pillow. I know how to take a punch and I know
how to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   He highlighted his congressional record of battling against
pork-barrel spending. Then, borrowing a line from onetime candidate
Steve Forbes, McCain repeatedly charged that state spending in
Texas had gone up under Bush, though he used two figures _ 34
percent and 36 percent. Under Clinton, he said, federal spending
had gone up 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who do you want? A big-spender nonreformer or a guy with a
record?'' he asked the Michigan State audience.
</P>
<P>
   He also skewered Bush on the isssue of money in politics. ``In
five and a half years, as the governor of the state of Texas, he
did not propose a single campaign finance reform proposal in a
state where anything goes,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator showed no remorse for an attack ad, which he
had removed from television in South Carolina, that challenged
Bush's truthfulness and compared him to Clinton. The senator has
now pledged to run no negative advertising throughout the primary
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain insisted that Bush had distorted the truth ``when he says
that I'm not a reformer, when he says that I'm a hypocrite, when he
says that I'm in the pocket of lobbyists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
