<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JARRETT, THIRD VICTORY AT DAYTONA IS NO BREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos (NYT 26 and NYT 27) are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The smiles came last on a day of emotional
extremes for Dale Jarrett. By Sunday's end, the defending Winston
Cup Series champion had won his third Daytona 500, considered the
Super Bowl of Nascar, before a crowd of 190,000 at Daytona
International Speedway. And there, to top it off, was the legendary
stock car driver Richard Petty, extending his hand in
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sent chills up my spine,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours before the race, he certainly did not feel
like the race favorite. His Ford Taurus sat in a garage with damage
to the both front fenders, hood and rear bumper, the result of a
collision with Jeff Gordon and Bill Elliott late in practice on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeless? Not with Robert Yates Racing, the megabucks team
owner. Three fabricators were flown in from North Carolina and,
working from 4:45 a.m. on, they virtually rebuilt the car's body.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned, Jarrett nursed the car early. But by the fourth lap,
``I knew the car was every bit as good as before.'' He led for 89
of the 200 laps and averaged 155.669 miles an hour in winning the
race under a yellow caution flag after Jimmy Spencer crashed his
Ford into a wall with little more than two laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who started from the pole, won $2,277,975, the biggest
payday in Nascar history. It includes $1 million from R.J. Reynolds
as one of five Winston Cup races rewarding the winner with that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton, N.C., native also won the Daytona 500 in 1993 and
'96.
</P>
<P>
   The next four finishers were also in Fords, including Jeff
Burton in second place and Bill Elliott in third. The highest
Pontiac finish was sixth, and Chevrolet had only one car among the
top 12.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett made a dramatic pass of the Pontiac-driving Johnny
Benson coming out of Turn 2 on the 197th lap to win the race. If he
had deserted his drafting help and not passed Benson, he probably
would have faded out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faked high and he went up there, and as soon as I saw him
move up the racetrack, I cut my car dead left,'' Jarrett said. ``I
was committed. If I would have had to go to the apron, which I
almost had to, that's where I was going. But I had a run and then
the 99 helped push me by.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, No. 99, had a simple explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my car, I couldn't run the middle,'' he said. ``I had to
run at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, still looking for a big-bucks sponsor to compete with
the big teams, flirted with an upset. Starting from the 27th post
position, he worked his way to the lead on Lap 158 and held on
through Lap 196, despite having five Fords breathing down his
bumper. On Lap 186, Mark Martin, running second, went high to pass,
and he apparently thought Jarrett was going to go with him,
providing drafting support. Instead Jarrett swooped low and took
second, while Martin quickly dropped to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that later, Martin said tersely, ``I got lied to.''
He chose not to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett acknowledged that he had agreed via radio to work with
Martin, but not indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried it for a lap and didn't really get a very good run,''
Jarrett said. ``Next time around, I had every intention of
following him again, but in my rearview mirror I saw the 99 car
dive to the bottom of the race track. I realized that if I didn't
go low, too, I would lose my spot for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Martin threw up his arms and yelled, ``What
happened?'' as Jarrett wheeled by him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally understand that,'' Jarrett said. ``I would have been
the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   There were six cautions in the race, and there were no crashes
until the 194th lap. And then Spencer's wreck took the suspense out
of the last two laps.
</P>
<P>
   Burton sounded far from bitter. ``The 88 car probably still
would have won,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Benson knew he had gambled by changing just two tires at his
last pit stop, but he said Jarrett earned the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything I could to block him on that pass,'' he said.
``Put it this way: I couldn't get him any lower.''
</P>
<P>
   There were many other dramas during the race, one that saw the
Fords take a decided early lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I saw, the Chevys need to work a little better
together,'' said Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief. ``I think the
Fords just more or less teamed up with each other and didn't work
with them very well. We were at a disadvantage two years and we had
to work at it. Now they have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the race:
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte's crew crippled his chance of a victory at the pit
stop on Lap 134. As he was returning to the track in third
position, one of his tires rolled into pit lane, prompting a
penalty from Nascar. He had to go to the back of the lead lap,
putting him 27th.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he finished sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton benefited the most from the stop, going from ninth
place to fifth. He wound up eighth.
</P>
<P>
   On the third yellow caution of the race, precipitated by Tony
Stewart's brush against a wall, which left metal fragments on the
track, Stewart injured a member of his pit crew. Mike Lingerfelt,
the front tire changer, went to move a tire out of Stewart's path
as the car was leaving the pit area and Stewart hit him. The tire
went flying into the infield as Lingerfelt fell in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   Lingerfelt, 23, from Marietta, S.C., suffered a fractured left
leg and was transported to Halifax Medical Center for surgery.
Stewart, who said it was difficult to concentrate on racing
thereafter, finished 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the three-time Winston Cup Series champion, was
eliminated from contention after his Chevrolet developed an oil
leak on the 30th lap. He fell four laps behind before he could
return and finished 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't run with those Fords, but I was making some
gains,'' Gordon said. ``I think we would have been able to get up
to about fifth or sixth, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the day belonged to the Fords, particularly Jarrett's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day full of emotions,'' he said, ``but in the end it
couldn't have worked out any better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
