<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-20 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS FOUND RIGHT PERSON TO SWAY PAYTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you are among the relatively few eyewitnesses to
the Sonics this season _ there is so much empty space in KeyArena
these days that it has drawn the attention of the Hubble telescope
_ your curiosity might have been piqued by the presence of Chuck
Person.
</P>
<P>
   As in: What is he doing out there?
</P>
<P>
   In his 14th NBA season, Person at 35 is the oldest Sonic, and
his game doesn't appear a day older than 50. He's played in barely
half the games, averaging three points in 10 minutes per contest.
The one-time ``Rifleman'' shoots 30 percent from the field,
including just 25 percent from behind the stripe, his one-time
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 8, he is neither a help on the boards nor in handling
the ball. And defense is something he figures goes around deyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reputation is as a shooter,'' he said. ``But I think I can
do more things to help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is pulling off what has been one of the more
difficult tasks with this franchise over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   He talks with Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Not at him. Not behind his back. Not against him _ hey, nobody
can do that. It's more productive to shake a finger at a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But Person can talk with him, a job almost as hard as trying to
one-up Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is a unique, sometimes puzzling guy,'' Person said. ``He
doesn't let a lot of people close to him. You have to earn his
trust and respect. You have to walk, and talk, where he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 10 years in Seattle, Payton has gone from arrogant rookie
with minimal game to an MVP-caliber star. But the arc has never
been as smooth as it has been for Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson,
Larry Bird, Karl Malone or John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Payton can be uncommonly prickly to friends as well as
opponents. His ultra-competitiveness combined with his
self-proclaimed street attitude has often alienated coaches and
teammates. And without a championship as a shield, Payton will
always hear the claim that his approach ultimately will cost him
and his team.
</P>
<P>
   But the circumstances this time around for the Sonics are
different, even unique, in his tenure. The roster was remade in his
image _ younger, faster, shorter, more mercurial. It was remade
with the expectation that he would lead it _ something he had not
done here.
</P>
<P>
   For a lone wolf, it is an awkward fit. Payton would much rather
be the gunslinger than the marshal.
</P>
<P>
   He can say that leading the NBA in minutes played over the last
half-decade should be enough. He can also say that topping the club
in points, assists and steals should also be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Good arguments. But the fact is, unless he leads by word and
deed, the Sonics have no shot.
</P>
<P>
   Person is the guy with the brass to tell Payton that the old
Gary won't get it done in some situations, and he can no longer
embarrass himself or the franchise with his tantrums. Person is the
one to remind that the only one left among Shawn Kemp, George Karl,
Tim Grgurich, Nate McMillan, Detlef Schrempf, Sam Perkins or Hersey
Hawkins is Payton.
</P>
<P>
   It's him or close to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Making the point, however, requires a little shrewdness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, he's willing to listen,'' Person said. ``He's
still going to be Gary; he's going to rant and rave. But I always
make sure never to tell him something in front of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will pull him aside, maybe during a timeout, maybe before
practice, maybe 11 o'clock at night. But he's willing to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those moments happened during a game in Milwaukee last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary was coasting,'' Person said. ``I told one of the coaches,
`Gary's struggling. You better get him out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``What? You know he'll go off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know. I got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton was pulled before halftime, and predictably erupted. But
Person pulled him aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `G, if you don't get it together, we can't win.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Payton came out big in the second half, and the Sonics beat Karl
and the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely are things so straightforward or productive, because
Payton is still so volatile. Last week, Payton followed up his
career-best 41-point night against Washington with a 4-for-19
stinker against Sacramento. That's what happens when one deals in
humans rather than binary code.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was back in form Saturday night, scoring 14 of his 27
points in the third quarter as the Sonics beat the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Payton's leadership has to come away from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to him about practicing,'' Person said. ``He has to
practice. Sometimes he can start practice, and then sit down. But
this team is so new to each other, Gary has to practice with them
every day in order for things to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership also includes the small stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him about bringing up his teammates' names in
the quotes in the papers,'' he said. ``Gary needs to trust and
respect his teammates, and once he mentions them, it gives them a
lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Person has slipped into a role once filled by McMillan, and more
recently by David Wingate, players senior to Payton who worked as
easily with him as anyone can. Some will contend that the Sonics'
biggest personnel mistake last year was cutting Wingate.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Person who horses around with Payton, or spots a flaw
or suggests a better shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always remember something one of my old coaches, Bob Hill,
told me,'' Person said. ``He said you have to make a bad night into
a good night, because the good nights take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Sonics are so dependent on Payton, if Person can
influence him to turn three bad games into good ones, it can make
the difference between a fourth-place seed in the Western playoffs
and a seventh seed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the same as hitting the game-winning 3-pointer. But
sometimes its important for the Rifleman to ride shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
