NYT-02-20-00 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3001 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     02-20 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS DEFEAT WAS MORE LIKE A WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marco Antonio Barrera is an example of a fighter
who was victorious in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, it seemed his on-the-rise career was
shattered after consecutive knockout losses to Junior Jones. At 23,
he was dismissed by some as a has-been and admitted that he
suffered significant psychological damage.
</P>
<P>
   His response?
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished something profoundly rare in boxing: He
resurrected himself upon the rubble of two taxing, disheartening
losses that might've destroyed a lesser man.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has combined more discipline and enough defensive skills
to avoid unnecessary punishment with the same raw aggression he
used to climb to the top of his division as a young fighter who was
promoted by the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   We saw the result on Saturday, when he turned in one of the most
remarkable performances in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Seven fights into what had been an unconvincing comeback,
Barrera beat up one of boxing's most-feared champions _ Erik
Morales _ in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't win in the eyes of the judges. He lost a close
decision in what certainly was a very close fight.
</P>
<P>
   However, he stunned the boxing world by making Morales look
beatable. Barrera, hurt so badly by Jones, stood up to Morales'
best punches and never ceased moving forward in what will be
remembered as a classic, give-and-take brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Morales might have connected on a few more punches but Barrera
landed the more meaningful, more pain-inducing blows. He hurt
Morales several times and the champion's face was badly bruised and
battered after the fight, much worse than Barrera's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you the truth, he had me reeling and hurt several
times during the fight,'' Morales admitted.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Morales was a bit less great and Barrera had
re-emerged as one of the elite _ as well as exciting _ fighters in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera, who had poured his soul into the fight, was bitter
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell HBO that their fighter isn't that good,'' he said
in the ring minutes after the decision was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Distraught, he missed the point: It's not that Morales (begin
ital)isn't(end ital) that good; it's that Barrera (begin
ital)is(end ital) _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Rematch? HBO executive Lou DiBella called immediately for a
rematch. However, it might not happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Morales-Barrera fight was expected to face
Naseem Hamed in a lucrative featherweight bout, assuming Hamed
beats Vuyani Bungu on March 11. Morales, who said he will no longer
fight at the junior featherweight limit of 122, probably will take
the Hamed fight if the big-talking Briton has the guts to sign.
</P>
<P>
   That means Morales wouldn't fight Barrera again until late this
year or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't pity Barrera. If he can maintain focus after such
a disappointing loss, he will remain in line for many meaningful,
good-money matchups in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   He earned that on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions, decisions: The scoring of Saturday's bout by judges
Duane Ford (114-113 Barrera) and Carol Castellano (114-113 Morales)
was no disgrace. The fight was that close.
</P>
<P>
   However, judge Dalby Shirley's card _ 115-112 for Morales _
bordered on ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera was awarded a knockdown in the 12th round, which means
Shirley's score would've been 116-112. That gives Morales an 8-4
edge in rounds, which is a clear victory.
</P>
<P>
   No way that fight was so one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley's score was the only thing that marred an otherwise
wonderful evening, one that boxing sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Mitch Halpern made a mistake on the knockdown _ which
appeared to be a slip _ but it had no bearing on the result.
Morales would've won a majority decision without the point
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity: Derrell Coley, who faces Oscar De La Hoya in the
biggest fight of his life on Saturday in New York, has been one of
the most frustrated fighters of the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old from the Washington D.C. area had been ranked
the No.1 welterweight contender by the WBC for roughly two years _
until De La Hoya displaced him after (begin ital)losing(end ital)
to Felix Trinidad _ but has yet to receive a championship bout.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was promised a bout with Trinidad after he beat De La
Hoya only to hear second-hand the announcement that Trinidad would
fight David Reid instead.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the most-asked question leading up to Saturday's
fight is: Who's Derrell Coley?
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point where I didn't like boxing,'' he said. ``I
didn't want to box. I'm not a quitter, though. I love a challenge.
I've survived this and now I have my title shot.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, De La Hoya-Coley (begin ital)is(end ital) a
championship fight. The winner is expected to be elevated to
champion assuming Trinidad remains at 154 after his fight with Reid
and gives up his 147-pound title, which is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few know who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Coley (34-1-2, with 24 knockouts) is similar to Oba Carr. He's
well-schooled, quick and only a moderately hard puncher. He had a
fine amateur career: 96 victories, four losses before turning pro
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe he won the only fight he officially lost, to Carr
in 1995. Carr was promoted by Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Three of his biggest victories were over Terrence Alli (TKO in
11 rounds) in 1994, Ray Lovato (decision) the following year and
Romallis Ellis (decision) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no respect.
</P>
<P>
   Coley blames his promoters _ he's jumped from one to another _
but acknowledges that he has nothing special on which to hang a
marketing campaign. He's a good fighter without compelling
background.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he's in the the difficult position of being a significant
risk: too much talent, not enough payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone is fortunate enough to get an Olympic gold
medal,'' he said, referring to De La Hoya. ``The professional level
is different. You could be a great amateur and a bad pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone deserves a chance. Why would they have
ratings if they didn't plan to abide by them?''
</P>
<P>
   Coley will make $1 million-plus against De La Hoya, which dwarfs
his previous high of $175,000 against Carr.
</P>
<P>
   However, he insists this isn't about money. Again, he's had to
scrape and claw for everything he's accomplished in boxing while De
La Hoya took the high road from the Olympics to superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   For Coley, this is about acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's earned anything he has,'' Coley said of De
La Hoya. ``... He's way overrated. They made De La Hoya into a
superstar. He didn't earn superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pick who they want to be successful in boxing and I had
my frustrating days. Now, I'm the happiest fighter in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad night? Coley might've been exposed as vulnerable against
journeyman Pat Coleman when the two met in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Coley was dominating the fight when Coleman threw a punch that
Coley said landed on his shoulder in the 10th round. It apparently
hit a nerve and Coley was knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   The bout was later ruled no contest when Coleman tested positive
for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gone,'' Coley admitted. ``Regardless of the drugs, it
was a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   If Coleman can render Coley helpless with one punch, imagine
what might happen against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Reid, who like Coley is promoted by America Presents,
predicted Coley will beat De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his talk about the `new Oscar,' or `the original Oscar,'
or the `new and improved Oscar,' only shows me that he's the (begin
ital)same(end ital) Oscar,'' said Reid, who fights Trinidad on
March 3. ``And that's the Oscar who was shown up by Pernell
Whitaker, lost to Felix Trinidad and given a close shave by Ike
Quartey. He hates to be hit, so he won't take any chances in this
fight. I think Derrell Coley will give a clinic for as long as it
lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Feb.26, you won't be hearing any more talk about Oscar
moving up to 154 pounds. It wouldn't surprise me if he moved back
down to 140.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of what Reid says is true, he's off-base on his
prediction. Most believe De La Hoya will win easily.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Boxing lost a memorable voice in Chuck Hull, the
ring announcer who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, 75, announced most of the big Las Vegas fights of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, he personified the sport of boxing in Las
Vegas,'' said Marc Ratner, the executive director of the Nevada
State Athletic Commission. ...
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deny former champion Terry Norris a boxing
license in Nevada was sound.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to the 32-year-old have expressed concern about
damage to his brain. He already is difficult to understand because
of what has been called ``lazy speech syndrome'' and doctors fear
he could further deteriorate. ...
</P>
<P>
   Two Los Angeles amateurs are scheduled to compete in the U.S.
Olympic box-offs, Thursday through Saturday in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Mosley faces Dante Craig at 147 pounds while Jose Navarro
takes on Roberto Benitez at 112 pounds. The winners advance to the
Americas Olympic qualifier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
