<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-S.C.-CONSERVATIVES-BO     02-20 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S.C.-CONSERVATIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, CONSERVATIVES CARRIED DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ While South Carolina voters were busy
repudiating Senator John McCain's summons to a new direction for
the Republican Party, they also knocked down the notion that
politics have changed in this growing state.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Arizona senator thought he saw an opening among the
half million new residents who arrived in the state during the past
decade, he was overrun Saturday by a surge of Christian
conservatives and old-line Republicans who threw their support to
Texas Governor George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conservative state,'' said Henry McMaster, chairman
of the Republican Party of South Carolina. ``We are conservative
fiscally, we are conservative socially, we are conservative
whatever else there is.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolinians turned out in record numbers, lured by Bush's
siren song of ``limited government and lowered taxes'' and a
God-and-country approach highlighted by Bush's appearance at
fundamentalist Bob Jones University in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan was also aided enormously by a veteran Republican
organization led by Carroll Campbell, a former South Carolina
governor. It is the same GOP network that gave Bush's father a
critical victory in the 1988 South Carolina primary and helped Bob
Dole turn back a threat from Patrick Buchanan in 1996, shortly
after Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   During McCain's successful campaign in New Hampshire, his
strategists looked ahead to South Carolina and saw a chance to
break the old regime. They believed Campbell's organization had
atrophied after a candidate it was supporting, Governor David
Beasley, lost a bid for reelection 15 months ago, and they felt
McCain would be a natural favorite among new, independent-minded
voters in the Myrtle Beach and Greenville-Spartanburg regions.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowds seemed to grow with each successive rally in South
Carolina last week, one of McCain's chief advisers predicted that
as many as 400,000 voters might turn out in the primary. If that
threshold were crossed, he said, McCain would win.
</P>
<P>
   Never had more than 276,000 voted in a South Carolina
presidential primary. On Saturday, however, more than 560,000 South
Carolinians cast votes. McCain took 238,000, a number his aides
thought would easily be enough to win. But regular Republicans,
apparently concerned that their primary would be violated by an
influx of nonparty voters, rushed to the polls for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted by a consortium of news organizations found
that Christian conservatives accounted for one-third of the total
vote, and they supported Bush by a 2-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right has long been an important element in
Republican politics in this state, which is top-heavy with Southern
Baptists and other evangelical faiths.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush used a nationally televised debate last Tuesday to
point to a feud between the Christian Coalition and Warren Rudman,
a former New Hampshire senator who supports McCain, the
conservative grapevine buzzed the rest of the week with word that
Rudman had called the organization ``bigoted'' because the group
criticized General Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   An 11th-hour endorsement of McCain by Gary Bauer, a leading
Christian conservative who dropped out of the presidential race,
proved to have little impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush's message resonated among the religious
conservatives,'' said Randy Tate, director of Republican affairs
for Voter.com and a former Christian Coalition official.
</P>
<P>
   ``They approved of the moral tenor of his campaign. They are
concerned about issues of integrity, particularly as we move out of
the Clinton area,'' he said. ``And they know the next president may
pick three Supreme Court judges, which could lead to the overthrow
of Roe v. Wade.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate said Bush also succeeded, in large measure, in ``winning
over the old Reagan Democrats who were the only hope for McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two weeks, McCain talked repeatedly of
attracting thousands of independents and ``Reagan Democrats'' in
South Carolina, forces that would become part of a new Republican
coalition he would lead. But in a state with no party registration,
most of the Reagan Democrats have considered themselves Republicans
since Ronald Reagan converted them in the 1980 primary, and they
appeared to march lock-step with traditional Republicans in support
of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   When the results were complete late Saturday, it was apparent
that McCain succeeded in attracting unprecedented numbers of
independent and Democratic voters for a Republican presidential
candidate. But it was not nearly enough. Bush won 70 percent of the
votes among those who identified themselves as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a 40-point deficit among Republicans'' for McCain, said
Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster who specializes in Southern
campaigns. ``You can't win a Republican nomination with those
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John McCain is going to succeed elsewhere, he's got to
energize independents and do far better among registered
Republicans,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
