<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACE--BIOTMETRIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILE _ ATM KNOWS YOUR FACE  &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Throughout the history of civilization, the human face has remained
the easiest method for people to identify one another.
<P>
   Now, a San Francisco company believes it is poised to cash in on
new technology that allows computers to recognize faces and,
eventually, store gigabytes worth of information about that person.
</P>
<P>
   InnoVentry Corp., a joint venture between Wells Fargo Bank and
U.S. pawnshop king Cash America International Inc., is marketing an
ATM that uses face-recognition technology to identify its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   About 180 of the ATMs, called RPM, are already in convenience
and grocery stores in Texas and Arizona. An additional 300 machines
in a version called ATREVA are in gambling casinos in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to have an additional 1,500 installed by the
end of 2000. It signed a deal last week to put the ATMs in
billionaire Donald Trump's casinos in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   InnoVentry is one of the biggest examples of how cutting-edge
biometric technology is entering the consumer world. As companies
scramble for ways to tighten their security measures against
hackers, what better, more secure form of identification is there
than the human face, asks InnoVentry CEO Frank A. Petro.
</P>
<P>
   InnoVentry uses a program called FaceIt, developed by Joseph
Atick, CEO of Visionics Corp. of New Jersey. While he was head of
Princeton University's Neural Cybernetics Group and later the
Computational Neuroscience Laboratory at Rockefeller University in
New York, Atick began studying how mathematical algorithms could be
used to tell one person's face from another.
</P>
<P>
   The program determines a face print by quickly computing the
measurements between 60 possible facial landmarks, such as the
center of the eyes, the bridge of the nose or the protrusions of
the jaw or cheekbones. The distances between only 14 of those
``nodal points'' can determine a face print that won't change even
if you grow a beard or wear glasses, Atick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do a lot more than a nose job to get your relative
distances altered,'' Atick said.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology is now used by the Israeli government to
monitor 50,000 Palestinian day laborers who cross from Gaza to
Israel each day. It was also used with a closed-circuit TV system
to identify wanted criminals in the London borough of Newham and
credited with helping reduce crime by about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   InnoVentry markets an ATM primarily aimed at the estimated 65
million Americans who want to cash checks but either don't have a
bank account or maintain low balances in their checking account.
Customers sign up by registering their faces and Social Security
number with InnoVentry, but need only show their face for
subsequent visits.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1998, has enrolled more than 350,000
customers and cashed 1.3 million checks with a loss rate that is
``well below 1 percent,'' Petro said.
</P>
<P>
   The ATMs will soon dispense money orders and online bill-paying
services, and Petro believes the machines will help Internet-based
banks lure future customers. InnoVentry expects to roll out about
25,000 machines in the United States in the next four years, and
unlike most biometric companies, it expects to start making a
profit in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   InnoVentry also plans to use face recognition for a broader
range of services, such as allowing credit card advances. For
example, the company is testing a system that will recognize a
customer pumping gas, know what products that customer has bought
in the past and display targeted ads on a nearby monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biometrics has the ability to create a more intimate
relationship with your customers,'' Petro said.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year in Phoenix, the company plans to test a system
in which customers can order and pay for groceries online at work
and pick them up on the way home, using only their face to identify
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   While the technology seems to reflect some of the themes in
George Orwell's classic novel ``1984,'' about a totalitarian
society filled with all-seeing view screens, Petro said his ATMs
still give the customer control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to use this, this is not Big Brother forcing
you to do this,'' Petro said. ``We're trying to engineer something
here to create better value for the consumer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GUN--BIOMETRICS-SFCHR     02-20 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN--BIOMETRICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMART GUN' MAY BE A MUCH SAFER ONE  &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
John Stiver was given a handgun for his services about 10 years ago
after doing some computer consulting for a firearms publication. He
had never owned a gun before. He had three children at home.
<P>
   ``We ended up locking it up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually, he got to wondering if there wasn't a better
solution, some way that the gun could be made secure to prevent
accidents in the home while still being accessible in case of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Stiver is president of Advanced Biometrics, a Puyallup,
Wash., company that is among a number of outfits working to come up
with technology for a ``smart gun'' _ a weapon that can recognize
and function only for authorized users.
</P>
<P>
   Such weapons are for the most part still on the drawing board,
although prototypes are being developed by leading firearms
manufacturers. A new generation of smart guns, advocates say, will
significantly reduce firearms-related accidents in the home and
prevent stolen weapons from being used in other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is among the more enthusiastic supporters of
smart-gun technology. He has called for providing some $10 million
in federal funds to firearms manufacturers so they can push ahead
with development of authorized-user-only weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In Advanced Biometrics' case, the solution lies in employing a
beam of light to scan the user's entire hand, both above and below
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much better than using fingerprints,'' insisted
Stiver. ``It's easy to duplicate a fingerprint. I can make one that
identifies me as you with 35 cents' worth of latex.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Advanced Biometrics is nowhere close to making its
technology compact enough to fit into the handle of a pistol _ the
ultimate goal of all smart-gun endeavors. And while Stiver said his
company could have a rifle-size version operational in about six
weeks, he estimated this would take about $80,000 in new
research-and-development funding.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, a company called Applied Biometrics says it
has scored a breakthrough in smart-gun research by shrinking its
fingerprint-identification technology to the point where it and a
pair of AAA batteries can be inserted into a pistol handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real,'' said John Catalano, the firm's chief executive.
``Ready for prime time today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of. While Applied's technology was incorporated in a
high-security version of the PalmPilot last month, it has yet to be
tested in a prototype weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Foley, vice president of product engineering at Smith &AMP;
Wesson, the country's largest handgun manufacturer, said Applied's
technology is still too costly and too fragile for use in actual
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said his company is leaning toward a rival
fingerprint-ID system created by Mytec Technologies in Toronto.
This one is contained in a separate module that attaches to the
handle of a newly developed pistol with an electronic firing
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Upon pressing a finger to the module, an authorized user would
detach the gun and be ready to fire. ``It can be done relatively
quickly,'' said Dennis Hollingshead, Mytec's CEO. If the gun is
released, it instantly locks back up again.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson's Foley said he expects the first smart guns to
reach the market in about two years. Smarter guns with handle-based
security systems would follow several years later.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Foley said uniform standards should be set for
user-ID I.D.  &LR; technology and procedures, and legislators will have
to address the question of exempting the technology's developer
from product-liability issues in the event of shooting accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of testing and an awful lot of proving
that still has to occur,'' he said. ``But if people want to make
this happen, we can make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the National Rifle Association is wary of any
firearm-related measure backed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the development of new technology,'' said Jim
Marown, a spokesman for the organization. ``We welcome its
introduction to the market, but only as long as it's not government
mandated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the NRA believes that gun owners should be free to
choose the security they use for firearms in the home and that
``the key to preventing accidents is education and training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot make a smart gun,'' Marown said. ``You can only
make smart gun use.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
