<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CAR--BIOMETRICS-SFCHR     02-20 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR--BIOMETRICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET YOUR FINGERS DO THE DRIVING  &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK AND CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The trouble with car keys is it's easy to lose them. Or leave them
in the ignition, letting a thief simply drive away.
<P>
   But several automakers are building prototypes that don't use
keys to start a car at all, instead scanning drivers' fingers or
thumbs. DaimlerChrysler showed off a thumb-reader, for instance, in
a ``concept car,'' introduced last month at the Detroit Auto Show.
And General Motors plans to incorporate the technology in a
Cadillac prototype during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because fingerprints are considered unique (and hard to lose),
proponents say the technology could be enormously popular as a
replacement for car keys.
</P>
<P>
   It could also let cars recognize the driver, and adjust
everything from the car seat pitch to the radio station. ``It's
very convenient,'' said Won Lee of Secugen, a San Jose biometrics
company that makes fingerprint readers. Secugen is working with
several automakers, though it says the technology won't appear on
car lots for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   And DaimlerChrysler spokesman Sjoerd Dijkstra said the
technology still has plenty of kinks. For one, he said, fingerprint
readers are too delicate to expose to sun, sleet and other harsh
conditions on the outside of the car, so drivers probably would
still need to carry a key or remote control to open the door.
</P>
<P>
   And Dijkstra said it's still too cumbersome to turn the car over
to a valet or mechanic. Though drivers can program the car to
recognize additional fingerprints, the current driver must be
sitting in the car with the new one and go through several steps.
That's fine for a spouse or kids, Dijkstra said, but too slow when
simply dropping the car off at a parking lot. And the problem is
even worse when turning the car over to an auto shop for repairs if
the mechanic who will be working on the car isn't available when
the car is dropped off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of questions that are still unanswered,'' said
Dijkstra. ``It's more of a gizmo right now than a real feature.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main arguments for using fingerprint or handprint
readers in cars is to prevent auto theft, experts say. Thousands of
cars are stolen each year because someone left the keys in the
ignition. And BMW engineers say some thieves have even broken into
homes to steal keys, because some cars are difficult to break into.
</P>
<P>
   But if your finger becomes your password, might thieves also be
willing to cut one off to steal a car?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely one of the issues that has to be taken into
account,'' said BMW engineer Byron Shaw. He said some researchers
claim the technology can ``distinguish a live finger from a dead
one,'' but said there is no definitive proof. And even if a car
could tell the difference, Shaw added, it wouldn't do the driver
much good if the thief didn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves also have a track record of hot wiring cars and finding
other ways around security devices. Many thieves, for instance,
have learned to foil the popular Club _ a bar that locks the
steering wheel in place _ by pouring a few drops of liquid nitrogen
on the device and cracking it, or simply sawing the steering wheel
off and using a screwdriver to steer the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take rocket science'' to defeat these devices, said
Jean O'Neil, research director for the National Crime Prevention
Council.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neil said scanners could be a strong deterrent if combined
with other technologies _ like a ``kill switch'' that wouldn't
supply any gasoline to an engine unless the scanner gives the green
light. Though thieves often try to find ways around the devices,
eventually, she said, ``they run out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Biometrics technology has other possible car-related uses, such
as sensing the driver's condition to find out if the person appears
drunk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
