<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3021 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-SPI     02-20 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GOING ALL OUT IN WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington's Feb. 29 Democratic presidential primary, a beauty
contest in which no national convention delegates are chosen, has
nonetheless assumed a do-or-die importance to the insurgent
campaign of former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be here practically every day until the
primary,'' Bradley said in an interview before leaving Seattle for
New York. He will debate Vice President Al Gore Monday night at
Harlem's historic Apollo Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican contest between Texas Gov. George Bush and
Arizona Sen. John McCain has dominated news since the New Hampshire
primary. It has choked off media coverage of the Democratic contest
in which Bradley needs to gain traction against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Washington represents the first Gore-Bradley face-off since New
Hampshire, aside from a meaningless primary in Delaware that drew
few voters. It is also the Democrats' only showdown before critical
primaries in New York, California and other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is very important,'' Bradley said Saturday. ``It
comes a week before March 7. It is an opportunity for us to
demonstrate movement ... Washington state is also a place where I
am extremely comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for a momentum-building Bradley showing has not been
lost to the Gore campaign. It has staffed the Washington effort
with veterans of the vice president's successful campaign in the
Jan. 24 Iowa caucuses. Tipper Gore will campaign in the state
Monday, speaking to a Democratic crab feed in Olympia Monday night,
and the vice president will appear at a dinner party Saturday night
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Gore backers have also counterpunched at every Bradley
appearance. Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., countered one Bradley visit
with a hastily called news conference at which she defended the
vice president's record on womens issues and reproductive rights.
Last week, Reps. Norm Dicks and Jay Inslee, D-Wash., along with
Sierra Club Northwest representative Bill Arthur praised Gore's
environmental achievements.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes have not dimmed in the Bradley camp. Seattle Mayor
Paul Schell, who backs Bradley, said a win in the state could
``bring about another shift in momentum in a year already full of
surprises.'' Schell and Oregon Gov. John Kitzhaber campaigned with
Bradley on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley trailed Gore by a margin of 64-26 in a CNN-USA Today
poll taken last week by Gallup. After Tuesday's GOP contests in
Michigan and Arizona, however, ``the attention will focus back on
this (Democratic) race,'' Bradley argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say they know the vice president better than me,'' he
added. ``I'm pretty easy to know. I've always been pro-choice. I
look at Al Gore when he was in the House and he voted 84 percent
pro-life. He was viewed as a poster boy for the National Rifle
Association, now he supports limited gun control ... You have to be
an archeologist digging to know where he has been on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Although citizens will go to the polls a week earlier, Democrats
will use the March 7 precinct caucuses as a basis for picking their
delegation to this summer's national convention in Los Angeles. The
Democratic National Committee refused to recognize any presidential
delegate selection prior to March 1, except for the Iowa caucuses
and the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington has a tradition of being rough on front-runners,
and giving its heart to at least one reformer in every presidential
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of independents and Democrats invaded the 1980 GOP
caucuses to give a strong showing to liberal Republican Rep. John
Anderson. Colorado Sen. Gary Hart upset eventual Democratic nominee
Walter Mondale in the 1984 caucuses. In 1992, former Sen. Paul
Tsongas easily outdistanced Bill Clinton, who also ran behind
former California Gov. Jerry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous surveys have shown that, among Washington voters,
self-described independents now outnumber both Republicans and
Democrats. Next week, voters will be free to choose which party's
primary in which to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is facing stiff competition for independent and
reform-minded voters. McCain needs a victory in the Republican
primary to recover momentum from Saturday's loss in South Carolina.
An Elway Poll, taken earlier this month, showed the Arizona senator
heavily supported by independents. Republicans will use their
party's primary to determine one-third of the delegation to the GOP
National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and McCain have made campaign finance reform a
centerpiece of their campaigns for the presidency. But, in
Bradley's view, the Democratic and Republican insurgents have
``significant differences'' on numerous other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pro-choice (on abortion), he is not,'' Bradley said. ``I
am for common sense gun control, he is opposed. I have proposed a
comprehensive health care program aimed at gaining coverage for
every American, he has not.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has argued that he opposes abortion except in cases of
rape, incest and threat to the life of the mother. He has spoken of
the need for background checks on gun buyers, but opposes Bradley's
call for registration of all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans a barnstorming tour across Washington on Wednesday.
He will speak at a morning rally at Gonzaga University, deliver a
noon speech in Seattle and later travel by boat to Bremerton for a
rally.
</P>
<P>
   In their calls for political reform, both Bradley and McCain
will likely find fertile ground in Washington. The state's voters
enacted a pioneering public disclosure law in 1972. Two decades
later, they voted to limit individual contributions to candidates
for state office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, for a lot of people nationally, our political life is
like a broken thermostat: You turn it and it doesn't work,''
Bradley said. ``Money determines the outcome on issues. Big things
can't be done ... Politics is being seen by the public as an
exercise in the mechanics of winning _ fund raising, media and
polling _ rather than something that can improve their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley faulted President Clinton and Vice President Gore for
failing to act on political reform in 1993 and 1994, when Democrats
held the White House and both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he went to Clinton in 1993. ``I told him, `You
ought to do campaign finance reform first because it is the key to
doing everything else,''' said the former New York Knicks forward.
But he said the White House preferred to play an inside game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EYES--BIOMETRICS-SFCH     02-20 1863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYES--BIOMETRICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL PASSWORD IS FOR YOUR EYES ONLY  &HT;     BY KELLY ZITO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
If the eyes are a window to the soul, the iris could be the window
to a keyless, cardless, password-less world.
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from DNA, the iris _ or colored ring that surrounds the
pupil _ is considered among the most distinctive human
characteristics, and therefore, among the best ways to definitively
identify a person _ better even than fingerprints, voice or face
(even though developers of each technology say theirs is best).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is iris scanning, as it's called, is also among the
most expensive _ about $800 for a hair dryer-size consumer
identification device for a PC (not to mention the special cards it
requires) versus about $100 for a much smaller fingerprint system.
</P>
<P>
   As with most technologies, the price of iris scanning will
decline as the hardware and software becomes &LR;  cheaper and more
companies jump into the development ring _ but that will happen for
other biometrics as well. And iris technology, which analyzes about
266 data points in the iris, will always remain more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   For those and other reasons, consumers probably won't find iris
technology popping up in everyday devices anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Raj Nanavati, a partner at International Biometric Group, a New
York biometric consulting firm, says iris recognition works well in
ATMs and facilities where management is trying to control access to
a building.
</P>
<P>
   On the consumer side it's fuzzier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the consumer market, fingerprint (recognition) is more
appropriate because it's much smaller and cheaper to use,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Iris technology works like this: Instead of sliding a card
through a reader in the foyer of an office to gain access, a user
stands about two feet in front of a special camera.
</P>
<P>
   The camera zooms in on the eye, records an image of the iris and
converts it to a digital file similar to a bar code. If the code
matches the existing one on file, the worker proceeds inside. If
they don't match, it's time to call upstairs. Though there's some
debate as to the necessity of an exact match, IriScan, the leading
iris technology company, says the probability that two irises will
create the same digital code are 1 in 10 followed by 78 zeros.
</P>
<P>
   So far, banks, prisons, public assistance programs and even
e-commerce companies have invested in the technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highest-profile users is Bank United in Houston, &LR; 
Texas &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 12-year-old bank installed iris scanning
components in three prototype automated teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months the iris-ATMs have been in place, the bank
has gotten mostly positive feedback, it says, with a few complaints
that the technology doesn't work with certain mirrored sunglasses.
Most consumers like the fact that they can ditch one of the cards
in their bursting wallets and commit one less PIN number to memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preliminary results have been favorable on all accounts _
customer acceptance, usage and an image of the institution being
forward-thinking,'' said Bank United spokesman Vern Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the results after a year, the bank will decide this
summer whether to spend about $5,000 a pop to retrofit more of its
ATMs with the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have a vested interest in driving customers to ATMs _
they're more accurate and cheaper to maintain than humans. But
industries outside the financial realm also are testing the
usefulness of iris recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The Sarasota County Sheriff's Office in Florida says it thwarted
two inmate escape attempts in the first year it used iris scanning
at its detention center. There, the system verifies the identity of
all inmates who leave the facility _ for court appearances, work
assignments and at the end of the term.
</P>
<P>
   A company in Virginia is hoping to help cities speed up commutes
by developing an automated fare collection system that uses iris
technology. The system would allow commuters onto train or subway
platforms after they've been identified by their transit accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Biometrics experts say iris recognition _ not to be confused
with retinal scanning, which requires an examination of the inner
part of the eye _ is accurate because of the complex nature of the
connective tissue of the iris.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare it to face, where you can grow a beard, or
voice, which is a hybrid between physical and behavioral
characteristics, iris scanning is a more robust technology,'' said
Nanavati.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike fingerprints, irises generally don't don't &LR;  generally
 &LR; change over time, unless the person develops cataracts or suffers
some trauma. Fingerprints, on the other hand, can be marred by
scars or abrasions over time. There's also a certain criminal
stigma attached to fingerprints, as well as concern about the
cleanliness of pressing a pad used by hundreds or thousands of
others.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 study by Gartner Group, a Massachusetts research firm,
said iris recognition will overtake fingerprints by 2002 as the
preferred biometric for installations serving many users.
</P>
<P>
   But iris scanning, like all biometrics, faces a major roadblock
in gaining acceptance _ worries about privacy. Because these
technologies are so accurate, many believe consumer rights will be
sacrificed in the name of preventing fraud and increasing
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly IriScan thinks the technology will overcome
those hurdles and eventually become as ubiquitous as cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   John Siedlarz, the Marlton, N.J., company's president and chief
executive, believes a couple of in-development technologies will
change the way we interact with our cars, homes, banks and
employers.
</P>
<P>
   IriScan is currently working on the Iris Key, a handheld device
equipped with a camera that authenticates a customer's ID and is
then pointed at the front door of a house, car or boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradigm shift is so rapid today,'' he said. ``A few years
ago people saw the Palm Pilot and said, `This is a toy.' Now it's
indispensable.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; DIGITAL PASSWORD IS FOR YOUR EYES ONLY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY KELLY ZITO &LR;
</P>
