<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EAZEL--LINUX-SFCHRON &LR;      02-20 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAZEL--LINUX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LESS COMPLEX LINUX: FIRM WANTS TO MAKE OS AS EASY AS
MAC,  WINDOWS 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
For the average computer user, Linux isn't nearly as friendly as
its smiling penguin mascot suggests. But now, proponents of the
freely distributed operating system are stepping up efforts to make
it more inviting to non-geeks.
<P>
   Eazel, a Palo Alto startup, is working with volunteer
programmers around the world to give Linux a new ``graphical
shell'' _ a point-and-click interface for managing files and
folders.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal: to make the upstart OS at least as easy to use as
the Mac or Windows _ and eventually even easier.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ambitious objective, but the people leading Eazel have
done it before. Most of them played key roles in creating Apple's
Macintosh almost two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to raise the bar in the same way the Finder and
MacPaint and MacWrite did,'' said company co-founder Andy
Hertzfeld, referring to the Mac's first software _ some of which he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Eazel initiative isn't the first effort to humanize Linux.
Its users already have a choice among two fairly extensive
graphical user interfaces, called KDE and Gnome, as well as a
variety of more limited ``window managers.'' Eazel originally
intended to offer its own alternative, but recently decided to join
the international team working on the second version of Gnome.
</P>
<P>
   The combined product, called Gnome 2.0, is slated for release
this summer. Like Linux itself, it will be distributed under an
``open-source'' license. It will be free to users, and its source
code, or underlying programming instructions, will be available to
programmers who want to improve or customize it.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Eazel's file-management software, code-named
Nautilus, are still in flux, but to judge by current prototypes,
Windows and Mac users will find it easy to master. Along with
familiar GUI basics _ icons, menus and multiple windows _ it will
offer a number of innovations, including the ability to view the
contents of many kinds of files right in the folder windows that
contain them. Icons will be variable in size, and users will be
able to zoom in and out to see more or less detail. Icons for text
documents will include the first few words or lines; for graphics
files, the image itself will be the icon.
</P>
<P>
   Eazel's executives know they won't be able to transform Linux
overnight. ``Linux for your mom is where we want to end up,'' said
Bart Decrem, one of the company's co-founders, ``but for the next
year or two, The software will be ``componentized,'' according to
Hertzfeld, so other developers will have an easy way to add new
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzfeld, who co-founded Eazel last August and now holds the
title ``software wizard,'' designed much of the original Mac OS,
including its user-interface code, while working at Apple in the
early 1980s. The new company's chief executive, Mike Boich, served
as Apple's first ``software evangelist'' for the Mac, before going
on to found two graphics-hardware companies, Radius and Rendition.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, another Apple veteran _ Bud Tribble, manager of the
original Macintosh software team _ signed on with Eazel as vice
president of software engineering. After leaving Apple in the
mid-1980s, Tribble, a former neurosurgeon, became vice president of
software engineering at Steve Jobs' NeXT Computer, then moved to
Sun Microsystems, where he helped create the Java programming
language. Most recently he has served as chief technology officer
for the Sun-Netscape Alliance, which produces e-commerce software.
</P>
<P>
   Eazel's board includes Mike Homer, a former marketing executive
at Apple who went on to become an executive vice president at
Netscape and now holds the title of senior vice president at
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Eazel's other co-founder, Decrem, is a native of Belgium. He
graduated from Stanford Law School and then founded Plugged In, a
nonprofit ``community technology access center'' in East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The startup's original funding came from its founders and
employees, but it has subsequently received ``angel'' investments
from several high-profile Silicon Valley sources, including Ron
Conway's Angel Investors, Sippl cq  &LR; Macdonald Ventures and former
Macromedia chairman John ``Bud'' Colligan, now a partner at
venture-capital firm Accel Partners. The amounts have not been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has yet to disclose details of its business
plan, but it reportedly intends to generate revenues by offering
tech support, automated updates and configuration assistance over
the Internet to users of its software.
</P>
<P>
   Linux, a derivative of the Unix operating system, originally
sported a ``command-line interface,'' requiring users to type in
cryptic instructions for even basic functions such as launching
programs and copying files. The initial versions of KDE and Gnome,
along with a variety of more limited ``window managers,'' made the
system easier to manage, but they remain more complex than Windows
or the Mac, and at times users may still confront a command line.
</P>
<P>
   Linux's popularity has skyrocketed over the last few years, but
mainly on computers used as Internet servers. In addition,
International Data Corp. recently estimated that some 4 million
people now use it on desktop machines, but most of these are
programmers, engineers and other technical users.
</P>
<P>
   While the addition of Eazel and its software heavy hitters are a
major boost to the Gnome team, the rival KDE interface is likely to
remain a strong alternative. The two Linux distributors who have
put the most emphasis on reaching out to mainstream desktop users _
Caldera Systems of Orem, Utah, and Corel of Ottawa, Canada _
currently ship KDE with their versions of the OS. And like the
Gnome group, the team behind KDE is hard at work on an ambitious
second version.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of other companies are also at work on new software
that could attract a broader audience to Linux. Corel, which
already offers a Linux version of its WordPerfect word processing
program, is now bringing the complete WordPerfect Office suite,
which also includes a spreadsheet, database, and graphics tools, to
the new platform.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Cambridge, Mass., startup named HelixCode is
reportedly developing a Linux equivalent to Microsoft Outlook, a
program widely used for e-mail, scheduling and other basic needs on
Windows systems. HelixCode's staff includes Miguel de Icaza, the
former Mexican university network administrator who initiated the
Gnome project.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; 
Corp. recently estimated that some 4 million people now use it on
desktop machines, but most of these are programmers, engineers and
other technical users.
</P>
<P>
   While the addition of Eazel and its software heavy hitters are a
major boost to the Gnome team, the rival KDE interface is likely to
remain a strong alternative. The two Linux distributors who have
put the most emphasis on reaching out to mainstream desktop users _
Caldera Systems of Orem, Utah, and Corel of Ottawa, Canada _
currently ship KDE with their versions of the OS. And like the
Gnome group, the team behind KDE is hard at work on an ambitious
