<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVEST--ONLINE-SFCHRO     02-20 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST--ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP WEB SITES FOR INVESTMENT TIPS 
 &HT;     BY HARRY DOMASH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; I'm always on the lookout for good stock ideas. Anyone who
spends much time online knows there is an abundance of tips out
there, but quality is another matter. Over time, I've accumulated a
list of sites I can count on for good ideas. Here are some of my
favorites.
<P>
   CBS MarketWatch
</P>
<P>
   I rely on CBS MarketWatch ( &LR; cbs.marketwatch.com &LR; ) for timely
ideas from what I call ``superstar pundits.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the well-known money managers and analysts you
frequently see on TV and quoted in the financial press.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is finding them. CBS MarketWatch is difficult
to navigate. The best way to find the columns is to select Regular
Features just below the main headlines on the home page. Then click
on Commentary for a list of current columns.
</P>
<P>
   CBS MarketWatch carries at least a dozen different columns. Here
are the ones I try not to miss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frank Cappiello &LR; . The longtime Wall Street Week panelist is a
mutual fund and money manager who favors blue-chip growth stocks.
His columns mix overall market comments with specific stock
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Courtney Smith &LR; . Orbitex Funds' chief investment strategist
uses fundamental analysis to select stocks but also looks at the
charts before he buys a company. Smith's columns generally feature
a single company, usually midcap growth, describing its business
and prospects in detail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joe Battipaglia &LR; . The chairman of investment policy at Gruntel
&AMP; Company focuses on the technology portion of the market. He
sometimes recommends individual stocks, but his emphasis is on the
outlook for the tech market in general. Run for cover when he gets
bearish.
</P>
<P>
   CBS MarketWatch archives three or four recent columns by each
pundit. You can find them by clicking Commentary Library on the
Commentary page.
</P>
<P>
   MSN MoneyCentral
</P>
<P>
   the stock, his current view and a sell price target.
</P>
<P>
   Jubak's Future Fantastic 50 is an aggressive, mostly high-tech
version of his conservative ``50 Best Stocks in the World''
portfolio. Jubak started the Future Fantastic 50 on July 30, 1999,
and hasn't made any changes since. As of Jan. 28, 2000, the
portfolio was up 62.9 percent since inception compared to 2.4
percent for the S&AMP;P 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   ValueStocks.net
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  ValueStocks.net ( &LR; www.valuestocks.net &LR; ) is run by Dr. Michael J.
Burry, CEO and chief investment strategist at hedge fund Scion
Capital Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Burry, inspired by Benjamin Graham, looks for beaten down stocks
trading far below their real or intrinsic value.
</P>
<P>
   Burry tracks his stock picks in a hypothetical mutual fund he
calls the VSN Fund. You can see his portfolio of 20 or so stocks by
selecting VSN Portfolio on ValueStocks.net's home page.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked, he had shorted Amazon.com. Burry does a lot of
trading for a disciple of Benjamin Graham. As of February 8, most
of the stocks had been in the portfolio less than three months. You
can see his trades for each month by clicking on VSN Fund Activity
below the portfolio and fund results.
</P>
<P>
   The VSN Fund returned 68.1 percent in 1999 according to Burry.
</P>
<P>
   America-iNvest.com
</P>
<P>
   The site MicroCap1000.com was renamed America-iNvest.com
( &LR; www.america-invest.com &LR; ) in November when it expanded its focus
beyond micro-cap stocks to encompass all size companies. The site
provides two good sources of ideas: the Model Portfolio and
Editor's Choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Model Portfolio is a basket of 15 or so stocks taken from
the site's MicroCap 1000 index. The index consists of 1,000
companies with a maximum market cap of $500 million. They're all
listed on the Nasdaq or the New York or American stock exchanges.
According to the site, the Model Portfolio returned 143 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the Model Portfolio by clicking Portfolios on the
home page and then selecting MicroCap Model Portfolio. Click on the
link at the bottom to see deleted listings.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Heftner, America-iNvest.com's editor, highlights
individual stocks in his Editor's Choice column. The updates appear
on an irregular schedule, but at least once a week. Heftner gives a
detailed rundown on each company, its business and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned investors treat all tips, whether from Warren Buffett
or a Yahoo chat room, as ideas to be researched, not ``buy''
signals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
