<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCH     02-20 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET DRUGMAKERS TO DO THE RIGHT THING 
 &HT;     BY TOM ABATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miraculous advances in medicine are widening the gap between the
healthy nations of the West and the rest of the planet, where poor
people die by the millions from illnesses that aren't lucrative
enough to interest drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, the fruits of biotechnology are available only
to the fortunate few and not to the many,'' says Richard Feachem,
director of the Institute for Global Health in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Feachem gathered more than three dozen world health leaders in
Carmel this past weekend to discuss the embarrassing fact that,
while medicine has increased life spans in the developed world to
77, average life expectancy in the poorest nations is closer to 52.
</P>
<P>
   Feachem enlisted the support of people such as Sean Lance, chief
executive of Chiron Corp. in Emeryville; Adel Mahmoud, president of
the vaccines division for New Jersey's Merck; Dr. Sally Stansfield,
medical director for the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation; and
World Bank economist Joseph Stiglitz.
</P>
<P>
   The get-together was called to suggest tax and other incentives
to encourage the development of vaccines for illnesses such as
diarrhea and pneumonia, which kill millions of poor kids but are
not considered drug research targets because there's no money in
curing them.
</P>
<P>
   It can take 10 to 15 years and hundreds of millions of dollars
to develop a new vaccine or a drug. Companies have a tough time
justifying that sort of expense for malaria research, when a drug
to fight fat, impotence or cholesterol would be a much bigger
moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior execs regret this, but they have commercial pressures
on their decisions they cannot ignore,'' Feachem said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some companies have bucked the profit motive and
done the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, for instance, scientists at Merck realized that
Ivermectin, a drug they were developing to treat heartworms in
dogs, also seemed to kill the parasite that causes river blindness
in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   River blindness is spread by parasites that breed alongside
fast-moving water. The parasites multiply and migrate through the
body, causing a debilitating itch and, in many cases, blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Merck executives gave the scientists permission spend years
modifying the dog drug to be safe for humans. By 1987, Merck had
created Mectizan, a $1.50 pill that prevented infection by the
parasites that caused river blindness.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one hitch. There was no market for Mectizan.
National governments in West Africa pleaded poverty. People in the
bush were too poor to pay. International health agencies had other
priorities than mass-purchasing river blindness pills and then
giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   So Merck decided to make Mectizan freely available,
indefinitely. So far the company has dispensed 400 million pills
though a network of public health officials. The program has been
so successful that last year the World Health Organization declared
river blindness ``on the verge of elimination,'' and credited
Merck's pill with sparing 12 million African children from
blindness.
</P>
<P>
   A Merck spokesperson said the company was able to justify the
giveaway because Ivermectin, the dog pill, was so profitable.
Imagine that. Dogs in the developed world have greater access to
pharmaceuticals than West Africans.
</P>
<P>
   And that is really what the medical divide boils down to, a
problem in purchasing power. Japan topped the world in per capita
drug consumption in 1990, according to Feachem's figures, spending
$412 per person. Germany and the United States followed at $222 and
$191, respectively. Mexico managed $28 per head, far less than its
northern neighbor but still far more than the $4 spent by Kenyans
or the $3 spent by Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Given that drug development will always follow the money,
Feachem's group can only hope to propose modest measures to
redirect some research toward unprofitable Third World killers like
malaria or tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   But at least policymakers are receptive. Legislation now in
Congress, including Rep. Nancy Pelosi's HR 1274, would create tax
incentives for vaccine research. President Clinton, who addressed
the medical divide in his State of the Union speech, has asked
industry leaders to join him in March to find ways to bridge the
gap.
</P>
<P>
   Feachem hopes to come away from Carmel with proposals, vetted by
industrial, governmental and philanthropic leaders, to put into
Clinton's hands. I'll revisit the issue from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   CASE IN POINT: ``The Coming Age of Biotech,'' by Richard Oliver,
business professor at Vanderbilt University, captures the
excitement engendered by biotechnology. &UR;  &LR; Oliver isn't troubled by
the inequities in the distribution of medical advances. His point
is that science is poised to deliver fascinating therapies for
people with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coming Age'' heralds potential breakthroughs _ such as
stem cell research to grow new organs and drugs to preserve memory
_ in breathless, hyper-optimistic prose. Biotechnology, Oliver
writes, ``promises to add more years to human life expectancy in
the next half century than were added throughout all prior human
history!''
</P>
<P>
   Though hyperbolic, Oliver provides a good overview of the
currents in biotech research and development. He explains how
biotech will affect not just drugs and agriculture, but every form
of manufacturing. Biotech has taught scientists how to create
molecules that perform specific tasks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, we've used these molecule-building skills to fashion new
drugs. But biotech techniques can be just as readily applied to
creating inorganic molecules to filter pollution from the air,
perhaps, or build microscopic machines. Science is on the verge,
says Oliver, of ``making every atom and every cell a factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff, and some of it no doubt true. I thank Scott
Morrison, biotech consultant with Ernst &AMP; Young in Palo Alto, for
bringing it to my attention.
</P>
<P>
   People interested in learning more about biotech would benefit
from a skeptical reading of ``The Coming Biotech Age.'' Just figure
that everything will take longer and be more difficult than he
assumes, and that the most profound changes are probably things
Oliver hasn't imagined. It is an exciting time in bioscience, and
the book sizzles with that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
