u a BC-NY-AVALANCHE-NYT &LR;      02-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AVALANCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE ADIRONDACK AVALANCHE KILLS SKIER AND INJURES FIVE OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six back-country skiers who ventured into a dangerous snowslide
area were caught in a roaring avalanche and swept hundreds of yards
down a mountainside in the Adirondack High Peaks of northern New
York State on Saturday. Rescuers found one dead under the snow and
his companions all injured, one critically.
</P>
<P>
   While avalanches are not uncommon in Alaska and the Alps, they
are unusual in New York, and state officials and forest rangers
said they could not recall a similar death in Adirondack Park, the
vast preserve of mountains, lakes and forests stretching from the
Mohawk River to the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was not stormy, although three to four inches of
snow fell in the area Friday night, and the cause of the slide was
unclear. But state officials said that Hurricane Floyd last
September may have been a factor. Its rains caused a landslide that
swept away vegetation and soil from the slope where the snow
collapsed. It had been posted for months with warnings to hikers
and skiers.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche _ a shelf of snow 100 yards wide that broke loose
and rumbled down 500 yards _ struck shortly before 1 p.m. on the
northeast slope of Wright Peak, a 4,580-foot mountain nine miles
south of Lake Placid. In its path was a party of skiers who had
been warned orally twice that the slope was unstable.
</P>
<P>
   The skiers, far off the marked trails and more than halfway up
the mountain, were carried away. ``They rode it down,'' said Lt.
Gary Roberts, the state forest ranger who coordinated the search
and rescue operation. ``It must have been a couple of hundred
yards, and it must have been terrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Toma Jacob Vracarich, 27, of Lake Placid,
was buried in the snow and killed. Lauren Konowitz, of Keene, N.Y.,
suffered head and internal injuries, multiple fractures and
hypothermia. She also was buried, although she was soon uncovered
by two companions who were less seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that a witness had heard the avalanche and used a
cell phone to call forest rangers of the State Department of
Environmental Protection, which manages the state parks. Two
rangers on skis, Jim Giglento and Gary Hodgson, were on patrol in
the area, checking avalanche conditions, and within 40 minutes had
found the five survivors, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   A state police helicopter ferried them to the Adirondack Medical
Center in nearby Saranac Lake, where Konowitz underwent surgery and
was admitted to the intensive care unit in guarded condition. Her
husband, Ron Konowitz, and the others, Dean Cook, of Saranac Lake,
Christina Ford, of Lake Placid, and Rohan Roy, of Chateaugay, were
treated for various injuries and released.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a search for Vracarich was organized. The effort was
joined through the afternoon by 50 people _ forest rangers, state
police officers, Lake Placid firefighters, officials of the State
Emergency Management Office and the State Office of Fire Prevention
and Control and local volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobiles were used to bring in long probes to search the
snow, portable lights and other equipment. Rangers said the search
was difficult because the area had been hazardous since the runoff
of Hurricane Floyd five months ago, and had been made more
dangerous by snowstorms and thawing that created shelves of
unstable snow. Some skiers had reported wandering into armpit-deep
snow.
</P>
<P>
   It was after dark, about 6 p.m. Saturday, when a dog belonging
to a volunteer led the searchers to Vracarich's body. It was buried
in about three and a half feet of snow, Roberts said. The victim
was taken to Lake Saranac, pending an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Post, a spokeswoman for the State Department of
Environmental Conservation, said the avalanche occurred on a slope
where a major landslide had taken place last September, part of the
widespread damage caused by the torrential rains of Hurricane
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The landslide _ one of several at the time in the 46 Adirondack
High Peaks ranging up to more than 5,000 feet _ left a swath of
Wright Peak's northeast slope denuded of vegetation, a barren area
that could not hold soil or snow. The slope had been posted with
warnings for months, and the skiers, said to be very experienced,
had been warned, Post said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew they were taking a risk,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were signs in the area and they apparently had been
warned on Friday and Saturday, by a forest ranger and by someone
from the Adirondack Mountain Club,'' she said, referring to a
private group. ``They were cautioned about the possibility of
slides.''
</P>
<P>
   But Post and Roberts noted that the skiers, while taking a
chance, had done nothing illegal in going into the dangerous area.
And despite the accident and a continuing investigation, he said,
the slope where the avalanche occurred will remain open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of freedom out there in the park,'' the
lieutenant said. ``That's the way it has to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although avalanches are relatively uncommon in New York, at
least 33 major snowslides have struck south-central Alaska in
recent weeks. They have killed two people, flattened homes and
warehouses, snapped trees, cut off electricity to thousands,
blocked highways and caused an estimated $16 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, where 11 people were killed in avalanches last year,
experts say this year's slides, two of them mile-wide monsters,
have been caused by unusual cycles of thawing and freezing,
creating unstable glacial shelves on mountain sides and conditions
for what one official called ``hundred-year avalanches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
