<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-GORE-NYT &LR;      02-20 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOGETHER ON THE STUMP: MRS. CLINTON AND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y _ They sat with their heads together, whispering
into each other's ears and at one point holding hands. They bobbed
and swayed and clapped in syncopation as the crimson-robed choir
rocked behind them. They invoked their college days and Bob Dylan
and their 1992 bus adventure across America.
</P>
<P>
   And at the end of a three-hour church service here, nothing
seemed more natural than the fact that Vice President Al Gore and
Hillary Rodham Clinton would be campaigning together, reinforcing
each other with their shared political heritage and their shared
political desire to run on Bill Clinton's successful economic
record but away from his impeachment-stained legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Clinton have left the White House nest and are learning
to fly on their own. Sunday at the Wilborn Temple, a historic black
church in downtown Albany packed with more than 1,000 worshipers,
the two came together for the first time as candidates, he for
president, she for senator from New York. They praised each other
to the rafters and their spokesmen said the two were eager to
appear together again.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been on his own a little longer and his wings seem a
little stronger. He dominated the service with a rousing 25-minute
sermon that prompted some in the audience to call out ``Preach!''
and ``Amen!'' as he proclaimed the nation to be at a ``mountaintop
moment.'' He exulted in the first lady's work for education and
families. ``I have seen her rare mix of idealism and effective
leadership, of inspiration and stamina,'' he declared from the
pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Clinton lavished similar praise on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in America is more qualified to lead us than our vice
president,'' she said. ``He knows what to do and how to do it, in
ways visible and perhaps invisible to the general public. He has
been the partner in progress that has been made with our president
and has helped to lead this country to this extraordinary moment of
opportunity and obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment they were referring to was the one where the country
is now, leading the longest economic expansion in American history.
But the moment that drew such attention was the intersection of
these two candidates _ one a vice president who is campaigning with
a new sure-footedness as he marches through the primary season, the
other a first lady who is making a historic leap for political
office, both of them linked to a president both hailed and scorned.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Clinton had been circling each other for some time, but
aides to both determined that the moment for their joint appearance
was at last ripe. In other words, they would probably help each
other more than they would hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days of rumors of their rivalry for the
president's attention and their competition to make major
announcements. When Clinton met Gore's limousine Sunday morning
outside the red-brick church, they hugged each other with what
seemed like genuine affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to see him was a pleasure,'' Clinton said later. ``I'm
very fond of him personally.''
</P>
<P>
   They made their joint debut to an overwhelmingly sympathetic
crowd, at a service for the annual meeting of the Legislature's
black and Hispanic members. Black and Hispanic Americans are among
President Clinton's most loyal supporters, and they make up about
15 percent of the state's Democratic voters. (Gore even dropped a
little Spanish into his sermon Sunday; Clinton said that as a girl,
she had heard the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. speak and ``it
changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is enormously popular among these core Democratic
voters, as is Gore. The thinking in both campaigns is that Clinton
could help boost the turnout in New York's March 7 presidential
primary for Gore over former Sen. Bill Bradley. Of course, Gore is
already well on his way to claiming his party's nomination, so
there was no real risk for him Sunday in appearing with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, advisers in both camps expect that by the
fall, Gore, as a Democrat, will be stronger in New York than the
Republican presidential nominee, whoever that is, and that he can
then help Clinton. He may face more of a problem in aligning
himself with her at that time if she has not won over at least two
groups _ white women and Orthodox Jews _ who are not now
enthusiastic about her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Gore and Clinton is that together, they are a
double-dose extension of the Clinton era. They both played that
association down Sunday, with Clinton brushing past a reference to
``our president'' and Gore paying hasty respect to the Clinton-Gore
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But most striking was how very similar their speeches were, both
in style and in content. Great chunks of their speeches were
interchangeable with each other's and with President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   They both highlighted the economic boom, the low unemployment
rate for African-Americans and the strides in helping families pay
for college. They both said that while much had been achieved in
the last several years, much remained to be done. And they offered
the same centrist-Democratic course for the future, calling for the
expansion of health care and advocating hooking up all classrooms
to the Internet, making prescription drugs cheaper for the elderly
and closing the digital divide, in which those with computers (who
tend to be white) have economic advantages over those without
computers (who tend to be members of minorities).
</P>
<P>
   In reference to high rates of poverty in New York, Clinton said,
``It doesn't have to be this way.'' This has been a longtime
campaign theme for Gore, who tells audiences, ``It's not supposed
to be this way.'' After they spoke, the Rev. A.R. Bernard Sr., the
guest minister, took the pulpit and highlighted something else they
have in common _ bad press. He said he was grateful for the chance
to meet them and touch their hands. ``I've learned not to let the
newspapers tell me who people are,'' he said to great applause.
</P>
<P>
   For some, President Clinton's scandals only forged a new respect
for the first lady. As Gloria Davis, an assemblywoman from the
Bronx, said in introducing her, ``She knows what trials and
tribulations are.'' She later added: ``We understand Hillary. She
may be young. But she has what it takes, because in this world you
got to be strong. You got to be able to say, `Back off.' You got to
be able to say, `Move over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the churchgoers seemed charmed by the event. Rodney
Goulding, 66, a retired police officer from the Bronx, said he
would vote for Clinton and Gore after hearing them Sunday. ``This
country is in the best shape that it's ever been,'' he said, ``and
you don't want to stop the ball from rolling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
