<DOCNO> NYT20000220.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-20 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-1STLD-WR     02-20 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND IS SMART AND SHARP IN RACE 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for complete writethru.) 
 (ms) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ From the transom of Team New Zealand's
latest weapon of engagement, NZL 60, Brad Butterworth, the Kiwi
tactician, basked in the cheers of thousands of dockside
well-wishers moments before pulling into his syndicate's compound
Sunday after a businesslike 1-minute-17-second victory over Italy's
Prada Challenge in Race 1 of the five-of-nine-race America's Cup
finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a broad grin plastered across his mug, Butterworth caught
the eye of someone ashore. Then he wagged his index finger skyward,
toward the glorious blue heavens, and said, ``That's one.''
</P>
<P>
   Going back to their performance in San Diego in 1995, when they
mercilessly dismantled Dennis Conner's American defender in a 5-0
drubbing, the Kiwis have won six straight races in America's Cup
finals. Considering that it has been five years since the New
Zealanders faced outside competition in a truly meaningful contest,
as opposed to in-house training and sparring, the sailing clinic
they displayed for the Italians was nothing less than masterful.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, Francesco de Angelis, the low-key Prada
helmsman, was philosophical. ``It's just the beginning,'' he said.
``Someone had to win and someone had to lose. But it's just the
first day. Our team has come back before.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the Italians showed in the long lead-up to these cup
finals that they could fight back. But they had to be disheartened
by one glaring certainty. In the day's 12- to 14-knot breezes and
flat seas, the conditions in which they purportedly might enjoy a
marked speed advantage over the Kiwis, they clearly did not.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the boat-speed differences between NZL 60 and
Prada's Luna Rossa, one interested and knowledgeable observer, the
Australian yacht designer Iain Murray, said: ``The Kiwis have an
upwind edge, though Prada may be marginally faster downwind. But
the New Zealanders sailed a terrific race.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's first point is open to debate. As de Angelis rightfully
said about the quickness issue: ``I think it's too early to
comment, after a shifty day like today. I think the boats are very
close.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no disputing the fact that the Kiwis showed no
trace of the rust many felt would be inescapable after forgoing the
traditional defender trials leading up to a cup match. In their
nation of under four million citizens, Team New Zealand felt that
multiple defense syndicates would unnecessarily drain the country's
available resources in terms of both corporate backing and
manpower.
</P>
<P>
   So they decided to go it alone, and many believed that the lack
of a competitive work-up would be a fatal flaw. But the Kiwis
seemingly picked up right where they left off in 1995 and
Butterworth, particularly, was on top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth decided, early on, that the first significant wind
shift of the day would fill in from the right, and he protected
that side of the course as if the day's outcome depended on it,
which, as events proved, it did.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian tactician Torben Grael, to his credit, also
understood that the right side would pay handsomely. And he did his
level best to get Luna Rossa past the Kiwis and over to the spot
that both crews coveted. But the Kiwis, with flawless boathandling,
would not let him by.
</P>
<P>
   Grael had one shot, as both boats converged on opposite tacks
about halfway up the first windward leg. But Luna Rossa was on port
tack and NZL 60, on starboard, held right-of-way under the racing
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians would need to cross clear ahead; if the Kiwi
helmsman Russell Coutts altered course in even the slightest
manner, Luna Rossa would draw a potentially race-losing foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cross was the best one for us, but still it would have
been very scary to cross them, especially against those very
experienced guys,'' Grael said. ``It was early in the race and we
shouldn't risk a cross like that. We tacked to leeward and we lost
after that. But I think we wouldn't have been able to cross
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Grael was right, and Luna Rossa would not have made it
cleanly across. And not risking everything on an early maneuver in
the opening race of the America's Cup finals was definitely the
conservative, reasoned thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Grael may need to rethink his strategy next time and roll
the dice, for spotting the Kiwis an early, substantial lead in this
regatta could be suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   Race 2 is Tuesday. If, at the end of the day, Brad Butterworth
is waving two fingers at the crowds, the Italians will be in deep
trouble. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
