<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON JOINS CALL FOR OIL RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton joined a growing chorus of
Northeastern lawmakers Sunday in calling for a regional oil reserve
to help states cope with future shortages of home heating oil and
tamp down soaring consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a candidate for United States Senate in New York, said
Northeastern states rely most heavily on home heating oil and
therefore pay the highest prices during cold spells. In recent
weeks, a coalition of Democratic and Republican lawmakers from
hard-hit Northeastern states have been calling for a regional
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take this issue very personally, as does the president,''
Clinton, who recently bought a house in Chappaqua, N.Y., said in an
interview with a local television station. ``Now that we are
homeowners here in New York, our house is heated by heating oil,
and it is extremely expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, has
repeatedly criticized President Clinton for refusing to release oil
from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to drive down the cost of home
heating oil. As oil-producing countries have limited production,
the cost of heating oil soared to a peak of $2.02 earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep making this an issue until the president
releases the reserve,'' Giuliani said Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-00 2231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
