<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 02/19/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) HOLLAND, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- SC-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT --
Many conservative Christians identify with George W. Bush, shown
attending church Sunday in Michigan. For years, the demise of
organized religious conservatives has been declared. And while the
effort by groups like the Christian Coalition seemed decidedly tame
here compared with previous years, conservative Christians probably
played a decisive role in Bush's victory over Sen. John McCain in
the South Carolina primary. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- CAR-DAYTONA-2 --
Dale Jarrett sprays champagne after winning his third Daytona 500
at Daytona International Speedway on Sunday. He led for 89 of the
200 laps and averaged 155.669 miles an hour in winning the race
under a yellow caution flag after Jimmy Spencer crashed his Ford
into a wall with little more than two laps to go. (Tony Ranze/The
Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- CAR-DAYTONA-1 --
Dale Jarrett is congratulated by his crew after winning his third
Daytona 500 at Daytona International Speedway on Sunday. He led for
89 of the 200 laps and averaged 155.669 miles an hour in winning
the race under a yellow caution flag after Jimmy Spencer crashed
his Ford into a wall with little more than two laps to go. (Pierre
DuCharme/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) EAST LANSING, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 --
MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-4-B&AMP;W -- James W. Hensley, Arizona beer baron and
father-in-law of John McCain. Hensley gave McCain his first job out
of the Navy and helped bankroll his crucial first race for Congress
in 1982, enabling McCain, a political newcomer, to outspend and
defeat better-known opponents. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- OBIT-SOBCHAK
-- Anatoly A. Sobchak, the former mayor of St. Petersburg and
democratic reformer who gave Acting President Vladimir V. Putin his
start in public life, died of a heart attack this morning,
officials said. He was 62. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- OBIT-PATZERT-B&AMP;W -- Rudolph
W. Patzert in 1946. Patzert, the captain of a rusty 1904 gunboat
that carried more than 1,380 Jewish refugees from Europe to
Palestine as part of a secret rescue operation after World War II,
died Jan. 21 in a nursing home in Encinitas, Calif. He was 88. The
cause was cancer, said his son Bill. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) FORT HOOD, Texas -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- CANADIAN-GENERAL --
Rick J. Hillier is a major general in the Canadian Army. He is also
deputy commander of the United States Army's Third Corps. ``Some
found it a little strange at first,'' he says as he oversees a
group of National Guard soldiers preparing to leave Fort Hood for
Bosnia. ``Now it doesn't seem to matter that I'm in a Canadian
uniform. They just view me as part of the team.'' (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- THINKERS-CONVENE -- The
artist Joe Coleman, with an exploding firecracker on his stomach,
at Disinfo.con, an 11-hour event that its organizer, Richard
Metzger, summed up as ``Cyberpalooza. It drew an audience in the
hundreds at the Hammerstein Ballroom on Saturday; most were
clean-cut, in their 20s and working on the Internet or in other
media jobs. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Feb. 20, 2000 --
ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-2 -- John Redinger of Webcor uses a laptop
computer at a Santa Clara job site. Webcor's on-site
superintendents, like Redinger, can get access to the most
up-to-date specifications for a construction project on the Web.
(Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LONDON -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- LONDON-THEATER-2 -- The
intimate 400-seat auditorium of the restored Royal Court Theater in
London, where stucco has been removed to expose riveted cast-iron
plating. The leather seats, however, would not look out of place in
a gentleman's club. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LONDON -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- LONDON-THEATER-1 -- The
facade of the restored Royal Court Theater in London. When
reconstruction began, the ambitions seemed to outdistance the
possibilities. ``We were contemplating creating a proper working
theater out of the shambolic, unhygienic, aesthetically problematic
mess we had,'' says Stephen Daldry, the former artistic director.
``At one point we thought of knocking the whole thing down and
starting from scratch.'' (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- LETTERS-THEATER-REVIEW --
Tai Jimenez plays Fran in ``Letters From Cuba.'' You would be taxed
to name a show with a sweeter temper than this production - a
lovely and contemplative autobiographical morsel by Irene Maria
Fornes that opened Sunday at the Signature Theater's Peter Norton
Space. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HOLLAND, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MICH-REPUBS-3 --
Though the strain of campaigning shows on the face of Gov. George
W. Bush, who flew to Michigan overnight after his primary victory
in South Carolina on Saturday, the Texas governor was generally
upbeat, espousing his vision of ``a positive, optimistic, hopeful
tomorrow'' with renewed vigor. Sen. John McCain, however, chose on
Sunday to lead a sustained and brutal attack on Bush's reform
credentials. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WARREN, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MICH-REPUBS-2 -- Gov.
George W. Bush speaking to supporters at a rally held at the
Lawrence Technological University in Warren on Sunday. Just one day
after Bush's double-digit victory in South Carolina decisively
restored the Texas governor to front-runner status, it was Bush who
was sunny, speaking of his vision of ``a positive, optimistic,
hopeful tomorrow'' with renewed vigor. (Andrea Mohin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WARREN, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MICH-REPUBS-1 -- An
animated Gov. George W. Bush speaking to supporters (excluding the
distracted children behind him) at a rally held at the Lawrence
Technological University in Warren on Sunday. As the fight for the
Republican presidential nomination shifted to Michigan, Sen. John
McCain on Sunday attacked Bush's reform credentials, while his
rival stayed upbeat and campaigned as if he were already in the
general election. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- WATTS-PROFILE -- Rep.
J.C. Watts Jr. is the only black Republican in Congress. He is also
the communicator in chief for his party in the House, and a rising
national conservative star. But three weeks ago, Watts nearly
called it quits, frustrated with his job and its strains on his
family back in Oklahoma. He changed his mind only after
constituents in his district urged him to run again. ``The deciding
factor was that my family said, 'We are willing to stand with you
for re-election,' `` he says. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) EAST LANSING, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 --
MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-3 -- Sen. John McCain at a Michigan State
University rally Sunday in East Lansing. McCain is running for the
Republican presidential nomination as a champion of campaign
finance reform and an opponent of special interests. Yet a look at
his rapid ascension shows that his early career was founded on
special-interest money, and that he might never have emerged from
the competitive world of Arizona politics without the steadfast
backing of the city's political and business establishment. (Chang
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LIVONIA, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-2
-- Sen. John McCain signing copies of his book at a rally in
Livonia on Sunday. McCain is running for the Republican
presidential nomination as a champion of campaign finance reform
and an opponent of special interests. Yet a look at his rapid
ascension shows that his early career was founded on
special-interest money, and that he might never have emerged from
the competitive world of Arizona politics without the steadfast
backing of the city's political and business establishment. (Chang
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST LANSING, Mich. -- Feb. 20, 2000 --
MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-1 -- Sen. John McCain - his wife, Cindy, at his
side - speaking at a Michigan State University rally Sunday in East
Lansing. McCain's position as one of the wealthiest members of
Congress is derived from his wife's share of her family's
Anheuser-Busch beer distributorship in Phoenix and extensive real
estate investments through the company. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HOLLYWOOD -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- TALENT-AGENTS-MEDIA --
Members of the Broder, Kuland &AMP; Webb talent agency meeting in
Beverly Hills. From left, Chris Silbennann, Ted Chuvkin, Robert
Broder, Norman Kuland and Elliott Webb. Under a tentative agreement
with the Screen Actors Guild, talent agencies will soon be able to
participate in the financing and distribution of films and
television shows as well as have a noncontrolling interest in a
production companies. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- EAZEL-LINUX -- Mike
Boich, left, Andy Hertzfeld and Guy Tribble of Eazel Inc. want to
make the Linux system easier for ordinary PC users. This summer,
Eazel plans to begin offering a free user interface - an icon-based
software control system that can be downloaded from the Internet -
that they say will give Linux an ease-of-use advantage over
Macintosh and Windows-based computers. (Thor Swift/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- VANGUARD-JAZZ-2-B&AMP;W -- Max
and Lorraine Gordon at the Blue Angel, one of Mr. Gordon's clubs,
in the 1950s. Mr. Gordon also founded the Village Vanguard, which
is holding a private 65th birthday party expected to draw many of
the artists who have played it over the years. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- VANGUARD-JAZZ-1 -- Lorraine
Gordon marks the 65th birthday of the Village Vanguard, her
legendary jazz club, on Monday night. ``I've invited every musician
in town,'' says Gordon, 77. While a jam session is not officially
on the agenda, she says, ``if they don't play, this is not a jazz
club.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- KOSOVO-UNREST-3
-- American and German peacekeepers were pelted with rocks and
bricks Sunday during a massive house-to-house search for illegal
weapons in this tense, ethnically divided Kosovo town. Serb
officials bitterly complained about alleged acts of violence and
intimidation committed by the Americans. ``Americans were smashing
doors, destroying furniture,'' says Oliver Ivanovic, a local Serb
leader. ``There was no reason for such behavior.'' (Andrew
Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- KOSOVO-UNREST-2
-- French troops hold back a crowd of Serbs trying to attack German
soldiers as they moved into northern Mitrovica on Sunday to search
for weapons. The search -which turned up 14 rifles, a machine-gun,
seven blocks of plastic explosive and ammunition - was a bid to
halt a spiral of violence that has been building since Feb. 2, when
two Serbs died in a rocket attack on a U.N. bus. (Andrew Testa/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- KOSOVO-UNREST-1
-- Serbs in northern Mitrovica on Sunday throwing snowballs,
stones, rocks and bottles at departing U.S. peacekeeping troops who
entered the city to search for weapons. ``We either had to withdraw
or shoot somebody,'' a U.S. soldier says. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-TALKS -- David
Boies, chief trial lawyer for the Justice Department, is one of the
major players in the Microsoft antitrust case in Washington. The
stakes are high for both sides in what one person close to the
talks called ``the ultimate antitrust poker game.'' Walking away
from the settlement talks, under way since November, could well
mean waiting a couple of years for a final outcome in the courts,
including appeals. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN
