intimidation committed by the Americans. ``Americans were smashing
doors, destroying furniture,'' says Oliver Ivanovic, a local Serb
leader. ``There was no reason for such behavior.'' (Andrew
Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- KOSOVO-UNREST-2
-- French troops hold back a crowd of Serbs trying to attack German
soldiers as they moved into northern Mitrovica on Sunday to search
for weapons. The search -which turned up 14 rifles, a machine-gun,
seven blocks of plastic explosive and ammunition - was a bid to
halt a spiral of violence that has been building since Feb. 2, when
two Serbs died in a rocket attack on a U.N. bus. (Andrew Testa/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- KOSOVO-UNREST-1
-- Serbs in northern Mitrovica on Sunday throwing snowballs,
stones, rocks and bottles at departing U.S. peacekeeping troops who
entered the city to search for weapons. ``We either had to withdraw
or shoot somebody,'' a U.S. soldier says. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-TALKS -- David
Boies, chief trial lawyer for the Justice Department, is one of the
major players in the Microsoft antitrust case in Washington. The
stakes are high for both sides in what one person close to the
talks called ``the ultimate antitrust poker game.'' Walking away
from the settlement talks, under way since November, could well
mean waiting a couple of years for a final outcome in the courts,
including appeals. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Feb. 20, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN
-- John Redinger of Webcor uses a Palm Pilot to check a schedule at
a Santa Clara job site. Webcor's on-site superintendents, like
Redinger, can get access to the most up-to-date specifications for
a construction project on the Web. (Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
