<HEADER>
A3194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-LEDE-TEX     02-20 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT SOLVES DAYTONA FOR A THIRD TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Honestly, Dale Jarrett said, he did not
know what to expect from his hastily repaired Ford stock car in the
season-opening Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   No, Jarrett said, he did not lie to trusted friend Mark Martin
about their deal in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   And truth be told, Jarrett said, he could have handled watching
journeyman Johnny Benson Jr. win the so-called Super Bowl of the
2000 NASCAR Winston Cup season Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The range of emotions in about a 24-hour period has been
pretty incredible,'' said Jarrett, summing up the storyline of a
Daytona 500 victory that read like pulp fiction. ``This is like, if
you're going to write a script, this is the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assured by crew chief Todd Parrott that the pole-winning car
dinged up during Saturday's final Happy Hour practice had been made
aerodynamically and mechanically snug Sunday morning, Jarrett began
defense of his Cup championship with two late-race passes worthy of
Daytona 500 legend Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Running third to upstart-leader Benson and Martin on Lap 186 of
the scheduled 200, Jarrett shot under the latter and into second
place in Turn 2 of the high-banked, 2.5-mile trioval. With Benson
bearing down on an improbable victory, Jarrett caught a break when
Michael Waltrip triggered an accident on the frontstretch that
swept up seven cars and brought out the day's fifth yellow flag.
</P>
<P>
   When the race restarted on Lap 197, Jarrett faked a pass high on
Benson through Turn 2 and then cut back down the track and into the
lead with a push in the draft from Jeff Burton. Their battle for
the checkered flag became moot when Jimmy Spencer hit the outside
wall exiting Turn 4 on Lap 198, setting up a white flag/yellow flag
finish and Jarrett's third Daytona 500 victory since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible victory because it was a total team
effort,'' said Jarrett, referring to the overtime logged by
approximately 20 crewmen from Robert Yates Racing late Saturday
night and early Sunday. Jarrett was in the final minutes of
practice Saturday afternoon when he got tapped from behind by 1999
Daytona 500 champion Jeff Gordon in a chain-reaction accident.
Jarrett made a great save at speed, but the car suffered
considerable damage to its front and rear aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott had three fabricators flown from Charlotte, N.C., to the
racetrack Saturday night to begin NASCAR-approved repairs. The crew
put on a new left front fender, repaired the nose and right front
fender, hood and tailpipes. Parrott estimated that 35 to 40 percent
of the aero panels on the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit
Taurus had been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Yates Racing, there's something about it when you say
Daytona 500,'' said Parrott, who debuted as Jarrett's crew chief
with a victory in the 1996 Daytona 500. ``It's just how bad we want
to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett proved to the 43-car field, and the 190,000 spectators,
that the car that had dominated Speed Weeks was still a rocket by
leading 29 laps early and another 56 circuits before halfway.
Martin, the star of Roush Racing's five-car stable, later led 65
laps before Benson, making his debut for carowner Tim Beverley of
Tyler, used a two-tire pit stop to grab the lead on Lap 158.
Benson, driver of the No. 10 Lycos Pontiac Grand Prix, was leading
a breakaway pack of six cars when runner-up Martin and third-place
Jarrett conspired to push their Fords to the front. Only Martin
said Jarrett reneged on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lied to. I just asked to have a chance, and today we had
a chance,'' said Martin, who finished fifth in the No. 6 Valvoline
Ford. ``I did get lied to, but it was a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jarrett: ``Mark had radioed and asked if he went high would
I go with him, and I said yes. We tried it the lap before that and
didn't get a very good run on Benson. Nothing else was said then.
We came down through the trioval the next time, went into (Turn) 1,
Mark went high, I went into the corner high ... with every
intention of going with Mark. I look in my mirror, and the 99 car
(of Martin teammate Burton) dove to the bottom of the racetrack.
I've gotta protect my position at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lie to Mark Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Jarrett and Burton, Bill Elliott and Rusty
Wallace also freight-trained past Martin and set their sights on
Benson. Waltrip's second wreck in as many days at Daytona then
brought out the yellow that group needed to reel Benson in.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the restart, I knew that was going to be my best
opportunity,'' Jarrett said. ``I faked high and he went up there,
and as soon as I saw him move up the racetrack, I cut dead left.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's crash assured the outcome, and allowed Jarrett to
become only the fourth driver to win three or more Daytona 500s. A
second generation champion, Jarrett joined Petty (seven), Cale
Yarborough (four) and Bobby Allison (three) among Daytona 500
elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing today was Richard Petty came out, made his way
across pit road, and shook my hand,'' said Jarrett, who scored his
23rd career Cup victory. ``That sent chills up my spine. That says
how special it is to get those three.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
